ological Information for Poltava, Ukraine\n| publisher = Hong Kong Observatory\n| accessdate = 4 September 2012}}</ref>\n| date     = April 2012\n}}\n{{Clear}}\n[[File:October Parc Poltava 1550.JPG|thumb|left|200px|The Column of Glory commemorates the centenary of the [[Battle of Poltava]] (1709).]]\n[[File:\u0425\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0456 1909.jpg|thumb|right|The 200th Anniversary celebrations of the Battle of Poltava in June 1909]]\n\n==Government and subdivisions==\n[[File:\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0430. \u0411\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a \u0433\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0435\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 1.jpg|thumb|Building of the regional administration (by [[Vasyl Krychevsky]])]]\n[[File:\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0434\u0443\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0430\u0440\u0456\u044f.jpg|thumb|Theological seminary, which during [[World War I]] was converted into a military school quartering the Vilno Cadet School]]\nPoltava is the [[Capital (political)|administrative center]] of the [[Poltava Oblast]] ([[Oblast|province]]) as well as of the Poltava Raion housed within the city. However, Poltava is a [[Administrative divisions of Ukraine|city of oblast subordinance]], thus being subject directly to the oblast authorities rather to the raion administration housed in the city itself.\n\nPoltava's government consists of the 50-member Poltava City Council ({{lang-uk|\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430}}) which is headed by the Secretary (currently Oleksandr Kozub). The city's current mayor is Oleksandr Mamay, who was sworn in on 4 November 2010 after being elected with more than 61 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.dt.ua/articles/68558|title=Oleksandr Mamay won at the elections for the mayor of Poltava|accessdate=14 May 2011|date=6 November 2010|publisher=Dzerkalo Tyzhnya|language=Ukrainian}}</ref> In 2015 he was re-elected as a candidate of [[Conscience of Ukraine]] with 62.9% in a second round of Mayoral election.<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/304206.html Mamai reelected as Poltava mayor \u2013 election commission], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (16 November 2015)</ref>\n\nThe territory of Poltava is divided into 3 administrative [[raion]]s (districts):<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gska2.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/A006RM?rdat1=05.01.2009&rf7571=27018|title=Poltavska Oblast, city of Poltava (raion councils of the cities)|accessdate=4 January 2009|publisher=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]]|language=Ukrainian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521222037/http://gska2.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/A006RM?rdat1=05.01.2009&rf7571=27018|archivedate=21 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n# Shevchenkivsky Raion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.okt-rada.poltava.ua/|title=Official resource.|accessdate=3 January 2009|year=2008|publisher=Oktiabrskyi Raion Council of Poltava|language=Ukrainian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202175339/http://okt-rada.poltava.ua/|archivedate=2 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rada-poltava.gov.ua/districts/oktyabrsky/|title=Information of the Oktiabrskyi Raion of Poltava|accessdate=3 January 2009|year=2007|publisher=Poltava City Council|language=Ukrainian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405183341/http://www.rada-poltava.gov.ua/districts/oktyabrsky/|archivedate=5 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> to the south-west with an area of 2077 hectares and a population of 147,600 in 2005. It's a largely residential area and includes the city centre.\n# Kyivsky Raion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rada-poltava.gov.ua/districts/kyivsky/|title=Information of the Kyivskyi Raion of Poltava|accessdate=3 January 2009|year=2007|publisher=Poltava City Council|language=Ukrainian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405221918/http://www.rada-poltava.gov.ua/districts/kyivsky/|archivedate=5 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is the largest by area, comprising 5437 hectares, or 52.8% of the city total situated in the north and north-west. Its census in 2005 was 111,900. This district has a large industrial zone.\n# Podilsky Raion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rada-poltava.gov.ua/districts/leninsky/|title=Information of the Leninskyi Raion of Poltava|accessdate=3 January 2009|year=2007|publisher=Poltava City Council|language=Ukrainian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405221927/http://www.rada-poltava.gov.ua/districts/leninsky/|archivedate=5 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> to the east and south-east, in the valley of the Vorskla river, with an area of 2988 hectares and a population of 53,700 in 2005.\n\nThe village of [[Rozsoshentsi]], [[Scherbani]], [[Tereshky]], [[Kopyly]] and [[Suprunivka]] are officially considered to be outside the city, but actually constitute a part of the Poltava agglomeration.\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Poltava 1850 Main Square.PNG|thumb|275px|Alexander Square in 1850]]\n\nThe centre of the old city is a semicircular Neoclassical square with the [[Tuscan column]] of cast iron (1805\u201311), commemorating the centenary of the [[Battle of Poltava]] and featuring 18 Swedish cannons captured in that battle. As [[Peter I of Russia|Peter the Great]] celebrated his victory in the Saviour church, this 17th-century wooden shrine was carefully preserved to this day. The five-domed city cathedral, dedicated to the [[Exaltation of the Cross]], is a superb monument of [[Cossack Baroque]], built between 1699 and 1709. As a whole, the cathedral presents a unity which even the Neoclassical belltower has failed to mar. Another frothy Baroque church, dedicated to the Dormition of the Theotokos, was destroyed in 1934 and rebuilt in the 1990s.\n\nA [[minor planet]] [[2983 Poltava]] discovered in 1981 by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] astronomer [[Nikolai Stepanovich Chernykh]] is named after the city.<ref>{{cite book | last = Schmadel | first = Lutz D. | title = Dictionary of Minor Planet Names | pages = 246 | edition = 5th  | year = 2003 | publisher=Springer Verlag | location = New York | url = https://books.google.com/books?q=2983+Poltava+RW2 | isbn = 3-540-00238-3}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n\nThe most popular sport is [[Association football|football (soccer)]]. Two professional football (soccer) teams are based in the city: [[Vorskla Poltava]] in the [[Ukrainian Premier League]] and [[FC Poltava]] in the [[Ukrainian Second League|Second League]].\nThere are 3 stadiums in Poltava: [[Butovsky Vorskla Stadium]] (main city stadium), [[Dynamo Stadium (Poltava)|Dynamo Stadium]] are situated in the city centre and [[Lokomotiv Stadium (Poltava)|Lokomotiv Stadium]] which is situated in Podil district. In 2009, we went to the local capital of professional volleyball clubs Poltavchanka, where I can visit Ukraine.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Marie Bashkirtseff]] \u2013 19th-century Parisian painter, memoirist\n* [[Yitzhak Ben-Zvi]] \u2013 a historian, [[Labor Zionism|Labour Zionist]] leader, and the second and longest serving Israeli president\n* [[Hanka Bielicka]] \u2013 Polish actress\n* [[Oleksandr Bilash]] \u2013 Ukrainian composer\n* [[Verka Serduchka|Andriy Danylko]] \u2013 Ukrainian singer\n* [[Sonia Delaunay]] \u2013 Ukrainian-born French artist, a cofounder of the Orphism art movement, noted for its use of strong colors and geometric shapes\n* [[Nikolai Gogol]] \u2013 writer and playwright\n* [[Alexander Gurwitsch]] \u2013 [[Russia]]n physician and biologist\n* [[Dmitri Kessel]] \u2013 photojournalist, [[Life (magazine)|Life magazine]] war correspondent 1944\u20131972\n* [[Vera Kholodnaya]] \u2013 Ukrainian actress, the first star of Russian silent cinema\n* [[Yuri Kondratyuk]] (born Olexandr Gnatovich Shargei) \u2013 astronautics and spaceflight pioneer who, in the early 20th century, foresaw ways of reaching the moon\n* [[Ivan Kotlyarevsky]] \u2013 Ukrainian writer, poet, and playwright\n* [[Anatoliy Vasilievich Lunacharsky]] \u2013 Russian [[Marxist]] revolutionary and the first [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[People's Commissar]] of Enlightenment responsible for culture and education\n* [[Mykola Lysenko]] \u2013 Composer, founder of first Ukrainian classical music school\n* [[Mstyslav (Skrypnyk)|Mstyslav]] - Ukrainian Orthodox Church hierarch\n* [[Panas Myrny]] (born Panas Yakovych Rudchenko) \u2013 Ukrainian writer ([http://poltavahistory.org.ua/hisp_e_117.htm#met112 Panas Myrny's Memorial estate])\n* [[Mikhail Vasilievich Ostrogradsky]] \u2013 Ukrainian mathematician, mechanician, and physicist\n* [[Olena Pchilka]] \u2013 Pen name for Olha Petrivna Kosach, mother of [[Lesya Ukrainka]], famous writer, sister of [[Mykhailo Drahomanov]]\n* [[Ivan Paskevich]] \u2013 Ukrainian military leader in the Russian service\n* [[Symon Petliura]] \u2013  Ukrainian politician and statesman, a leader of Ukraine's fight for independence following the Russian Revolution of 1917\n* [[Zhanna Prokhorenko]] \u2013 Ukrainian actress\n* [[Sasha Putrya]] \u2013 Ukrainian artist\n* [[Moshe Zvi Segal (Rabbi)|Moshe Zvi Segal]] \u2013 a prominent figure in various movements and organizations in Israel, including [[Irgun|Etzel]] and [[Lechi]].\n* [[Avraham Shlonsky]] \u2013 Israeli poet and editor\n* [[Hryhorii Skovoroda]] \u2013 Ukrainian poet, philosopher, and composer\n* [[Maria Tarnowska]] (born Maria Nikolaevna O'Rourke) \u2013 famous [[femme fatale]], whose trial for murder ([[Venice]], 1910) attracted worldwide media attention\n* [[Paisius Velichkovsky]] \u2013 [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] [[monk]] and theologian noted for promoting [[starets]]dom\n* [[Nikolai Yaroshenko]] \u2013 Ukrainian painter\n* [[Mikhail Zoshchenko]] \u2013 [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] satirist\n\n== Economy and infrastructure ==\n\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Poltava train station.jpg|thumb|275px|The Kyivskyi Vokzal, the city's main railway station.]]\n\nPoltava's transportation infrastructure consists of two major train stations with railway links to [[Kiev]], [[Kharkiv]], and [[Kremenchuk]]. Poltava's Kiev line is electrified and is used by the Poltava Express. The electrification of the Poltava-Kharkiv line was completed in August 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poltava-Kharkiv rail line|url=http://gortransport.kharkov.ua/news/news.php?news_id=7022|accessdate=21 September 2008|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\nThe Avtovokzal serves as the city's intercity bus station. Buses for local municipal routes depart from \"AC-2\" (autostation No. 2 \u2013 along [[Taras Shevchenko|Shevchenko]] street) and \"AC-3\" (Zinkivska street). Local municipal routes are parked along the [[Taras Shevchenko]] Street. [[Marshrutka]] minibuses serve areas where regular bus access is unavailable; however, they are privately owned and cost more per ride. In addition, a 10-route [[trolleybus]] network of {{convert|72.6|km|mi}} runs throughout the city. On the routes of the city go more than 50 units of trolleybuses.\n\nPoltava is also served by a International Airport, situated outside the city limits near the village of Ivashky. The international highway [[International Highways (Ukraine)|M03]], linking Poltava with Kiev and Kharkiv, passes through the southern outskirts of the city. There is also a regional highway P-17 crossing Poltava and linking it with Kremenchuk and [[Sumy]].<ref>Poltava \u2013 Plan. Kiev Army-Cartographic Fabric.</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\nPoltava has always been one of the most important science and education centres in Ukraine. Major universities and institutions of higher education include the following:\n* [http://pnpu.edu.ua/en/ Poltava National Pedagogical University] named after [[Vladimir Korolenko|V. G. Korolenko]]\n* [http://pntu.edu.ua/index.php/en/ Poltava National Technical Yuri Kondratyuk University ]\n* [http://pdaa.edu.ua/ Poltava Agrarian State Academy]\n* [[Ukrainian Medical Stomatological Academy as Poltava Medical And Dental University]] (UMSA)\n* [[Poltava University of Economics and Trade]]\n* [[:uk:\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439_\u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439_\u0456\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442_\u0437\u0432%27\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0443|Poltava Military Institute of Connections]]\n* Poltavian Faculty of National Juridical Academy of Ukraine\n*[[:uk:\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430_\u0444\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f_\u0414\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457_\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0456\u0457_\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438,_\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0443_\u0442\u0430_\u0430\u0443\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0443_\u0414\u0435\u0440\u0436\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443_\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|Poltava branch of the State Academy of Statistics, region and audit to the State Statistics Committee of Ukraine]]\n\n'''Astronomy'''\n* Poltava gravimetric observatory (PGO) is situated a bit north from city centre (27\u201329 Miasoyedov St.). Its main work directions are measurements of Earth rotation, latitude variations (applying zenith stars observations, lunar occultation observations and other)\n* Observational station of PGO in rural area, some 20&nbsp;km east along the M03-E40 highway. Radiotelescope URAN-2 (Ukrainian: ''\u0423\u0420\u0410\u041d-2'') is situated there too.\n\n==International relations==\n{{see also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Ukraine}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 sister cities===\nPoltava is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n* {{flagicon|BUL}} [[Veliko Tarnovo]], [[Bulgaria]] (1963)\n* {{flagicon|GER}} [[Filderstadt]], [[Germany]]\n* {{flagicon|GER}} [[Ostfildern]], [[Germany]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Irondequoit]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n* {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Kristianstad ]], [[Sweden]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Poltava Dvoryanske zibrannya.JPG|Building of the Noble Assembly\nFile:Poltava City Hall.JPG|State administrative building (Russian Empire)\nFile:Poltava Hospital.JPG|Former military hospital\nFile:Poltava Choral Synagogue (Poltava Oblast Philharmonic).JPG|Former choral synagogue (today - Regional Philharmonic Society)\nFile:\"\u0413\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0434\u044a \u041e\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\" \u043a\u0443\u043f\u0446\u044f \u0406. \u0413\u0456\u043d\u0441\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430.JPG|Merchant Ginzburg's \"Grand Hotel\"\nFile:Poltava Ivan Kotlyarevsky Obelisk.JPG|Obelisk at the [[Ivan Kotlyarevsky]]'s burial\nFile:Poltava Mansion of Bahmackiy.JPG|[[Moorish architecture|Moorish-styled]] mansion of Bakhmatsky\nFile:Poltava Monastery 03.jpg|Exaltation of the Cross nunnery\nFile:Poltava Well (Memorial - Estate writer I.P.Kotlyarevsky).JPG|Traditional Ukrainian well, ''krynytsia'' (Kotlyarevsky's estate)\nFile:Poltava Zemstvo SAM 0439 53-101-0523.JPG|Former Regional Administration building\nFile:\u0406\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c.jpg|Former Institute of Noble Maidens (today - National Technical University)\nFile:\u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0430 1345 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0457\u043d\u0456\u0432 (\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0435 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0457 \u0431\u0438\u0442\u0432\u0438),.jpg|Mass burial of 1345 Russian soldiers (perished at the [[Battle of Poltava]])\nFile:Poltava2.jpg|Main pedestrian street of Poltava\nFile:Poltava7.jpg|[[Security Service of Ukraine|State security]] office\nFile:PoltavaStreet.jpg|A busy street in central Poltava\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Poltava}}\n{{wikivoyage|Poltava}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.rada-poltava.gov.ua/|title=Official website|publisher=Poltava City Council|language=Ukrainian}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.adm-pl.gov.ua/|title=News|publisher=Poltava Oblast State Administration|language=Ukrainian}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://poltavahistory.inf.ua/|title=Poltava Istoricheskaya5|publisher=poltavahistory.inf.ua|language=Russian}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://transport.poltava.ua/|title=Main|publisher=Transport of Poltava (unofficial project)|language=Russian}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://ingvarr.net.ru/photo/220|title=Photos of Poltava |language=Russian}}\n* [http://www.yadvashem.org/untoldstories/database/index.asp?cid=515 The murder of the Jews of Poltava] during [[World War II]], at [[Yad Vashem]] website.\n\n{{Poltava Oblast}}\n{{Administrative divisions of Ukraine}}\n{{Cities in Ukraine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Poltava| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Poltava Oblast]]\n[[Category:Poltava Governorate]]\n[[Category:Kiev Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Cossack Hetmanate]]\n[[Category:Cities of regional significance in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Oblast centers in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 9th century]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTransportation:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: a International \u2192 an International", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poltava"}
{"title_page": "Perfect Witness", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Perfect Witness\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = Terry Curtis Fox<br>[[Ron Hutchinson (screenwriter)|Ron Hutchinson]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Robert Mandel]]\n| starring             = [[Brian Dennehy]]<br>[[Aidan Quinn]]<br>[[Stockard Channing]]<br>[[Laura Harrington]]<br>[[Delroy Lindo]]<br>[[Joe Grifasi]]\n| narrated             = \n| composer             = [[Brad Fiedel]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = Elaine Sperber \n| editor               = Wendy Greene Bricmont \n| cinematography       = [[Lajos Koltai]]\n| runtime              = 103 minutes\n| company              = Granger Productions<br>[[HBO Pictures]]\n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[HBO]]\n| first_aired          = {{Film date|TV=y|1989|10|28}}\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Perfect Witness''''' is a 1989 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[Robert Mandel]] and written by Terry Curtis Fox and [[Ron Hutchinson (screenwriter)|Ron Hutchinson]]. The film stars [[Brian Dennehy]], [[Aidan Quinn]], [[Stockard Channing]], [[Laura Harrington]], [[Delroy Lindo]] and [[Joe Grifasi]]. The film premiered on [[HBO]] on October 28, 1989.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alan Carter |url=http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-perfect-witness-vol-32-no-18/ |title=Picks and Pans Review: Perfect Witness |publisher=People.com |date=1989-10-30 |accessdate=2017-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/412639/Perfect-Witness/ |title=Perfect Witness (1989) - Overview |publisher=TCM.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hal Erickson |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/perfect-witness-v37726 |title=Perfect Witness (1989) - Robert Mandel |publisher=AllMovie |date=1989-10-28 |accessdate=2017-11-22}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA witness to a mob killing has second thoughts about testifying when he realizes his family might become a target.\n\n==Cast== \n*[[Brian Dennehy]] as James Falcon\n*[[Aidan Quinn]] as Sam Paxton\n*[[Stockard Channing]] as Liz Sapperstein\n*[[Laura Harrington]] as Jeanie Paxton\n*[[Delroy Lindo]] as Berger\n*[[Joe Grifasi]] as Breeze\n*[[Ken Pogue]] as Costello\n*[[Markus Flanagan]] as Woods\n*[[David Margulies]] as Rudnick\n*Nial Lancaster as Danny Paxton\n*James Greene as Paddy O'Rourke\n*[[Colm Meaney]] as Meagher\n*[[Tobin Bell]] as Dillon\n*[[Tony Sirico]] as Marco\n*Sam Malkin as Stefano\n*Kevin Rushton as Rikky\n*David Cumming as Kevin O'Rourke\n*[[David Proval]] as Lucca\n*Christopher Trace as Eddie Wallis\n*David Christopher Adamson as Newton \n*Jennifer Pearson as Jeanie's Sister\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0098080|Perfect Witness}}\n\n{{Robert Mandel}}\n\n[[Category:1989 television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s thriller films]]\n[[Category:HBO Films films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Mandel]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Brad Fiedel]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:Thriller television films]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Perfect Witness\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = Terry Curtis Fox<br>[[Ron Hutchinson (screenwriter)|Ron Hutchinson]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Robert Mandel]]\n| starring             = [[Brian Dennehy]]<br>[[Aidan Quinn]]<br>[[Stockard Channing]]<br>[[Laura Harrington]]<br>[[Delroy Lindo]]<br>[[Joe Grifasi]]\n| narrated             = \n| composer             = [[Brad Fiedel]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = Elaine Sperber \n| editor               = Wendy Greene Bricmont \n| cinematography       = [[Lajos Koltai]]\n| runtime              = 103 minutes\n| company              = Granger Productions<br>[[HBO Pictures]]\n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[HBO]]\n| first_aired          = {{Film date|TV=y|1989|10|28}}\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Perfect Witness''''' is a 1989 American [[thriller film]] directed by [[Robert Mandel]] and written by Terry Curtis Fox and [[Ron Hutchinson (screenwriter)|Ron Hutchinson]]. The film stars [[Brian Dennehy]], [[Aidan Quinn]], [[Stockard Channing]], [[Laura Harrington]], [[Delroy Lindo]] and [[Joe Grifasi]]. The film premiered on [[HBO]] on October 28, 1989.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alan Carter |url=http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-perfect-witness-vol-32-no-18/ |title=Picks and Pans Review: Perfect Witness |publisher=People.com |date=1989-10-30 |accessdate=2017-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/412639/Perfect-Witness/ |title=Perfect Witness (1989) - Overview |publisher=TCM.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hal Erickson |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/perfect-witness-v37726 |title=Perfect Witness (1989) - Robert Mandel |publisher=AllMovie |date=1989-10-28 |accessdate=2017-11-22}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA witness to a mob killing has second thoughts about testifying when he realizes his family might become a target.\n\n==Cast== \n*[[Brian Dennehy]] as James Falcon\n*[[Aidan Quinn]] as Sam Paxton\n*[[Stockard Channing]] as Liz Sapperstein\n*[[Laura Harrington]] as Jeanie Paxton\n*[[Delroy Lindo]] as Berger\n*[[Joe Grifasi]] as Breeze\n*[[Ken Pogue]] as Costello\n*[[Markus Flanagan]] as Woods\n*[[David Margulies]] as Rudnick\n*Nial Lancaster as Danny Paxton\n*James Greene as Paddy O'Rourke\n*[[Colm Meaney]] as Meagher\n*[[Tobin Bell]] as Dillon\n*[[Tony Sirico]] as Marco\n*Sam Malkin as Stefano\n*Kevin Rushton as Rikky\n*David Cumming as Kevin O'Rourke\n*[[David Proval]] as Lucca\n*Christopher Trace as Eddie Wallis\n*David Christopher Adamson as Newton \n*Jennifer Pearson as Jeanie's Sister\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0098080|Perfect Witness}}\n\n{{Robert Mandel}}\n\n[[Category:1989 television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s thriller films]]\n[[Category:HBO Films films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Mandel]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Brad Fiedel]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:Thriller television films]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_Witness"}
{"title_page": "Norman Beasley", "text_new": "{{short description|American journalist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Norman Beasley\n| birth_date  = April 6, 1887\n| birth_place = [[Michigan]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1963|07|02|1887|04|06}}\n| death_place = New York<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/07/04/archives/norman-beasley-author-76-dies-former-newsman-wrote-several.html |title=NORMAN BEASLEY, AUTHOR, 76, DIES; Former Newsman Wrote Several Biographies}}</ref>\n| nationality = American\n| occupation  = Journalist, author\n}}\n\n'''Norman Beasley''' (April 6, 1887 \u2013 July 2, 1963)<ref name=\"City of Detroit\">{{cite web |title=The City of Detroit, Michigan, 1701\u20131922, Volume 4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Y4mAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA879&lpg=PA879&dq=%22norman+beasley%22+detroit&source=bl&ots=tCJl4upd6W&sig=ACfU3U1BORadhIv3nxkEq1Ro-4edha_7_w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjpnu7ruebmAhUIV80KHakMDyoQ6AEwEnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22norman%20beasley%22%20detroit&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"basic info\">{{cite web |title=librarything.com Norman Beasley profile |url=https://www.librarything.com/author/beasleynorman}}</ref> was an American journalist and author, best known for writing biographies. He also served in the [[United States Army]] as a Colonel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arlington National Cemetery |url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/norman-beasley.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nNorman Beasley was born in Detroit, Michigan, where his parents had moved just before his birth.<ref name=\"City of Detroit\"/>\n\nBeasley's writing career began after graduating from Detroit College of Law, working as a journalist for The [[Detroit Journal]], and later for The Dearborn News.<ref name=\"basic info\"/> The same year he joined the Detroit Journal, he also had his first and only child, named Norman Baird. Norman Beasley was a member of the Presbyterian church.<ref name=\"City of Detroit\"/>\n\nHe began writing books on history in the late 1920's, publishing ''Men, money, and motors: the drama of the automobile'' through Harper & Brothers in 1929. His biographical works would include books on [[William S. Knudsen]], [[Frank Knox]], [[Mary Baker Eddy]], and [[Carter Glass]], which was co-written with Rixey Smith.\n\n==Works==\n\nBeasley's book on [[William S. Knudsen|William Knudsen]], a leading automotive industry executive and general during World War II, is the only book-length work focused solely him and covering his entire life,<ref name=\"Knudsen\">{{cite web |title=William S. Knudsen Facts |url=https://biography.yourdictionary.com/william-s-knudsen}}</ref> and contains an introduction by Knudsen himself. However, other books exist focusing on Knudsen's work at [[Ford Motor Company]]. The book was authorized by the Knudsen family shortly before Knudsen's death. It was reprinted in 2011 by Literary Licensing, LLC.\n\nBeasley's writings on [[The First Church of Christ, Scientist]] are notable for two reasons. First, they are among a handful of books on the subject neither written by a member of the church nor by someone attacking the church, but, as one review puts it, \"dispassionately\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kirkus Review |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/norman-beasley-3/age-is-an-imposter/}}</ref> from a historical perspective. Secondly, the historical accounts do not end where most historical accounts end in 1910 with the passing of founder Mary Baker Eddy, but continue into the 1950's and cover the growth of the church doing that period. He wrote three books covering the topic, they are not authorized church literature sold in the church's [[Christian Science Reading Room|Reading Rooms]] however.\n\n==Published works==\n\n* ''Men, money, and motors: the drama of the automobile'' (New York: Harper & Brothers, 1929)\n* ''Freighters of fortune; the story of the Great Lakes'' (New York, Harper & Brothers, 1930)\n* ''Men working; a story of the Goodyear tire & rubber co.'' (New York and London: Harper & brothers, 1931)\n* ''Frank Knox, American; a short biography'' (Garden City, N.Y: Doubleday, Doran & Company, inc., 1936)\n* ''Texas, the Lone star state'' (Garden City, N. Y.: Doubleday, Doran & company, inc., 1936)\n* ''Michigan, the Wolverine state'' (Garden City, N.Y.: Doubleday, Doran and company, inc., 1936)\n* ''Carter Glass; a biography'' with Rixey Smith (New York: Longmans, Green and co., 1939)\n* ''Knudsen: a Biography'' (New York: Whittlesey House, 1947), {{ISBN|978-1-934044-01-8}}\n* ''Main Street merchant; the story of the J.C. Penney Company'' (New York: Whittlesey House, 1948)\n* ''Politics has no morals'' (New York: Scribner, 1949)\n* ''The cross and the crown'' (New York: Duell, Sloan and Pearce, 1952)\n* ''The continuing spirit'' (London: Allen & Unwin, 1957)\n* ''Made in Detroit'' (New York: Putnam, 1957)\n* ''For the years to come; a story of International Nickel of Canada'' with John F. Thompson (New York: Putnam, 1960)\n* ''Mary Baker Eddy'' (New York: Duell, Sloan, and Pearce, 1963)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beasley, Norman}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American journalist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Norman Beasley\n| birth_date  = April 6, 1887\n| birth_place = [[Michigan]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1963|07|02|1887|04|06}}\n| death_place = New York<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1963/07/04/archives/norman-beasley-author-76-dies-former-newsman-wrote-several.html |title=NORMAN BEASLEY, AUTHOR, 76, DIES; Former Newsman Wrote Several Biographies}}</ref>\n| nationality = American\n| occupation  = Journalist, author\n}}\n\n'''Norman Beasley''' (April 6, 1887 \u2013 July 2, 1963)<ref name=\"City of Detroit\">{{cite web |title=The City of Detroit, Michigan, 1701\u20131922, Volume 4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Y4mAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA879&lpg=PA879&dq=%22norman+beasley%22+detroit&source=bl&ots=tCJl4upd6W&sig=ACfU3U1BORadhIv3nxkEq1Ro-4edha_7_w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjpnu7ruebmAhUIV80KHakMDyoQ6AEwEnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22norman%20beasley%22%20detroit&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"basic info\">{{cite web |title=librarything.com Norman Beasley profile |url=https://www.librarything.com/author/beasleynorman}}</ref> was an American journalist and author, best known for writing biographies. He also served in the [[United States Army]] as a Colonel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arlington National Cemetery |url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/norman-beasley.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nNorman Beasley was born in Detroit, Michigan, where his parents had moved just before his birth.<ref name=\"City of Detroit\"/>\n\nBeasley's writing career began after graduating from Detroit College of Law, working as a journalist for The [[Detroit Journal]], and later for The Dearborn News.<ref name=\"basic info\"/> The same year he joined the Detroit Journal, he also had his first and only child, named Norman Baird. Norman Beasley was a member of the Presbyterian church.<ref name=\"City of Detroit\"/>\n\nHe began writing books on history in the late 1920's, publishing ''Men, money, and motors: the drama of the automobile'' through Harper & Brothers in 1929. His biographical works would include books on [[William S. Knudsen]], [[Frank Knox]], [[Mary Baker Eddy]], and [[Carter Glass]], which was co-written with Rixey Smith.\n\n==Works==\n\nBeasley's book on [[William S. Knudsen|William Knudsen]], a leading automotive industry executive and general during World War II, is the only book-length work focused solely him and covering his entire life,<ref name=\"Knudsen\">{{cite web |title=William S. Knudsen Facts |url=https://biography.yourdictionary.com/william-s-knudsen}}</ref> and contains an introduction by Knudsen himself. However, other books exist focusing on Knudsen's work at [[Ford Motor Company]]. The book was authorized by the Knudsen family shortly before Knudsen's death. It was reprinted in 2011 by Literary Licensing, LLC. \n\nBeasley's writings on [[The First Church of Christ, Scientist]] are notable for two reasons. First, they are among a handful of books on the subject neither written by a member of the church nor by someone attacking the church, but, as one review puts it, \"dispassionately\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kirkus Review |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/norman-beasley-3/age-is-an-imposter/}}</ref> from a historical perspective. Secondly, the historical accounts do not end where most historical accounts end in 1910 with the passing of founder Mary Baker Eddy, but continue into the 1950's and cover the growth of the church doing that period. He wrote three books covering the topic, they are not authorized church literature sold in the church's [[Christian Science Reading Room|Reading Rooms]] however.\n\n==Published works==\n\n* ''Men, money, and motors: the drama of the automobile'' (New York: Harper & Brothers, 1929)\n* ''Freighters of fortune; the story of the Great Lakes'' (New York, Harper & Brothers, 1930)\n* ''Men working; a story of the Goodyear tire & rubber co.'' (New York and London: Harper & brothers, 1931)\n* ''Frank Knox, American; a short biography'' (Garden City, N.Y: Doubleday, Doran & Company, inc., 1936)\n* ''Texas, the Lone star state'' (Garden City, N. Y.: Doubleday, Doran & company, inc., 1936)\n* ''Michigan, the Wolverine state'' (Garden City, N.Y.: Doubleday, Doran and company, inc., 1936)\n* ''Carter Glass; a biography'' with Rixey Smith (New York: Longmans, Green and co., 1939)\n* ''Knudsen: a Biography'' (New York: Whittlesey House, 1947), {{ISBN|978-1-934044-01-8}}\n* ''Main Street merchant; the story of the J.C. Penney Company'' (New York: Whittlesey House, 1948)\n* ''Politics has no morals'' (New York: Scribner, 1949)\n* ''The cross and the crown'' (New York: Duell, Sloan and Pearce, 1952)\n* ''The continuing spirit'' (London: Allen & Unwin, 1957)\n* ''Made in Detroit'' (New York: Putnam, 1957)\n* ''For the years to come; a story of International Nickel of Canada'' with John F. Thompson (New York: Putnam, 1960)\n* ''Mary Baker Eddy'' (New York: Duell, Sloan, and Pearce, 1963)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beasley, Norman}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norman_Beasley"}
{"title_page": "IBM PCjr", "text_new": "{{Short description|Home computer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox information appliance\n| name = IBM PCjr\n| logo = \n| image = Ibm pcjr with display.jpg\n| caption = IBM PCjr with original \"chiclet\" keyboard, PCjr color display, and 64&nbsp;KB memory expansion card\n| developer = \n| manufacturer = [[Teledyne Technologies|Teledyne]], [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]]\n| carrier = \n| family = \n| type = [[Personal computer]]\n| generation = \n| releasedate = {{Start date and100 age|1984|03}}\n| lifespan = \n| price = US$1,269 with 128&nbsp;KB memory and without monitor<!-- this is price at initial release, not the current price.--> (today US$3128.45)<br/> {{nowrap|[[British pound|GBP]]\u00a3800}} {{nowrap|(today \u00a3{{Inflation|GBP|800|1984|r=2}})}} w/o disk drive.<br/>{{nowrap|[[Canadian dollar|CAD]]$1900.00}}\n| discontinued = March 1985\n| unitssold = \n| unitsshipped = 500,000\n| media = \n| os = IBM [[PC DOS]] 2.10<!-- operating system -->\n| power = \n| cpu = [[Intel 8088]] @ 4.77 MHz\n| storage = \n| memory = 64 [[Kilobyte|KB]]\n| display = \n| graphics = [[Video Gate Array]]\n| sound = [[Texas Instruments]] [[SN76489]]\n| input = \n| location = <!-- GPS or Wi-Fi based -->\n| controllers = \n| output = \n| camera = \n| touchpad = \n| connectivity = \n| service = <!-- online service/s offered -->\n| dimensions = \n| weight = \n| topgame = \n| compatibility = \n| predecessor = [[IBM Personal Computer]]\n| successor = [[IBM PS/1]]\n| related = \n| website = \n}}\nThe '''IBM PCjr''' (read \"PC junior\") is a [[home computer]] that was produced and marketed by IBM from March 1984 to May 1985. The PCjr was positioned as a complement to the very successful [[IBM Personal Computer]] (PC), competing with other [[home computer]]s such as the [[Apple II series]] and the [[Commodore 64]]. It retains the IBM PC's [[Intel 8088|8088]] [[CPU]] and [[BIOS]] interface, but provides enhanced graphics and sound capabilities over the original IBM PC, [[ROM cartridge]] slots, joystick ports, and an infrared wireless keyboard. The PCjr supports expansion via \"sidecar\" modules, which are attached to the side of the unit. New software such as ''[[King's Quest I]]'' showcased its [[PC gaming]] capabilities.\n\nDespite widespread anticipation, the PCjr's launch was unsuccessful. IBM's inexperience with the consumer market led to unclear positioning, with analysts believing that IBM was unsuccessful at justifying the PCjr's higher cost in comparison to competitors such as the Commodore 64 and Apple II. It is only partially [[IBM PC compatible|IBM compatible]], so compatibility with existing PC software such as the [[killer app]] [[Lotus 1-2-3]] was not guaranteed. The PCjr's [[chiclet keyboard]] was widely criticized for its poor quality, with critics stating that it was unsuitable for extended use such as word processing. The PCjr's expandability is limited, and it was initially offered with up to 128&nbsp;KB of RAM only, insufficient for many IBM PC programs.\n\nIn 1984, IBM offered free replacement keyboards with a more traditional design, and a new 512&nbsp;KB RAM upgrade. A large advertising campaign promoted the PCjr's compatibility with \"over 1000\" of the most popular IBM PC applications (including a new [[porting|port]] of Lotus 1-2-3), and new discounted pricing and other bundle offers. PCjr sales greatly increased, amazing observers that saw it as a failure.\n\nBy January 1985, when the discounts ended, IBM had sold 250,000 PCjr computers, with 200,000 in the fourth quarter of 1984 alone. Unable to sell the computer without discounts, IBM abruptly discontinued the PCjr in March 1985 and would not produce a home-oriented computer until the [[IBM PS/1|PS/1]] in 1990. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' described the PCjr as \"one of the biggest flops in the history of computing\", with critics comparing it to the [[Edsel|Ford Edsel]] and [[New Coke]]. Inexpensive and almost entirely compatible [[PC clone]]s became popular in 1985 including the [[Tandy 1000]]. The Tandy was much more successful than the PCjr it imitated, and PCjr's enhanced graphics and sound standards became known as \"[[Tandy Graphics Adapter|Tandy-compatible]]\".\n\n==Description==\n\n===Overview===\nAnnounced November 1, 1983, and first shipped in late January 1984,<ref name=\"sanger19840517\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/05/17/business/ibm-s-problems-with-junior.html?pagewanted=all | title=I.B.M.'s Problems with Junior | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Sanger, David E. | date=May 17, 1984 | newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> the PCjr&mdash;nicknamed \"Peanut\" before its debut<ref name=\"time19840402\" />&mdash;came in two models: the '''4860-004''', with 64&nbsp;[[kilobyte|KB]] of memory, priced at US$669 ({{Inflation|US|669|1983|fmt=eq}}); and the '''4860-067''', with 128&nbsp;KB of memory and a 360&nbsp;KB 5.25-inch floppy disk drive, priced at US$1,269 ({{Inflation|US|1269|1983|fmt=eq}}). It was manufactured for IBM in [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]] by [[Teledyne Technologies|Teledyne]]. The PCjr promised a high degree of compatibility with the [[IBM PC]], which was already a popular business computer, in addition to offering built-in color graphics and 3 voice sound that was better than the standard [[PC speaker|PC-speaker]] sound and [[Color Graphics Adapter|color graphics]] of the standard IBM PC and compatibles of the day.  The PCjr was also the first PC compatible machine that was expressly designed to support [[page flipping]] for graphics operations. Since the PCjr uses system [[Random-access memory|RAM]] to store video content, and the location of this storage area can be changed, it can perform flicker-free animation and other effects that are difficult or impossible to produce on contemporary PC clones.\n\n====Video====\nUnlike the standard IBM PC, the PCjr has onboard video hardware. It is an improved subset of the [[Color/Graphics Adapter|CGA]] standard. The four CGA video modes (40x25 text, 80x25 text, 320x200x4, and 640x200x2 graphics) are supported in addition to three new graphics modes (160x200x16, 320x200x16, and 640x200x4). The 80x25 text mode, 320x200x16, and 640x200x4 modes are referred to in IBM's documentation as \"the high bandwidth modes\"; they are not supported on base models with only 64k of memory. The PCjr also has a composite video out and can support artifact colors on a TV or composite monitor much like the CGA cards, although the colors are slightly different. The PCjr also has palette registers which allow the colors to be redefined for any of the available 16\u2014this feature was retained in EGA and VGA cards. When the BIOS is used to set a video mode, it always sets up the PCjr palette table (i.e. the 16 palette registers) to emulate the CGA color palette for that mode.  Programs specifically written to use PCjr graphics can subsequently reprogram the palette table to use any colors desired.  Palette changes must be made during horizontal or vertical blanking periods of a video frame in order to avoid corrupting the display.  However, the provision of a vertical retrace interrupt (on IRQ5) simplifies this and also makes seamless page-flipping much easier. Although standard PC video cards had a flag to indicate that the vertical retrace was in progress, the PCjr added for the first time the ability to generate raster or VBLANK interrupts on IRQ 5. This allows the use of mixed video modes. The PCjr video subsystem also has a little-known graphics blink feature, which toggles the palette between the first and second groups of eight palette registers at the same rate used for the text blink feature, and a palette bit-masking feature that can be used to switch between palette subsets without reprogramming palette registers, by forcing one or more bits of each pixel value to zero before the value is used to look up the color in the palette table.\n\nVideo modes on the PCjr use varying amounts of system memory; 40x25 text mode uses 1k and 320x200x16 and 640x200x4 use 32k. Multiple text or graphics pages can be used as long as there is enough memory for them, thus the two largest modes allow only two graphics pages. The ability to page flip graphics modes answered one of the common criticisms of the CGA card, which had 16k of video memory and only supports multiple pages in text mode. Of the three new modes, 160x200x16 mode has the same layout as CGA graphics modes; the odd and even scanlines are stored in the first and second half of the video buffer, each half being 8k in size, and every four bits represents one pixel. The 320x200x16 and 640x200x4 modes have four blocks of scanlines; every four or two bits respectively represents a pixel.\n\nSince the PCjr uses the main system RAM for the video buffer, less memory is available for software than on a standard PC, which has its video memory in the A000h-BFFFh segments, above conventional memory.\n\n====Software====\nThe register mapping of the PCjr's video hardware is different from the standard CGA card, so software that tries to modify or read registers directly will not work\u2014the PCjr has a \"gate\" register in which the user writes the number of the video register to be accessed, followed by the value to be written into it.  Alteration of other CRTC registers cannot be assumed to produce the same results from the PCjr video system as from the CGA (and might damage the monitor).  (Programs for the CGA that manipulate the CRTC start address and that rely on address wrap-around above address 0xBC000 may not work correctly on the PCjr, because it always has a 32&nbsp;KB contiguous block of RAM in the video area from address 0xB8000 through 0xBFFFF.) The PCjr's video memory cannot be moved above 128k if expansion memory is added; some PC software that ran off of self-booting disks (mainly games) would not work on a PCjr if the software required more than 128k.\n\nPC DOS 2.10 was the minimum version of DOS required for the PCjr; IBM's OEM versions of MS-DOS supported the machine up to DOS 3.30, but memory expansion was required for DOS 3.20 and 3.30.\n\n====Hardware====\nThe PCjr display hardware consists primarily of two chips on the system board: a standard Motorola 6845 CRTC like the one used in the MDA and CGA adapters, and a custom IBM chip called the [[Video Gate Array]] (VGA)<ref name=\"vga\">VGA should not be confused with the later [[Video Graphics Array]] standard that IBM released with the [[PS/2]] line in 1987.</ref>{{r|nortonpcjrvideo19840124}}  The 6845 is responsible for the basic raster timing and video data address sequencing, and the Video Gate Array contains all the additional timing logic, the video data demultiplexing and color processing logic, and the programmable palette table logic, as well as the logic for multiplexing RAM access between the 8088 CPU and the video generation circuitry.  The 6845 CRTC and the VGA together are completely responsible for refreshing the internal DRAM of the PCjr (64 or 128&nbsp;KB), and this complicates the process of switching video modes on the PCjr.  (Resetting the VGA, which must be done during certain video mode switches, must be done by code not running from the internal RAM, and if the CRTC or the VGA is disabled for too long, the contents of the internal RAM can be lost.)  Additional external DRAM, in sidecar expansion modules, is refreshed separately, not by the CRTC and VGA.\n\n[[File:IBM PCB Jr Motherboard.jpg|thumb|IBM PC Jr Motherboard]]\n\n[[File:IBM PCB Jr Internal.jpg|thumb|IBM PC Jr Internal]]\n\n====Sound====\nThe PCjr's sound is provided by a [[Texas Instruments]] [[SN76496]] which can produce three square waves of varying amplitude and frequency along with a noise channel powered by a [[shift register]].<ref name=\"nortonpcjraudio19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Sound Abilities: The PCjr | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=137}}</ref> This device is sometimes also called a PSG (Programmable Sound Generator), and essentially equivalent devices were also used in the contemporary [[Sega Master System]] and the later [[Sega Genesis|Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]]. The PCjr design also allows for an analog sound source in an expansion-bus \"sidecar\" module, and software-controlled internal analog switch can select the source for the sound output from among the PC speaker, the SN76489, the cassette port, or the expansion-bus sound source.  Only one sound source can be selected at a time; the sources cannot be mixed.\n\n====Processor speed====\nThe PCjr's 4.77&nbsp;MHz [[Intel 8088]] [[CPU]] is faster than that of other computers that were aimed at the home market at the time,{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} though the stock PCjr usually does not run at the full rated 4.77&nbsp;MHz because access to the internal RAM is slowed by [[wait state]]s added by the Video Gate Array to synchronize shared access to RAM between the CPU and the video hardware. IBM claimed that an average of two wait states are added, but the designers of the Tandy 1000 claimed that six was a more accurate figure.<ref name=\"vose198412\">{{Cite magazine |last=Vose |first=G. Michael |date=December 1984 |title=The Tandy 1000 |url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1984-12/1984_12_BYTE_09-13_Communications#page/n99/mode/2up |magazine=BYTE |pages=98\u2013104}}</ref> However, this does not apply to programs or data located in ROM, including software on ROM cartridges plugged into the front of the PCjr, or located in additional RAM in a sidecar attachment; it only applies to the first 64 KB or 128 KB of RAM inside the system unit.  Therefore, under some circumstances the 8088 in the PCjr actually can run at the rated 4.77&nbsp;MHz.  The most common instances in which this maximum speed would be achieved are when running games or productivity applications from ROM cartridges; this would be a reason for PCjr users to prefer software in cartridges to software on disk media.  In fact, because the PCjr video subsystem continuously refreshes the system internal DRAM transparently, without disturbing the CPU, programs running from ROM on the PCjr will actually run slightly faster on the PCjr than on an IBM PC or XT.  This is because the PC and XT keep their DRAM refreshed by using a DMA channel to periodically request the bus from the CPU in order to perform a refresh cycle, whereas a program running from ROM on a PCjr will never be suspended for internal DRAM refresh cycles. To increase the system-speed of the IBM PCjr you can install a [[NEC V20]] instead of the 8088.\n\n====Wireless keyboard====\nThe detached wireless infrared keyboard promised a degree of convenience none of its competitors had, eliciting visions of word processing wirelessly from one's [[couch]] with the computer connected to a TV set as a display.{{r|hoffmann198403}}  For infrared wireless operation, it was powered by four common AA cells.  A keyboard cord option, that plugged into the keyboard with a modular 4-position telephone plug and into the back of the computer with a 6-pin (2x3) header connected, was also available for increased security and reliability. The cord also eliminated dependence on batteries; the keyboard IR receiver was automatically disabled when the keyboard cord was attached to the computer.\n\n===Differences from the IBM PC===\nWith a built-in [[RF modulator]], the PCjr can send video and audio to a television receiver; it also has an audio output jack to connect to an amplifier. The PCjr Color Display sold by IBM included an internal amplified speaker, being the only IBM monitor in the PC line to do so. [[IBM BASIC#IBM PCjr Cartridge BASIC|Cartridge BASIC]] enhances the standard IBM BASIC with commands to support the new video and audio functionality.<ref name=\"nortonpcjrvideo19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA128#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Screening the PCjr's Color, Video, And Memory Options | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | access-date=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=128}}</ref>{{r|nortonpcjraudio19840124}} Two joystick ports are also evidence of IBM's goal for marketing the PCjr as a home-friendly machine to compete with popular home machines like the Commodore 64, the Atari home computers, and the Apple II line. Other than the [[Tandy 1000]], which was designed as an enhanced PCjr clone to directly compete with the PCjr, and [[PC1512|Amstrad IBM PC compatible]] lines a few years later, the dual built-in joystick ports introduced by the PCjr never became standard on IBM PC compatibles, and have not been seen since. However, the single 15-pin D-subminiature joystick port common on later PCs supports two two-axis, two-button joysticks like those supported by the PCjr, and the 15-pin port can be split out to two separate joystick ports with a passive Y-adapter cable.\n\nFurther reinforcing the \"home-friendly\" goal, the PCjr also introduced two [[ROM cartridge]] slots on the front of the unit, meant to load software quickly and easily. The cartridges are plugged in from the front, prompting the computer to automatically reboot and run the software. This is more [[Usability|user-friendly]] than other home computer systems, which must be powered off when a cartridge was removed or inserted and come with warnings about damage to the computer if this requirement is ignored. Loading and saving data from cartridge software is possible via the floppy drive. The cartridge BASIC for the PCjr, in particular, gives programmers the advantage of a real programming language always ready without taking up system memory, as it was firmware, with its own address space. Being stored in ROM the BASIC loads very quickly, not needing access to the floppy disk or other storage.\n\nCartridges can also replace the system BIOS and other firmware.<ref name=\"norton19840320\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1tFFnOMCvv4C&lpg=PA477&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Unearthing The PCjr's Secrets | work=PC Magazine | date=March 20, 1984 | access-date=October 24, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=111}}</ref> A number of patches from various vendors are included on a single \"combo-cartridge\", licensed and sold by PC Enterprises, to support add-on hardware, bypass certain limitations of design, and keep up with changing OS requirements.\n\nExpansions (such as additional parallel ports, serial ports, memory, etc.) to the PCjr are provided via add-on [[daisy chain (electrical engineering)|\"sidecars\" that attach to the side of the PCjr]]. Multiple expansions are stacked together, increasing the width of the machine.\n\nThe floppy controller on the PCjr had its I/O registers mapped into different ports than on the PC, since the PCjr also did not have DMA, the BIOS routines for handling floppy access were different and more complex than those on the PC. Software that tried to perform direct, low-level disk access (mainly utilities, but also the occasional game such as ''Dunzhin: Warrior of Ras'') would not work unless it was rewritten for the PCjr.\n\nThe internal floppy drive on the PCjr was a half-height [[Qume]] 5.25\" unit; IBM also used these drives in the PC Portable, but the PCjr units were specially equipped with a small fan to prevent overheating since the computer did not have a case fan.\n\nThe PCjr's video uses 32&nbsp;kB of RAM as [[shared graphics memory]], which prevents using additional memory with the built-in 128&nbsp;KB under DOS.{{r|norton19840320}}  The specific issue is that while additional external RAM can be added directly above the internal RAM, making a [[flat memory model|flat model]], if the display is used, its buffer must reside somewhere within the first 128&nbsp;KB of RAM (from where it is mirrored at address 0xB8000).  Stock MS-DOS is not prepared to work around the video buffer in low RAM, using RAM both below and above it.  Two obvious solutions exist: Use the additional memory as a [[RAM drive]], or not use the built-in 128&nbsp;KB.<ref name=\"norton19840626\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IGkuDrOYjOcC&lpg=PA407&pg=PA98#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Adding to Junior's Memory | work=PC Magazine | date=June 26, 1984 | access-date=October 24, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=98}}</ref>  Another option would be to load a special DOS device driver or TSR, which would claim the RAM selected for use as the video buffer, causing DOS to load other drivers and programs above it.  A fourth option would be not to use MS-DOS, or to use a specially modified version of it.  For programs running from ROM cartridges, not using DOS was a very viable option, even in the mid-1980s when the PCjr was being marketed.\n[[File:IBM PC Jr BASIC Cartridge.jpg|thumb|IBM PC Jr BASIC Cartridge]]\n\n===Differences from other personal computers===\nThe PCjr initially shipped with a wireless [[chiclet keyboard]] called the \"Freeboard\",<ref name=\"halfhill198410\"/> powered by four AA batteries to provide infrared line-of-sight wireless communication. The keycaps are blank; labels appear between keys to permit [[Keyboard layout|overlays]].{{r|halfhill198401}} The chiclet keyboard was unpopular, and IBM replaced it with a model with typewriter keycaps.{{r|halfhill198410}} With 62 keys compared to the PC's 83, [[function keys]] and others need multiple keystrokes.{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|halfhill198401}} Certain room lights cause interference with the infrared keyboard sensor,<ref name=\"nichols20140322\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2014/03/22/ibm_pcjr_stripped_bare_still_mediocre_after_all_these_years/ | title=IBM PCjr STRIPPED BARE: We tear down the machine Big Blue would rather you forgot | website=The Register | date=March 22, 2014 | accessdate=April 1, 2014 | author=Nichols, Shaun}}</ref> as do multiple nearby keyboards.<ref name=\"lgr20110117\">{{cite AV media | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MbSto9irCoE | title=LGR - Experiencing The IBM PCjr Chiclet Keyboard | publisher=YouTube | date=January 17, 2011 | people=Lazy Game Reviews}}</ref> As mentioned previously, the keyboard can also operate with an optional [[modular connector|modular]] telephone-style cable, eliminating battery usage and IR interference.\n\nThe PCjr also has a [[light pen]] port. Besides being used for a light pen (a rarely purchased option), this port was used in combination with the serial port to supply voltage to a [[Mouse Systems]] optical mouse of the same design as those for [[Sun Microsystems|Sun workstations]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:PCjr.twinSCSI.jpg|thumb|A PCjr featuring most upgrades available from PC Enterprises, including combo cartridge, dual floppies, twin ST-225 HDDs (bootable via Future Domain firmware hidden under cover on right). Replacement keyboard sits on top of the Taxan RGB monitor. System is showing \"Battlechess\".]]\n\n===\"Peanut Panic\"===\n{{rquote|right|For my grandmother, and for millions of people like her, ''IBM '' and ''computer'' are synonymous.|''InfoWorld'', 1982<ref name=\"zussman19820823\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VDAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA19&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Let's keep those systems open | work=InfoWorld | date=1982-08-23 | accessdate=29 January 2015 | author=Zussman, John Unger | pages=29}}</ref>}}\n\nIBM in the early 1980s was the world's largest computer company, with 70% of the [[mainframe computer|mainframe]] market. When it introduced the IBM PC in August 1981, IBM did so as an experiment to defend against [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and others' newly popular microcomputers. While observers expected the PC to succeed, not even IBM executives expected it to become so popular so quickly. Within two years the PC created a large new ecosystem of business computers and software. It became a market leader<ref name=\"pollack19830327\">{{Cite news |last=Pollack |first=Andrew |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/03/27/business/big-ibm-has-done-it-again.html |title=Big I.B.M. Has Done It Again |date=1983-03-27 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-16 |page=Section 3, Page 1 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{r|ap19831102}}{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|time19831107}} with 26% of all microcomputers sold in 1983, in second place to the much less expensive [[Commodore 64]] (C64) and three times the [[Apple II]]'s share.<ref name=\"reimer20091102\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jeremyreimer.com/postman/node/329 | title=Total Share: Personal Computer Market Share 1975\u20132005 | accessdate=March 15, 2011 | author=Reimer, Jeremy | date=November 2, 2009 | publisher=Jeremy Reimer's Blog}}</ref>\n\nFor a year before the PCjr's announcement, the computer industry discussed rumors of a new IBM product, code named \"Peanut\", that would repeat the PC's success. The rumors described Peanut as a home computer with 64&nbsp;KB of memory that would be [[IBM PC compatible]], benefit from IBM's service network and, at US$600 to $1,000, less expensive than the [[Apple IIe]]. Customers visited stores attempting to buy the product, and rivals' revenue, product plans, and share prices reacted to the officially nonexistent computer in what the press called \"Peanut Panic\" or \"The Great Peanut Roast\".{{r|pollack19830327}}{{r|pollack19830619}}<ref name=\"greenwald19830711\">{{Cite magazine |last=Greenwald |first=John |date=1983-07-11 |title=The Colossus That Works |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,949693-2,00.html |url-status=live |url-access=subscription | magazine=TIME |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514004334/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,949693-2,00.html |archive-date=2008-05-14 |access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>{{r|coleco19830928}}{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"lock198312\">{{Cite magazine |last=Lock |first=Robert |date=December 1983 |title=Editor's Notes |url=https://archive.org/stream/1983-12-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_043_1983_Dec#page/n7/mode/2up |magazine=Compute! |page=6}}</ref><ref name=\"ruby198402\" /><ref name=\"infoworld19831121\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA19&dq=ibm%20peanut&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q=ibm%20peanut&f=false | title=Industry reacts to PCjr | accessdate=February 25, 2011 |author1=Mace, Scott |author2=Paul Freiberger | date=November 21, 1983 | pages=21\u201322 | work=InfoWorld}}</ref><ref name=\"springer198401\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/ahoy-magazine-01/Ahoy_01_January_1984#page/n37/mode/2up | title=Can the 64 Crack the Peanut? | work=Ahoy! | date=January 1984 | accessdate=October 16, 2013 | author=Springer, Steve | pages=39}}</ref>{{r|pollack19830619}}{{r|halfhill198401}}{{r|burton198303}}<ref name=\"gantz19831114\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA110#v=onepage&f=false | title=Heard On Tech Street | work=InfoWorld | date=November 14, 1983 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Gantz, John | pages=110}}</ref>{{r|levy198501}}\n\nMany expected, or feared, that an IBM home computer would destroy Apple, Commodore, and others, leaving no competitors. By November 1983, Peanut allegedly would cost $600-700 with the [[Motorola 68000]] or other powerful CPU, two {{frac|3|1|2}} inch disk drives, and sophisticated graphics.{{r|levy198501}} While the company repeatedly denied rumors<ref name=\"byte198311\">{{cite news|author=Curran, Lawrence J.|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1983-11/1983_11_BYTE_08-11_Inside_the_IBM_PC#page/n89/mode/2up|title=IBM's Estridge|date=November 1983|work=BYTE|accessdate=March 19, 2016|url-status=live|last2=Shuford, Richard S.|pages=88\u201397}}</ref>{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"maceiie19840409\"/>{{r|time19850401}} it estimated that 50 to 70% of PCs sold in retail stores went to the home, a market which CEO [[John Opel]] described as \"inevitable as the sunrise tomorrow\" for IBM.<ref name=\"burton198303\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7wCiNAUEuAMC&lpg=RA1-PA168&pg=RA1-PA467#v=onepage&f=false | title=Anatomy of a Colossus, Part III | work=PC | date=Mar 1983 | accessdate=March 30, 2014 | author=Burton, Kathleen | pages=467}}</ref> ''[[PC Magazine]]'' reported that observers believed the company did not \"face substantial competition on the home front\" from computers that many considered \"mere gadgets or expensive toys\".{{r|burton198303}} Andrew Pollack of ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated that \"One thing that seems certain is that movement will be away from game playing toward more powerful computers with greater capabilities\".<ref name=\"pollack19830619\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/19/business/the-coming-crisis-in-home-computers.html?pagewanted=all | title=The Coming Crisis in Home Computers | work=The New York Times | date=June 19, 1983 | accessdate=January 19, 2015 | author=Pollack, Andrew}}</ref> The success \"of the Peanut is as good as established\", ''Ahoy!'' predicted.{{r|springer198401}}\n\nBy September 1983, books and magazine articles on Peanut were ready for publishing, with only a few changes needed once the still officially nonexistent computer appeared. Software companies prepared to market products as \"Peanut compatible\" with the computer that, rumors said, IBM would produce 500,000 units of in the first year. ''[[Adweek]]'' estimated that IBM would spend $75 million on marketing, including an alleged license of [[Charles Schulz]]'s [[Peanuts]] characters. ''Smalltalk'' magazine in August published a detailed article on the computer, stating that it would cost $600 plus $400 for a disk drive, use a color TV as a display, and have a standard typewriter keyboard.<ref name=\"esd19830927\">{{Cite news |last=Sandberg-Diment |first=Erik |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/27/science/personal-computers-is-the-ibm-peanut-really-in-the-wings.html |title=Personal Computers; Is the I.B.M. Peanut Really in the Wings? |date=September 27, 1983 |work=The New York Times |access-date=December 14, 2017 |page=C5 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Release===\n[[File:PCjr chiclet.gif|thumb|right|300px|One observer compared using the original chiclet keyboard to \"massaging fruit cake\".{{r|sandler19840221}}]]\n\nOn what ''Time'' called \"[[Normandy landings|D-Day]] for the Home Computer\",<ref name=\"time19831107\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,949869,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122161630/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C949869%2C00.html |archive-date=November 22, 2008 |title=D-Day for the Home Computer |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=Moritz, Michael |author2=John Greenwald |author3=Frederick Ungeheuer |date=November 7, 1983 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and others described as \"the biggest fanfare in the history of computers\",{{r|ap19850321}} IBM announced the PCjr on November 1, 1983, at its [[IBM Building, New York City|New York City headquarters]] with an enormous amount of advance publicity, including live news coverage of the event.<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /> ''[[Compute!]]'' wrote \"Never before in the history of personal computing (admittedly a brief history) has a product been so eagerly awaited by so many\".<ref name=\"halfhill198401\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1984-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_044_1984_Jan#page/n45/mode/2up | title=IBM's New PCjr | work=Compute! | date=January 1984 | accessdate=October 30, 2013 | author=Halfhill, Tom R. | pages=44}}</ref>\n\n''[[Business Week]]''{{'}}s cover said \"AND THE WINNER IS...IBM!\"{{r|levy198501}} Experts predicted, according to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', that the PCjr \"will quickly become the standard by which all other home computers are measured\".{{r|wp19831106}} No longer facing a [[History of IBM#1969: Antitrust, the Unbundling of software and services|long-running antitrust suit by the United States government]], IBM and dealers boasted that \"we are going to sell as many of these things as we can possibly make\".{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|time19840402}} Observers agreed,<ref name=\"sanger19850707\">{{Cite news |last=Sanger |first=David E. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/07/07/magazine/the-changing-image-of-ibm.html |title=The Changing Image of I.B.M. |date=1985-07-07 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-11 |page=Section 6, Page 13 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> predicting sales of one million or more in 1984,<ref name=\"pollack19831102\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/02/business/the-debut-of-ibm-s-junior.html?pagewanted=all | title=The Debut of I.B.M.'S Junior | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Pollack, Andrew | date=November 2, 1983 | work=The New York Times}}</ref> and expected the PCjr to change the home-computer market in a similar way to how the IBM PC had changed the business-microcomputer market.<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /><ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" />{{r|halfhill198401}} They predicted that the PCjr would extend IBM's dominance, with customers able to use the company's computers in the home and in the office.{{r|burton198303}}{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|wp19831106}}\n\n''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' observed that \"The PCjr ... has at least three invaluable assets: the letters I, B, and M\".{{r|marcom19840222}} \"The three initials on its nameplate\", ''[[Popular Science]]'' wrote, were \"letters that, in the minds of many, represent quality, reliability, and an assurance that the company will be around for as long as the computer is\".{{r|ruby198402}} Even rivals like Coleco,<ref name=\"coleco19830928\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gg_I9TGYM-w |title=Coleco Presents The Adam Computer System |date=May 3, 2016 |publisher=YouTube |orig-year=1983-09-28 |time=1:05:15 |quote=We at Coleco think that IBM's possible or probably entry to the home-computer field with 'Peanut', whether it's this year or next year, is extremely encouraging and positive, both for the home-computer industry and in particular for Coleco. Now, I assure you I haven't taken leave of my senses, and obviously it's no lack of respect for the well-earned reputation of IBM that prompts me to say that. But there's at least four considerations that I'd like to throw out to you and help you as far as my thinking.}}</ref><ref name=\"ap19831102\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3360529// | title=Analysts say: IBM's PCjr won't disrupt Christmas for competitors | work=Santa Cruz Sentinel | date=November 2, 1983 | agency=Associated Press | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | pages=B-5}}</ref><ref name=\"rosenberg19831208\">{{Cite news |title=Home Computer? Maybe Next Year |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=December 8, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> Commodore,{{r|cook19840306}} and Tandy<ref name=\"mace19831226\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2i8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA86&pg=PA91#v=onepage&f=false | title=Q&A: Mark Yamagata | work=InfoWorld | date=December 26, 1983 \u2013 January 2, 1984 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | author=Mace, Scott | pages=91}}</ref> hoped that IBM would stabilize and bring credibility to the chaotic $2 billion home-computer market, which had seen \"cutthroat\" [[price war]]s between Commodore, [[Atari Inc.|Atari]], and others for 18 months.{{r|burton198303}}<ref name=\"ap19831101\">{{Cite news |title=IBM's Peanut Begins New Computer Phase |date=November 1, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>{{r|wp19831106}}<ref name=\"cook19840306\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhoP0KRkQe4C&lpg=PA8&pg=PA35#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Jr. Sneaks PC into Home | work=PC Magazine | date=March 6, 1984 | accessdate=October 24, 2013 | author=Cook, Karen | pages=35}}</ref><ref name=\"rosenberg19831106\">{{Cite news |title=Computers; The Abounding Uncertainties; Consumers and Companies Spar in New Arena without Guidelines |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=November 6, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>{{r|infoworld19831121}}{{r|ruby198402}} \"IBM is a company that knows how to make money\", Coleco CEO [[Arnold Greenberg (Coleco)|Arnold Greenberg]] said. \"What IBM can bring to the home-computer field is something that the field collectively needs, particularly now: A respect for profitability. A capability to earn money\".<ref name=\"coleco19830928b\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gg_I9TGYM-w |title=Coleco Presents The Adam Computer System |date=May 3, 2016 |publisher=YouTube |orig-year=1983-09-28 |time=1:06:55 |quote=IBM is just not another strong company making a positive statement about the home-computer field's future. IBM is a company that knows how to make money. IBM is a company that knows how to make money in hardware, and makes more money in software. What IBM can bring to the home-computer field is something that the field collectively needs, particularly now: A respect for profitability. A capability to earn money. That is precisely what the field needs ... I look back a year or two in the videogame field, or the home-computer field, how much better everyone was, when most people were making money, rather than very few were making money.}}</ref> TI left the market four days before IBM's announcement, after losing US$223 million in nine months against Commodore{{r|ap19831102}}{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"maceti19831121\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA19&dq=ibm%20peanut&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q=ibm%20peanut&f=false | title=TI retires from home-computer market | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Mace, Scott | date=November 21, 1983 | work=InfoWorld | pages=22, 27}}</ref> by selling its [[TI 99/4A|99/4A]] for as low as $99; such low prices likely damaged the reputation of the industry by making home computers appear to be inferior game machines.{{r|pollack19830619}}{{r|cook19840306}} (The 99/4A was so unsuccessful that TI stock immediately rose by 25% after the discontinuation.{{r|ap19831101}})\n\nIBM did not plan to sell the PCjr through discount stores,{{r|cook19840306}} and experts expected that the company would likely not compete on price;{{r|nyt19831102}} [[Paine Webber|PaineWebber]] predicted that the PCjr would open a \"price umbrella\" over home-computer companies.<ref name=\"wp19831106\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3360554// | title=IBM PCjr leads the way for industry | work=The Pantagraph | date=November 6, 1983 | agency=The Washington Post | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | pages=E6}}</ref> Observers did not see low-end computers as the PCjr's main competition, however, expecting it to most affect sales of the IIe, another home-business crossover product.{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|ap19831102}} PC expert [[Peter Norton]] wrote that the new computer \"has all, or nearly all, the capacity and flexibility that most of us who are already using PC's need ... All in all, the PCjr looks like a remarkable machine for its capabilities and an astounding one for its price\", and predicted that \"the PCjr will make an even bigger splash\" than the PC.{{r|norton19840124}} Financial writer John Gantz wrote \"Conventional wisdom says that with the PCjr, IBM has the personal-computer market sewed up [and that] IBM will kick hind end in any market remotely related to the PC, maybe in any market whatsoever\".{{r|gantz19831128}}\n\nDevelopers began developing PCjr software in 1982,{{r|maher20130718}} for which a rumor stated that IBM paid US$10 million.{{r|clapp19840109_16}} [[Sierra On-Line]], [[Software Publishing Corporation|SPC]], and [[The Learning Company]] were among those that produced two dozen games, productivity, and educational software as [[Launch game|launch titles]],{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|wiswell19840124}} using detailed IBM production outlines.{{r|rosenberg19840424}} IBM security made unannounced visits to search wastebaskets and verify that computer prototypes remained hidden in locked rooms,<ref name=\"sanger19840422\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/22/business/the-heady-world-of-ibm-suppliers.html |title=The Heady World of I.B.M. Suppliers |last=Sanger |first=David E. |date=April 22, 1984 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 | page=Section 3, Page 1 | |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |author-link=David E. Sanger}}</ref> with everyone entering signing logbooks that IBM could review at any time.<ref name=\"rosenberg19840424\">{{Cite news |title=The Secret World of IBM |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=April 24, 1984 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The PCjr's graphics and sound features were superior to the PC's,{{r|nortonpcjraudio19840124}}{{r|shea19840312}}{{r|pollack19831102}} and ''PC Magazine'' speculated that \"the PCjr might be the best game machine ever designed\".<ref name=\"wiswell19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA142#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Coming Soon: Games For The PCjr | work=PC | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=January 26, 2015 | author=Wiswell, Phil | pages=142\u2013145}}</ref> Prominent among launch titles was Sierra's [[graphical adventure]] ''[[King's Quest I]]''; IBM paid much of the game's $850,000 budget.<ref name=\"maher20130718\">{{cite web | url=http://www.filfre.net/2013/07/the-unmaking-and-remaking-of-sierra-on-line/ | title=The Unmaking and Remaking of Sierra On-Line | publisher=The Digital Antiquarian | date=July 18, 2013 | accessdate=February 5, 2015 | author=Maher, Jimmy}}</ref>\n\nObservers believed that software companies would also publish many non-game applications for the new computer{{r|cook19840306}} without fearing that it would quickly become [[orphaned technology]].{{r|pollack19831102}}<ref name=\"wierzbicki19831219\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5C8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA51&pg=PA51#v=onepage&f=false | title=Developers embrace PCjr despite drawbacks | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Wierzbicki, Barbara | date=December 19, 1983 | work=InfoWorld}}</ref> Major peripheral manufacturer [[Tecmar]] stated in full-page magazine advertisements \"We're glad you're here, PCjr. Tecmar will have a boat-load of products for you\".<ref name=\"ad198403\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/creativecomputing-1984-03/Creative_Computing_v10_n03_1984_Mar#page/n1/mode/2up | title=Welcome A-Board / Tecmar Greets the New PCjr | work=Creative Computing | date=March 1984 | accessdate=February 6, 2015 | pages=Inside front cover | type=advertisement}}</ref> Advanced Input, the small Idaho company IBM chose to manufacture the PCjr keyboard, predicted that it would be the world's largest keyboard manufacturer by 1990.{{r|nyt19831126}}\n\nAlthough IBM missed the [[Economics of Christmas|important Christmas sales season]] because of production delays, by announcing early the company succeeded in its likely goal of hurting competitors with [[fear, uncertainty and doubt]].<ref name=\"nyt19831102\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/02/business/ibm-s-speedy-redirection.html | title=I.B.M.'S Speedy Redirection | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | date=November 2, 1983 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{r|marcom19840222}}{{r|time19840402}}{{r|time19850401}} [[ComputerLand]] sold gift certificates with a large model of the computer \"'beautifully wrapped to go under your Christmas tree'\".<ref name=\"freiberger19840109_16\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ey4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA14&ots=qxysACmBMb&pg=PA20#v=onepage&f=false | title=IBM indicates March as likely PCjr delivery date | work=InfoWorld | date=January 9\u201316, 1984 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Freiberger, Paul | pages=20}}</ref> IBM planned to spend US$40 million on advertising<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,951424,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514070332/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C951424%2C00.html |archive-date=May 14, 2009 |title=A Flop Becomes a Hit |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=McCarroll, Thomas |author2=Philip Elmer-DeWitt |date=December 24, 1984 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> with [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s iconic character \"[[The Little Tramp]]\", already used in a successful campaign for the PC.<ref>{{cite web|title=IBM PCjr Classic Ad|url=http://www.adclassix.com/ads/84ibmpcjr.htm|year=1984}}</ref><ref name=\"papson1990\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC35folder/IBMtramp.html | title=The IBM tramp | author=Papson, Stephen | journal=Jump Cut: A Review of Contemporary Media |date=April 1990  | issue=35 | pages=66\u201372}}</ref> [[Ziff Davis]], publisher of the successful ''PC Magazine'', printed the first issue of ''PCjr Magazine'' before the first units shipped; competing [[computer magazine]]s included ''Peanut'', ''PCjr World'',<ref name=\"nyt19831109\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/09/business/boom-in-computer-magazines.html | title=Boom in Computer Magazines | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | date=November 9, 1983 | work=The New York Times }}</ref> ''jr'', and ''Compute! for the PC and PCjr''.<ref name=\"bartimo19841210\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=si4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA35&pg=PA35#v=onepage&f=false | title=Magazines Woo Users | accessdate=March 14, 2011 | author=Bartimo, Jim | date=December 10, 1984 | pages=35\u201336 | work=InfoWorld}}</ref> The publisher of an [[instant book]] that appeared the month of the computer's introduction said that consumers wanted to learn about it as much as [[Operation Entebbe]] and the [[Jonestown Massacre]].<ref name=\"rosenberg19831125\">{{Cite news |title=160-page 'Instant Book' on IBM's PCjr Home Computer Due Out Today |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=November 25, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe }}</ref>\n\n===Commercial failure===\n{{rquote|right|The machine has the smell of death about it.|[[Steven Levy]], 1984{{r|mccarroll19841224}}}}\n\nErik Sandberg-Diment of the ''Times'' wondered when discussing Peanut rumors in September 1983 why IBM would release a lower-cost, mass-market product compatible with PC software when demand for the PC exceeded supply: \"Why should I.B.M. undercut its own, already practically guaranteed sales, just to engage in a very messy fight in the notoriously fickle and often profitless consumer market? That just doesn't make sense\".{{r|esd19830927}}\n\n[[George Morrow (computers)|George Morrow]] was one of the few to be pessimistic about the PCjr after the November announcement, predicting that Commodore's [[Jack Tramiel]] would \"make mincemeat\" of the \"toylike\" computer.{{r|infoworld19831121}} \"Somehow the mighty colossus looked a lot smaller that day\", ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' wrote, calling PCjr \"a terrible disappointment\".<ref name=\"shapiro198402\">{{Cite magazine |last=Shapiro |first=Neil |date=February 1984 |title=Big Bytes for Little Bucks |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GuMDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA99&ots=046J8EGyex&pg=PA98#v=onepage&f=true |magazine=Popular Mechanics |pages=98\u201399,139\u2013142}}</ref> ''InCider'' agreed that the computer was disappointing, but observed that \"no product could have lived up to the jr's pre-release publicity\".<ref name=\"ryan198407\">{{Cite magazine |last=Ryan |first=Bob |date=July 1984 |title=The newest member of the family goes head to head with the PCjr. |url=https://archive.org/stream/inCider_84-07#page/n59/mode/2up |magazine=InCider |pages=60\u201363}}</ref> The ''Times'' noted that \"After all that waiting, it seems odd that no one appears particularly enthusiastic about the machine\".<ref name=\"esd19831227\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/27/science/personal-computers-the-little-ibm-finally-arrives-for-a-test.html |title=Personal Computers: The Little I.B.M. Finally Arrives for a Test |last=Sandberg-Diment |first=Erik |date=December 27, 1983 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Steven Levy]] recalled that at the press conference \"I felt like I was at the eighties version of [[Woodstock Festival|Woodstock]]. But what awaited us was, to my eyes, more like [[Altamont Free Concert|Altamont]]\". Despite his disappointment, Levy said that so many others were positive about the computer that he doubted his own judgment until receiving a review unit.{{r|levy198501}}\n\nSeveral ''[[InfoWorld]]'' writers criticized the computer. Offering a \"contrarian view: the PCjr could actually turn out to be a dog\", Gantz wrote that \"it's consumer and buyer demand that will spell success, not how awesome IBM is. It's still a free country, we don't ''have'' to buy the PCjr\".{{r|gantz19831128}} [[John Dvorak]] joked that \"champagne corks were popping all over the place. The bottles were being opened by Apple shareholders\".<ref name=\"dvorak19831128\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA188&ots=R2H3IQegBq&pg=PA188#v=onepage&f=false | title=Inside Track | work=InfoWorld | date=November 28, 1983 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | author=Dvorak, John C. | pages=188}}</ref> Doug Clapp called PCjr \"a pathetic, crippled computer\", but glumly expected that \"the magic letters IBM\" and the company's enormous financial and marketing resources would let it \"get away with this stuff\".<ref name=\"clapp19840109_16\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ey4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA14&ots=qxysACmBMb&pg=PA14#v=onepage&f=false | title=Clapp-Trapp | work=InfoWorld | date=January 9\u201316, 1984 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Clapp, Doug | pages=14}}</ref>\n\nDvorak added that after the PCjr announcement \"I go to my local ComputerLand dealer and everyone there is depressed. 'I'm not sure I even want to carry it,' said the manager\", in contrast to the reaction to the PC.{{r|dvorak19831128}} When the PCjr became widely available in early 1984{{r|freiberger19840109_16}} sales were below expectations. One store owner reported that \"Interest was at a fever pitch\" after the announcement, but \"Once we had a demonstration model (in January), the only thing I can say is that the response was underwhelming\".{{r|marcom19840222}} Dealers reported that consumers disliked the price, keyboard, and lack of memory;{{r|nyt19840420}}  those that sold to business customers did not know how to market it.<ref name=\"mcmullen19840221\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UCIvSU6Y2GAC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA120#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Apple Charts The Course For IBM | work=PC Magazine | date=1984-02-21 | accessdate=24 October 2013 | author=McMullen, Barbara E. and John F. | page=122}}</ref>\n\nBy March the press reported that PCjr could be an embarrassment for IBM, with executives reportedly worrying about demand. Stores began discounts while vendors slowed plans to release products.{{r|richter19840328}}<ref name=\"zientara19840409\"/>{{r|sanger19840517}} The company admitted that \"In April, demand for the PCjr has been variable, and is not growing quite as rapidly as we expected\". It said that demand in the first quarter of 1984 \"met our expectations\", but each dealer was required to purchase a certain quantity at the computer's introduction.<ref name=\"nyt19840420\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/20/business/pcjr-sales-less-than-expected.html |title=PCjr Sales Less Than Expected |date=1984-04-20 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-11 |page=D3 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> IBM began unusually early discounts of up to US$370<ref name=\"winter19850324\">{{cite news | url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1985/03/24/page/79/article/behind-the-short-unhappy-life-of-ibms-junior | title=Behind the short, unhappy life of IBM's Junior | work=Chicago Tribune | date=March 24, 1985 | accessdate=April 29, 2015 | author=Winter, Christine | pages=Section 7, Page 3}}</ref> on 7 June, lowering the two models' prices to $599 and $999,{{r|bulman19841105}} but many of its 1,400 dealers could not sell initial allotments of 25 computers.{{r|marcom19840222}}{{r|bulman19841105}} IBM allowed dealers to postpone paying for inventory for 180 days.<ref name=\"pollack19850120\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/01/20/business/the-daunting-power-of-ibm.html |title=The Daunting Power of I.B.M. |last=Pollack |first=Andrew |date=January 20, 1985 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 3, 2017 |page=A1 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \"Inventory is beginning to pile up\", ''Time'' wrote in April;<ref name=\"time19840402\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,954205-2,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609012541/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C954205%2C00.html |archive-date=June 9, 2008 |title=The Peanut Meets the Mac |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=McCarroll, Thomas |author2=Michael Moritz |author3=Philip Elmer-DeWitt |date=April 2, 1984 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> by August ''InfoWorld'' described it as \"the colossal flop that the experts said couldn't happen\";<ref name=\"mace19840813\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA38pg=PA38#v=onepage&f=true | title=PCjr: Back to Basics | work=InfoWorld | date=August 13, 1984 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Mace, Scott | pages=38}}</ref> and in December ''Time'' stated that the PCjr \"looked like one of the biggest flops in the history of computing...[it] sold as sluggishly as [[Edsel]]s in the late 1950s\".<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" />\n\n====Keyboard====\n{{rquote|right|How could IBM have made that mistake with the PCjr?|Tandy executive, 1984{{r|iw19840820}}}}\n\nJournalists at the PCjr announcement who hoped for, ''Compute!'' reported, \"a revolutionary machine that would reinvent the home computer\"{{r|halfhill198401}} \"gasp[ed in] dismay\"{{r|pollack19831102}} when they saw its chiclet keyboard. \"No single component in an IBM computer has ever attracted such controversy\", the ''Times'' said,{{r|sanger19840422}} describing it as \"not suitable for serious long-term typing\"{{r|pollack19831102}} and \"nearly useless\",<ref name=\"nyt19840821\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/21/science/personal-computer-keyboard-is-a-stroke-of-genius.html | title=Keyboard is a Stroke of Genius | work=The New York Times | date=August 21, 1984 | accessdate=July 31, 2014 | author=Sandberg-Diment, Erik}}</ref> with fingers having \"all the grace of a rubber-kneed centipede\" on it.{{r|esd19831227}} ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' described the \"noticeably different\" PCjr keyboard as \"weak for word processing\",<ref name=\"rosenberg19831102\">{{Cite news |title=Enter IBM with PCjr |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=November 2, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> and ''Popular Mechanics'' warned that no \"businessman or professional would feel comfortable with\" the \"distinctly toylike\" keyboard.{{r|shapiro198402}} ''PC Magazine'' quoted someone comparing the keyboard's touch to \"massaging fruit cake\",<ref name=\"sandler19840221\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UCIvSU6Y2GAC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA323#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=A Secret Inside The ROM | work=PC Magazine | date=February 21, 1984 | accessdate=October 24, 2013 | author=Sandler, Corey | pages=323}}</ref> and stated that using IBM's function keys-dependent [[IBM DisplayWrite|DisplayWrite]] word processor on the PCjr \"requires a level of digital dexterity more normally associated with concert piano playing\".{{r|dickinsondw19840918}}\n\nA [[Yankee Group]] analyst said that the keyboard\u2014which IBM reportedly sought to manufacture for the unusually low $15\u201320\u2014needed \"orangutan fingers to type on\",<ref name=\"nyt19831126\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/26/business/advanced-input-s-ibm-coup.html |title=Advanced Input's I.B.M. Coup |date=November 26, 1983 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Clapp wrote that \"to say that jr even ''has'' a keyboard is far too charitable\".{{r|clapp19840109_16}} ''Compute!'' agreed, stating that the computer \"leaves something to be desired. A keyboard for one\". The magazine observed that \"Atari and Coleco must have breathed collective sighs of relief, because both promptly raised January 1 pricing of their personal computer systems\".<ref name=\"lock198401\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1984-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_044_1984_Jan#page/n7/mode/2up | title=Editor's Notes | work=Compute! | date=January 1984 | accessdate=October 30, 2013 | author=Lock, Robert | pages=6}}</ref> ''[[BYTE]]'' called the keyboard \"a new standard for intentional product handicapping\",<ref name=\"malloy198406\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1984-06/1984_06_BYTE_09-06_Computers_and_Education#page/n297/mode/2up | title=Reviewer's Notebook | work=BYTE | date=June 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Malloy, Rich | pages=297}}</ref> and despite IBM denials{{r|levy198501}} other publications and experts agreed that the keyboard was evidence of [[product differentiation]] by the company, giving the PCjr less capability to avoid [[cannibalization (marketing)|cannibalizing]] IBM PC sales.{{r|nyt19831126}}{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"ahoy198402\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/ahoy-magazine-02/Ahoy_02_February_1984#page/n13/mode/2up | title=Rumor, Innuendo & \"Ted\" | work=Ahoy! | date=February 1984 | accessdate=October 16, 2013 | pages=14}}</ref><ref name=\"ruby198402\" />{{r|richter19840328}}{{r|mccarroll19841224}}\n\nThe keyboard design stunned many in the industry, including [[Ken Williams (game developer)|Ken Williams]] and others at Sierra\u2014whose prototypes did not have the chiclet keyboard\u2014and [[Doug Carlston]] of [[Br\u00f8derbund|Br\u00f8derbund Software]].{{r|infoworld19831121}}{{r|sanger19840422}}{{r|maher20130718}} \"How could IBM have made that mistake with the PCjr?\", an astounded Tandy executive asked.<ref name=\"iw19840820\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA50&pg=PA50#v=onepage&f=false | title=From Home to Business: The Eclectic Radio Shack Computer Line | accessdate=May 26, 2011 | date=August 20, 1984 | work=InfoWorld | pages=47\u201352}}</ref> Dvorak stated that \"the week before the announcement, [another journalist] told me it had a 'chiclet' keyboard. 'No way \u2014 that's the dumbest thing IBM could do,' I replied ... [it's] associated with $99 el cheapo computers\".{{r|dvorak19831128}} Factory workers manufacturing the keyboard mocked its poor quality,<ref name=\"digibarn\">{{cite web | url=http://www.digibarn.com/collections/devices/pcjr-chicklet-keyboard/index.html | title=Chicklet Keyboard frm IBM PC Jr | publisher=DigiBarn Computer Museum | accessdate=January 26, 2015 | author=Damer, Bruce}}</ref> even IBM salesmen advised customers to buy a replacement,{{r|sanger19840517}} and Dvorak predicted that other companies would \"make a fortune selling real keyboards for the thing\".{{r|dvorak19831128}}\n\n====Cost====\n{{rquote|right|Junior is probably the most expensive product sold with the famous legend, \"Batteries not included.\"|''PC Magazine'' on the PCjr's wireless keyboard, 1985<ref name=\"manes19850528\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DDlmJxSURq8C&lpg=PP1&pg=RA1-PA67#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Junior and Edsel: Two of A Kind Together At Last! | work=PC Magazine | date=1985-05-28 | accessdate=28 October 2013 | author=Manes, Stephen | pages=67}}</ref>}}\n\nThe PCjr's cost was its biggest disadvantage, even more so than the keyboard.<ref name=\"time19840402\" /> ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that customers \"find that the PCjr is expensive for a home computer but isn't very powerful for an expensive computer\".{{r|marcom19840222}} ''Ahoy!'' wrote that \"a machine with relatively limited technology at a relatively high price, not only presented much less of a threat than the industry had feared\", but benefited the C64 by encouraging Atari and Coleco to raise prices.<ref name=\"leemon198405\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/Ahoy_Issue_05_1984-05_Ion_International_US#page/n43/mode/2up | title=The Future of Commodore? | work=Ahoy! | date=May 1984 | accessdate=June 27, 2014 | author=Leemon, Sheldon | pages=44}}</ref> IBM did not say whether the target market was the home, schools, or executives working at home, confusing software developers, consumers,{{r|wierzbicki19831219}}{{r|ap19850321}} and dealers,{{r|mcmullen19840221}} but likely erred by setting the PCjr's price in the US$800\u2013$1,600 range, where demand was weaker than for computers that cost less\u2014especially the C64\u2014or more. Norton warned that the PCjr \"may well be targeted at a gray area in the market that just does not exist\",{{r|sanger19840517}} and an observer estimated that \"perhaps only 10 to 15% of the home market will be interested\".{{r|uston198403}} IBM were surprised to learn that many of the initial customers for the PCjr were not home users as they assumed, but instead businesses who wanted a cheaper PC that took less space on a desk.\n\nIBM was unfamiliar with the consumer market but hoped that customers would be willing to pay more for a product with, as an industry expert said, \"those three letters\".{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|wp19831106}} Many consumers wanted a computer more sophisticated than those costing less than $500, but did not want to spend more than $1,000.{{r|ap19850321}} Without a [[VisiCalc]]-like [[killer app]] for the home \"There is no compelling reason, based on what's available in software, to convince families to\" spend $2,000 on a computer, one computer-store chain manager said.<ref name=\"rosenberg19840228\">{{Cite news |title=Doubts Raised About PCjr |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=February 28, 1984 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> ''Popular Mechanics'' warned that at $669 and $1,269, PCjr \"has been priced out of those markets\" and [[Coleco Adam]] or \"almost any other computer in those price ranges is a better buy\".{{r|shapiro198402}} Gantz agreed, stating that \"inasmuch as it goes after the home market, [the PCjr] goes to a very price-sensitive crowd\". Unlike IBM's traditional corporate customers \"the home computer crowd has no notion of concepts like upward compatibility, software availability, or the importance of vendor stability\", he wrote;<ref name=\"gantz19831128\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA186&pg=PA186#v=onepage&f=false | title=Heard on Tech Street | work=InfoWorld | date=November 28, 1983 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Gantz, John | pages=186}}</ref> such customers usually bought the C64, which became more popular.{{r|sanger19840517}}\n\nThe PCjr cost more than twice as much as the C64 and the [[Atari 8-bit family]], while inferior to both and the IIe for games.{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|lima19841203}} [[Imagic]] stated that the C64 was \"a lot faster and it sells for one third the price\",{{r|cook19840306}} Sierra's Williams predicted that \"There's no way our game [[Frogger]] will ever look as good on the PCjr as it does on the Commodore 64 or the Atari\",{{r|pollack19831102}} and Spinnaker said that \"for its level of performance it is simply the most expensive machine on the market\".{{r|time19840402}} After the PCjr's discontinuation, Spinnaker chairman William Bowman said that it developed software assuming that the more expensive model would cost $800 to $900, and \"we dropped production immediately\" when the company learned that it would cost $1,269.<ref name=\"ap19850321\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31243737/poughkeepsie_journal/ |title=The runner stumbles: IBM pulls back from troubled PCjr |date=1985-03-21 |work=Poughkeepsie Journal |access-date=2019-05-05 |agency=Associated Press |page=7 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThose willing to pay more than $1,000 could buy better computers than the PCjr for the same price.{{r|ap19850321}} Consumers were reportedly much more excited about the also-new [[Macintosh 128K]], more sophisticated but only US$300 more expensive with accessories and software.{{r|time19840402}}<ref name=\"marcom19840222\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3360489// | title=IBM's PCjr receives a cool reception | work=Santa Cruz Sentinel | date=February 22, 1984 | agency=Wall Street Journal | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | author=Marcom, John Jr. | pages=B-5}}</ref> So compelling that one dealer called it \"the first $2,500 [[impulse item]] I've ever seen\", Macintosh reportedly outsold the IBM product during their first two months on the market.<ref name=richter19840328>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31276226/the_cincinnati_enquirer/ |title=Macintosh Takes Lead In Sales Race |last=Richter |first=Paul |date=1984-03-28 |work=The Cincinnati Enquirer |access-date=2019-05-05 |agency=Los Angeles Times |pages=B-1, B-2 |language=en}}</ref> PCjr's price was close to that of the Coleco Adam, but the Adam also included a [[tape drive]], a printer, and software.{{r|time19831107}} A realistic cost including peripherals was $2,000{{r|esd19831227}}{{r|levy198501}} and other packages cost $3,000 or more,<ref name=\"ruby198402\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQAAAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA68&dq=peanut%20ibm%20pcjr&pg=PA68#v=onepage&q=peanut%20ibm%20pcjr&f=false | title=IBM's PCjr&mdash;was it worth the wait? | accessdate=February 24, 2011 | author=Ruby, Daniel | date=February 1984 | work=Popular Science | pages=68\u201371}}</ref> even while IBM did not include batteries for the wireless keyboard.{{r|manes19850528}}{{r|levy198501}}\n\nThe IIe was the PCjr's most direct competition.{{r|richter19840328}}{{r|zientara19840409}}{{r|ryan198407}} Although the PC outsold it{{r|maceiie19840409}} Apple sold almost 110,000 units in December 1983, in part to customers who had waited until details of the PCjr became available.<ref name=\"pollack19840116\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/01/16/business/apple-expands-product-line.html |title=Apple Expands Product Line |last=Pollack |first=Andrew |date=January 16, 1984 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Apple estimated that 80% of its dealers sold IBM and Apple computers, and many visitors disappointed by the PCjr, or curious about the Macintosh, reportedly left with a IIe instead; the latter was so popular that a shortage occurred in early 1984.<ref name=\"maceiie19840409\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jC4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA15&pg=PA54#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Apple IIe Sales Surge as IIc is Readied | work=InfoWorld | date=April 9, 1984 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Mace, Scott | pages=54\u201355}}</ref> The US$669 PCjr model compared favorably to a $1,400 IIe also with 64&nbsp;KB and no floppy drive,<ref name=\"pollack19831102\" />{{r|wierzbicki19831219}} but Apple lowered the computer's price<ref name=\"time19840402\" /> as part of a \"Starter System\" with monitor and floppy drive with a price as low as $1,300,{{r|maceiie19840409}} offered a 30% discount to the important education market,{{r|infoworld19831121}} and in April 1984 introduced the [[Apple IIc]], a portable version with a more compact form factor, 128&nbsp;KB of RAM, and a floppy drive. Although the PCjr's CPU is superior, the IIc\u2014which Apple did not describe as a home computer, to avoid the \"game machine\" connotation\u2014has an excellent keyboard and is compatible with the Apple II's thousands of programs.<ref name=\"winter19840424\">{{cite news | url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1984/04/24/page/37/article/apple-aiming-to-take-bite-out-of-ibm | title=Apple aiming to take bite out of IBM | work=Chicago Tribune | date=April 24, 1984 | accessdate=April 29, 2015 | author=Winter, Christine | pages=Section 3, Page 1}}</ref>{{r|sanger19840517}}<ref name=\"miller198407\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n7/116_Apple_announces_the_IIc.php | title=Apple announces the IIc | accessdate=March 17, 2011 | author=Miller, George A. | date=July 1984 | work=Creative Computing | pages=116}}</ref><ref name=\"ah08\">{{cite web | url=http://apple2history.org/history/ah08/ | title=The Apple IIc | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | work=Apple II History| date=June 23, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"hayes19840424\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/24/business/apple-is-banking-on-new-portable-the-iic-computer.html | title=Apple is Banking on New Portable: The IIc Computer | work=The New York Times | date=April 24, 1984 | accessdate=January 5, 2015 | author=Hayes, Thomas C.}}</ref> A dealer stated that Apple \"very neatly bracketed the PCjr\", and the IIc and IIe's good sales compared to the PCjr implied that cost was not the latter's only problem.{{r|sanger19840517}}\n\n====Not fully PC compatible====\n{{rquote|right|The PCjr cannot be used for serious business computing.|''The New York Times'', 1983{{r|pollack19831102}}}}\n\n{{rquote|right|The PCjr is a failure as a game machine.|''InfoWorld'', 1984{{r|lima19841203}}}}\n\nBy early 1984, PC compatibility was vital for any new non-Apple computer's success. ''InfoWorld''{{'}}s Clapp suggested that were [[Cray]] to introduce an incredibly sophisticated, shirt pocket-sized computer, \"what's the first question that the computer community asks? [[Influence of the IBM PC on the personal computer market#\"Is it PC compatible?\"|'Is it PC compatible?']]\"<ref name=\"clapp19840227\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gy4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA15&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=PC compatibility | work=InfoWorld | date=February 27, 1984 | accessdate=January 18, 2015 | author=Clapp, Doug | pages=22}}</ref>\n\n\"IBM had given us a machine for little kids that also runs some grown-up programs\", Levy wrote.{{r|levy198501}} Unfamiliar with the  consumer market IBM expected that most customers would be new to computers, but 75% were familiar with computers and wanted to run business software on the PCjr.{{r|sanger19850707}} An important market was executives who took data home to work on applications such as the spreadsheet [[Lotus 1-2-3]], and many customers visited stores believing that the PCjr could run most PC software;{{r|marcom19840222}}{{r|time19840402}}{{r|sanger19840517}}{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|gantz19831128}} they compared it\u2014which the ''Times'' warned \"cannot be used for serious business computing\"{{r|pollack19831102}}\u2014unfavorably to the PC instead of other home computers.<ref name=\"sanger19850118\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/01/18/business/computer-giant-finds-problems-in-success.html?pagewanted=all | title=Computer Giant Finds Problems in Success | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Sanger, David E. | date=January 18, 1985 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nPeanut had been rumored to be fully PC compatible.{{r|greenwald19830711}} Norton estimated that the PCjr had about 85% of the PC's capability for a smaller fraction of its price.<ref name=\"norton19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA109#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=The Two Faces of PCjr | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=109}}</ref> IBM technical documentation stated that the \"PCjr is a different computer than the PC\", but \"has a high level of programming compatibility\". The documentation also promised software developers that \"if your application maintains an interface ... at the BIOS and DOS interrupt interfaces, then all hardware differences are handled transparently to your application\".<ref name=\"ibm198311\">{{cite book | title=IBM Personal Computer PCjr Hardware Reference Library / Technical Reference | publisher=IBM | url=https://archive.org/stream/IbmPcjrTechnicalReference#page/n317/mode/2up | year=1983 | pages=4\u20131 to 4\u201311}}</ref> Norton expected that \"any program that followed a design guideline of 64&nbsp;KB and one disk drive is likely to run beautifully on the PCjr. That means that the PCjr will run most of the PC's programs nicely\".{{r|norton19840124}} He warned that developers \"must understand the PCjr's basic limitations and promise not to cheat\", however, and predicted that applications that required more than 128&nbsp;KB of memory, did not support using only one disk drive, or used IBM PC-specific [[copy protection]], would have problems.<ref name=\"pcnortonpcjrport\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA144#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Developing PCjr Software | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=144}}</ref>\n\nThousands of PC applications did require more than 128K of memory{{r|diamond19840801}} and one disk drive.{{r|esd19831227}}{{r|levy198501}} The PCjr was incompatible with about 60% of software, including the popular word-processing program [[WordStar]] and Lotus 1-2-3,<ref name=\"time19840402\" /><ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" /> often used to test PC compatibility;<ref name=\"alsop19940131\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AzsEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PT1&dq=%22flight%20simulator%22&pg=PT1#v=onepage&q=%22flight%20simulator%22&f=false | title=A public Windows pane to make compatibility clearer | accessdate=February 28, 2011 | author=Alsop, Stewart | date=January 31, 1994 | work=InfoWorld | pages=102}}</ref><ref name=shea19840312>{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=li4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA38&pg=PA37#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=PCjr users wait for packages | accessdate=February 24, 2011 | author=Shea, Tom | date=March 12, 1984 | work=InfoWorld | pages=37\u201339}}</ref><ref name=\"trivette198504\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue59/review_lotus_123.php | title=Lotus 1-2-3 For IBM PCjr | work=Compute! | date=April 1985 | accessdate=October 6, 2013 | author=Trivette, Donald B. | pages=63}}</ref> even IBM DisplayWrite requires a separate PCjr version.<ref name=\"dickinsondw19840918\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pq3POofPsBEC&lpg=PA62&pg=PA248#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=IBM's Displaywriter Begets a Family of PC Software | work=PC | date=September 18, 1984 | accessdate=January 29, 2015 | author=Dickinson, John | pages=238}}</ref> The limitations made the computer unsuitable for taking work home;{{r|levy198501}} although 1-2-3 was so important that ''InfoWorld'' joked that \"PC compatible\" really meant \"1-2-3 compatible\",{{r|clapp19840227}} a PCjr version did not become available until a year after the computer's announcement.{{r|trivette198504}} IBM's own stores had a list of software they distributed that was compatible with the PCjr, but customers had to, the ''Chicago Tribune'' reported, learn from \"trial and error\".{{r|winter19840424}}\n\nLevy observed that unlike most good computers, PCjr did not have a killer app.{{r|levy198501}} An analyst stated that its incompatibility with PC software made the PCjr akin to a game machine, benefiting Apple,{{r|hayes19840424}} but ''InfoWorld'' stated that compared to Apples it \"is a failure as a game machine\" because of poor performance with arcade games.{{r|lima19841203}} Apple satirized IBM's Tramp mascot in a commercial that emphasized the IIc's larger software library.{{r|papson1990}}<ref name=\"IIcAd\">{{cite AV media | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DywV6FogNsA | title=Apple IIc versus IBM PCjr commercial | publisher=YouTube | date=June 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====Limited hardware expansion====\nComputer dealers quickly identified the PCjr's limited hardware expansion capability as another major disadvantage.<ref name=\"zientara19840409\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jC4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA15&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=PCjr sales below expectations, dealers say | accessdate=April 3, 2011 | work=InfoWorld | author=Zientara, Marguerite | date=April 9, 1984 | publisher=IDG}}</ref>{{r|time19840402}} Spinnaker expected to sell most PCjr programs on disk because of cartridges' small storage capacity;{{r|cook19840306}} the PCjr version of Lotus 1-2-3 requires two cartridges and a floppy disk, and a 128&nbsp;KB model running it does not have enough memory for many business spreadsheets.{{r|trivette198504}} The computer only has an internal slot for a modem and an external slot on the right side for \"sidecar\" peripherals. IBM published technical details for the PCjr as it had done for the IBM PC to encourage third parties to develop accessories, but did not offer a second floppy drive, hard drive,{{r|wp19831106}}<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /> or memory beyond 128&nbsp;KB{{r|hoffmann198403}} although many customers preferred to use IBM peripherals.{{r|halfhill198410}} Multiple sidecars are very clumsy, and the computer requires additional power supplies with a second floppy drive or more than one sidecar. IBM advised against adding more than four sidecars.<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /><ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" />{{r|levy198501}} The PCjr also lacks a DMA controller, so the 8088 CPU has to service standard system interrupts such as the serial port or the keyboard directly. The PCjr thus cannot use modems faster than 2400 baud, and it refuses to process keyboard input if its buffer is full or while the disk drive is in use.<ref name=\"hoffmann198403\">{{cite web | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n3/74_IBM_PCjr.php | title=IBM PCjr | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Hoffmann, Thomas V. | date=March 1984 | work=Creative Computing | pages=74}}</ref>{{r|levy198501}}{{r|manes19850528}}\n\n===The \"Save-the-Junior campaign\"===\n{{rquote|right|I want an Apple.|Child demonstrating PCjr at IBM event, when asked what computer she wanted for Christmas.<ref name=\"diamond19840801\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/01/business/ibm-raises-dividend-offers-a-free-keyboard.html | title=I.B.M. Raises Dividend, Offers a Free Keyboard | work=The New York Times | date=1984-08-01 | accessdate=4 February 2015 | author=Diamond, Stuart}}</ref>}}\n\nBy mid-1984, the PCjr had experienced months of bad publicity, and dealers were panicking.{{r|mccarroll19841224}} Sales were poor and falling each month before rising slightly with the June discounts; each dealer sold an average of 15 units total in the first half of the year.{{r|bulman19841105}} Levy described it as \"the biggest flop in the history of computing\". Sierra's Williams told him that his company \"was taking a bath on\" PCjr software; \"'The machine is a turkey', he said\".<ref name=levy198501>{{Cite magazine |last=Levy |first=Steven |date=January 1985 |title=The Life and Times of PC junior |url=https://archive.org/details/popular-computing-1985-01/page/n94/mode/2up/search/smell |magazine=Popular Computing |page=92 |access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Apple sold almost as many IIc computers on its first day as PCjr since introduction.{{r|levy198501}} Observers believed that it was doomed; no company had ever succeeded in improving early poor sales of a personal computer.<ref name=\"bulman19841105\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31277231/fort_lauderdale_news/ |title=Big time: IBM skillfully revives lackluster sales of PCjr |last=Bulman |first=Philip |date=1984-11-05 |work=Fort Lauderdale News |access-date=2019-05-05 |page=47 |language=en}}</ref> \"The machine has the smell of death about it\", Levy said.{{r|levy198501}}\n\n[[Don Estridge]] in April said \"The only people who don't like [the keyboard] are writers, and they are the only ones who write about it\",{{r|sanger19840422}}{{r|levy198501}} but on 31 July his company announced that it would replace customers' chiclet keyboards for free with a new model with conventional typewriter keys. Although IBM attempted to hide the decision at the end of a press conference about an educational program for schools,{{r|levy198501}} the press focused on the new keyboard. The act surprised observers by being unusually generous even for IBM\u2014with a reputation for excellent customer service\u2014and the industry;{{r|halfhill198410}}<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" /><ref name=\"lima19841203\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qS4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA60&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=New PC Jr | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Lima, Tony | date=December 3, 1984 | work=InfoWorld | pages=60\u201361}}</ref> ''[[Creative Computing]]'' compared it to an auto maker sending four new free tires to customers,{{r|sandler198411}} and the ''Times'' favorably compared the free keyboard to Apple charging $995 for upgrading the Macintosh to [[Macintosh 512K|512K]].<ref name=\"esd19850319\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/19/science/personal-computers-apple-might-learn-a-thing-or-two-from-ibm.html |title=Apple Might Learn a Thing or Two from I.B.M. |last=Sandberg-Diment |first=Erik |date=1985-03-19 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-07-03 |page=C4 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By replacing the keyboards IBM also acknowledged its initial mistake;{{r|halfhill198410}} other than the keycaps the two designs are identical, so the company could have released the conventional one with the PCjr.{{r|nichols20140322}} The new keyboards cost US$50 each but IBM had to replace only about 60,000 to 75,000, compared to the 250,000 to 480,000 computers that experts had estimated the company would sell during the first six months.{{r|diamond19840801}}{{r|halfhill198410}}<ref name=\"fastie198502\">{{Cite magazine |last=Fastie |first=Will |date=February 1985 |title=An old friend takes a hard look at the IBM product line. |url=https://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v11n2/150_IBM_images_an_old_friend.php |department=IBM Images |magazine=Creative Computing |page=150 |access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 1984 IBM began a massive advertising campaign through the end of the year.{{r|bulman19841105}} It reduced the PCjr's list price, offering a US$999 package that was arguably superior to the comparably priced IIe and IIc, and introduced new IBM-made memory expansion options to 512&nbsp;KB.<ref name=\"halfhill198410\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue53/020_1_IBMs_New_Improved_PCjr.php | title=IBM's New & Improved PCjr | accessdate=February 24, 2011 | author=Halfhill, Tom R. | date=October 1984 | work=Compute! | pages=50}}</ref> As part of $32.5 million in advertising for the computer during 1984,<ref name=\"shiver19850926\">{{Cite news |title=Advertising Age Report Spending by Top 100 U.S. Advertisers Up 16% in '84 |last=Shiver |first=Jube Jr. |date=September 26, 1985 |work=Los Angeles Times |page=2}}</ref> it began what the company described as the most extensive marketing campaign in IBM history, in which 98% of Americans would see at least 30 PCjr advertisements in the last four months of the year. Three simultaneous [[bundled software]] promotions, a sweepstakes with [[Procter & Gamble]], and direct mail to more than 10 million people marketed the redesigned computer,<ref name=\"sandler198411\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n11/298_IBM_colossus_of_Armonk.php | title=IBM: Colossus of Armonk | work=Creative Computing | date=November 1984 | accessdate=February 26, 2013 | author=Sandler, Corey | pages=298}}</ref>{{r|rosch19841113}} while deemphasizing the PCjr's role as a home computer and emphasizing PC compatibility.{{r|halfhill198410}}{{r|levy198501}} Advertisements listed the new price, \"new typewriter-style keyboard\", standard 128&nbsp;KB of memory and expansion options, the PCjr version of 1-2-3, and the ability to \"run over a thousand of the most popular programs written for the IBM PC\".<ref name=\"ibm198412\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mF8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA47&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Now picture this. | work=Black Enterprise | date=December 1984 | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | pages=47 | type=advertisement}}</ref> A $500 rebate to dealers let them include a free color monitor with the discounted PCjr.{{r|fastie198502}}{{r|winter19850324}}\n\nDespite widespread skepticism,<ref name=\"dudek19841002\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d-tPdHcBE9wC&lpg=PA346&pg=PA35#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Is jr 'Likely to Succeed'? Friends Gloat, Foes Groan | work=PC Magazine | author=Dudek, Virginia | date=October 2, 1984 | accessdate=October 25, 2013 | pages=35}}</ref> what observers called the \"Save-the-Junior campaign\"{{r|rosch19841113}} succeeded, amazing the industry. Sales rose every month from June (1.9 units sold per store) to September (4.2);{{r|bulman19841105}} many dealers reported selling more in the weeks following the changes than in the previous seven months.<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" /><ref name=\"sanger19841115\">{{cite news\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/11/15/business/at-computer-show-many-retrenching.html\n | title=At Computer Show, Many Retrenching\n | work=The New York Times\n | date=November 15, 1984\n | accessdate=October 24, 2013\n | author=Sanger, David E.\n}}</ref>{{r|rosch19841113}} One large dealer stated in November 1984 that \"it could be a PCjr Christmas\".{{r|mccarroll19841224}} The more expensive model now cost the $800 to $900 that Spinnaker had expected.{{r|ap19850321}} With the new hardware options and lower prices consumers could buy a PCjr for $1,000 less than a comparable PC.{{r|diamond19840801}}{{r|halfhill198410}} The PCjr reportedly became the best-selling computer,<ref name=\"kennedy19850514\">{{Cite news |last=Kennedy, Don |title=Junior Axed By IBM |date=May 14, 1985 |work=PC |pages=33}}</ref> outselling the IIe and IIc by four to one in some stores{{r|fastie198502}}<ref name=\"machrone19850402\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w1aA2lOwdNIC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=PCjr Renaissance | work=PC Magazine | date=April 2, 1985 | accessdate=October 28, 2013 | author=Machrone, Bill | pages=81}}</ref> and even the C64.{{r|mccarroll19841224}} As sales reached an estimated 50 per store in December{{r|pollack19850320}} dealers increased inventories,{{r|ap19850321}} and Tecmar resumed production of PCjr peripherals after retailers suddenly ordered its millions of dollars of unwanted products.<ref name=\"rosch19841113\">{{Cite news |last=Rosch, Winn L. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ukz6hjZEA4C&lpg=PA33&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=true |title=Jr's Growth Spurts Sales |date=November 13, 1984 |work=PC |access-date=2020-03-15 |pages=33, 35}}</ref>\n\n===Discontinuation===\n{{rquote|right|We're just sitting here trying to put our PCjrs in a pile and burn them. And the damned things don't burn. That's the only thing IBM did right with the machine\u2014they made it flame-proof.|William H. Bowman, Chairman of PCjr software company [[Spinnaker Software|Spinnaker]], March 1985<ref name=\"bowman19850611\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZFw924nLBSoC&lpg=PA86&pg=PA59#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Burn Baby Burn, Says PCjr Software Maker | work=PC Magazine | date=1985-06-11 | accessdate=28 October 2013 | pages=59}}</ref>}}\n\nBy January 1985 experts estimated that IBM had sold 240-275,000 PCjrs, including 200,000 in the fourth quarter of 1984. When the discounts ended, however, sales decreased to 2.4 units in February{{r|kennedy19850514}}<ref name=\"pollack19850320\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/20/business/ibm-drops-pcjr-production.html | title=I.B.M. Drops PCjr Production | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Pollack, Andrew | date=March 20, 1985 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{r|time19850401}}\u2014compared to 4.0 units in February 1984{{r|bulman19841105}}\u2014with large unsold inventories.{{r|ap19850321}} By this time three PCjr-specific magazines had ended publication;{{r|bartimo19841210}} [[ABC Publishing]] reportedly lost $100,000 or more on its magazine.<ref name=\"tuller19861116\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/16/business/abc-s-axe-wielding-publisher-robert-g-burton-championing-print-in-a-tv-world.html?pagewanted=all |title=ABC'S AXE-WIELDING PUBLISHER: ROBERT G. BURTON; Championing Print in a TV World |last=Tuller |first=David |date=November 16, 1986 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> IBM was unable to meet the demand for its new [[PC AT]] business microcomputer, but the home-computer market was in decline{{r|sanger19850118}}{{r|time19850401}} and the company was likely unable to make a sufficient profit when selling the PCjr at a discount.{{r|pollack19850120}}{{r|pollack19850320}}{{r|ap19850321}}{{r|time19850401}}\n\nIBM discontinued the PCjr on March 19, 1985, stating that \"The home market didn't expand to the degree I.B.M. and many observers thought it would\". The surprise decision{{r|pollack19850320}}<ref name=\"time19850401\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,964850,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625185216/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C964850%2C00.html |archive-date=June 25, 2009 |title=Kicking Junior Out of the Family |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=Castro, Janice |author2=Bob Buderi |author3=Thomas McCarroll |date=April 1, 1985 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> by CEO [[John Akers]] himself{{r|sanger19850707}} astounded Sierra and others, some of which only made PCjr products.{{r|kennedy19850514}} Rumored to have 100,000 to 400,000 unsold PCjrs{{r|kennedy19850514}}<ref name=\"steele19850709\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SprPDrQRvM8C&lpg=PA51&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=COMDEX: Nothing New Under the Georgia Sun | work=PC Magazine | date=July 9, 1985 | accessdate=October 28, 2013 | author=Steele, William | pages=34}}</ref>{{r|mintzer19860114}} despite not having ordered new microprocessors from Intel since summer 1984,<ref name=\"iw19850415\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zC4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA13&ots=a_Fs_n1Np8&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Death of the PCjr: Insiders Foresaw It | work=InfoWorld | date=April 15, 1985 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | pages=13 | editor=McCarthy, Michael}}</ref> the company offered large discounts to its employees<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/09/19/business/ibm-offers-a-pcjr-deal.html | title=I.B.M. Offers a PCjr Deal | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | date=September 19, 1985 | work=The New York Times}}</ref> and consumers. Inventory remained through Christmas 1985, and IBM used discounts and radio and full-page print ads for the computer;<ref name=\"mintzer19860114\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hoPbDSDNLTQC&lpg=PA75&pg=PA75#v=onepage&f=false | title=News in Brief | work=PC | date=January 14, 1986 | accessdate=January 21, 2015 | pages=38 | editor=Mintzer, Jane}}</ref> one industry executive stated that \"only the unaware purchaser would be liable to pick that thing up\".<ref name=\"mace19851202\">{{cite news|last=Mace|first=Scott|title=Christmas Contenders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=My8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA28&dq=mecc&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q=mecc&f=false|accessdate=January 22, 2011|newspaper=InfoWorld|date=December 2, 1985}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{rquote|right|It will never happen again.|IBM engineer, 1985{{r|strehlo19850617}}}}\n\nThe press widely covered the first public failure of the world's most profitable company.{{r|sanger19850707}} Although PCjr had little effect on its $46 billion in 1984 revenue, discontinuing such a prominent product embarrassed IBM.{{r|ap19850321}} The failure was so great that the ''Chicago Tribune'' later compared PCjr to that of the Edsel and [[New Coke]],<ref name=\"lynch19901026\">{{cite news | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-26/entertainment/9003300627_1_ibm-ps-prodigy-software-microsoft-works | title=The Pros, Cons Of Buying An IBM PS/1 | work=Chicago Tribune | date=October 26, 1990 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Lynch, Dennis}}</ref> and IBM reportedly created a '''Chiclet rule''', requiring [[human factors]] testing for future products.<ref name=\"strehlo19850617\">{{cite news\n | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA8&pg=PA8#v=onepage&f=false\n | title=The Chiclet Rule and the Green Dragon\n | work=InfoWorld\n | date=June 17, 1985\n | accessdate=May 31, 2016\n | author=Strehlo, Kevin\n | quote=\"\n | page=8}}</ref>\n\nSome observers believed that IBM's bureaucratic culture, so different from that of the less-rigid Boca Raton division that created the PC, had caused PCjr to fail; others thought that the absence of IBM's cautious and thorough bureaucrats had caused the failure. Estridge said \"It turned out that we had it all wrong\" by expecting that first-time computer users would buy PCjr.{{r|sanger19850707}} Spinnaker's Bowman said \"IBM didn't talk to anybody when they designed this product. They tried to enter a market segment without knowing anything about the customers\".{{r|ap19850321}} Even PCjr's end surprised the company. When it announced the discontinuation IBM promised to continue to support the computer, as it did with mainframes. The press criticized the company, however, for orphaning the product. Executives admitted that the reaction was another example of IBM not understanding the consumer market.{{r|sanger19850707}}\n\n[[Sell-side analyst]] Barbara Isgur correctly predicted in 1984 that the PCjr \"will probably establish the standard operating system for the home market as it has in business. So even if the PCjrs have gone into the closet, I think that as the software continues to evolve and increase, they will be brought out\".<ref name=\"uston198403\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n3/18_Barbara_Isgur_talks_to_Ke.php | title=Barbara Isgur talks to Ken Uston; an industry analyst speaks out. | work=Creative Computing | date=Mar 1984 | accessdate=January 5, 2015 | author=Uston, Ken | pages=18}}</ref>{{r|loguidice2014}} [[Tandy Corporation]] released a clone, the [[Tandy 1000]], in November 1984,<ref name=\"infoworld19850121\">{{cite magazine | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9y4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=%22tandy+1000%22&hl=en&ei=bTdrTeuLIITmsQPlx8SmBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=48&ved=0COwBEOgBMC84ZA#v=onepage&q=%22tandy%201000%22&f=false | title=BRIEFS | accessdate=February 27, 2011 | date=February 12, 1985 | magazine=InfoWorld | pages=23}}</ref> describing it as \"what the PCjr should have been\".<ref name=\"bartimo19850311\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5C4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA28&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Tandy Revamps Product Line | work=InfoWorld | date=March 11, 1985 | accessdate=January 21, 2015 | author=Bartimo, Jim | pages=28\u201329}}</ref> After its discontinuation Tandy quickly removed any mention of the PCjr in advertising while emphasizing the {{Not a typo|1000's}} PC compatibility. The machine and its many successors sold well, unlike the PCjr, partly because the Tandy 1000 was sold in ubiquitous [[Radio Shack]] stores and partly because it was less costly, easier to expand, and almost entirely compatible with the IBM PC. The PCjr's enhanced graphics and sound standards became known as \"[[Tandy Graphics Adapter|Tandy-compatible]]\", and many PC games advertised their Tandy support. A company developed a PCjr modification that made it compatible with Tandy software.<ref name=\"loguidice2014\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=wZnpAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA97&pg=PA96#v=onepage&f=false | title=Vintage Game Consoles: An Inside Look at Apple, Atari, Commodore, Nintendo, and the Greatest Gaming Platforms of All Time | publisher=CRC Press |author1=Loguidice, Bill |author2=Barton, Matt | year=2014 | pages=95\u201397 | isbn=978-1135006518}}</ref>\n\n\"[The PCjr] was a nice enough machine, a little underpowered for its price, but not fatally flawed. Its cardinal sin\", ''PC Magazine'' concluded in late 1985, \"was that it wasn't PC compatible\".<ref name=\"machrone19851126\">{{cite magazine | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VUKL2rKYb8UC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA59#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Compatibility Wars\u2014Here and Abroad |magazine=PC Magazine | date=November 26, 1985 | accessdate=October 29, 2013 | author=Machrone, Bill |page=59}}</ref> From mid-1985, what ''Compute!'' described as a \"wave\" of inexpensive clones from American and Asian companies caused prices to decline; by the end of 1986, the equivalent to a US$1,600 real IBM PC with 256&nbsp;KB RAM and two disk drives cost as little as $600, lower than the price of the Apple IIc. Consumers began purchasing DOS computers for the home in large numbers; Radio Shack estimated that half of Tandy 1000 sales went to homes, not offices. The inexpensive clones succeeded with consumers where the PCjr had failed; unlike the IBM product, they were as fast as or faster than the IBM PC and highly compatible.<ref name=\"halfhill198612\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1986-12-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_079_1986_Dec#page/n33/mode/2up | title=The MS-DOS Invasion / IBM Compatibles Are Coming Home | work=Compute! | date=December 1986 | accessdate=November 9, 2013 | author=Halfhill, Tom R. | pages=32}}</ref>\n\nSeveral upgrades for the PCjr were designed by IBM/Teledyne but never reached the store shelves before the IBM PCjr was canceled. These included a wireless joystick and various memory/drive upgrades. PC Enterprises became the last of the major third party vendors to supply full service, parts, and add-ons, extending the functional life of the PCjr to about 10 years, often buying out inventory and rights for PCjr support.\n\nOther manufacturers provided support items for PCjr fans, such as hard drive attachments and specialized sidecars that the user could use to enhance the system. The PCjr was able to run other software designed for the PC, such as word processor, database and spreadsheet programs ran well on the PCjr with 128K of memory. When fully expanded to over 600K memory, the PCjr would run all IBM PC software.<ref>http://oldcomputers.net/ibm-pcjr.html see the comments.</ref>\n\n\nIBM returned to the home market in 1990 with the [[IBM PS/1|PS/1]]. Unlike the PCjr, the PS/1 offered full PC compatibility, a low price, and a conventional keyboard.{{r|lynch19901026}}\n\n==Technical specifications==\n* '''CPU:''' [[Intel 8088]], 4.77&nbsp;MHz\n* '''Memory:''' 64&nbsp;KB on the motherboard, expandable to 128&nbsp;KB via a card in a dedicated slot. Further expansion via IBM sidecar adapters. Later third-party add-ons and modifications raised the limit to 736&nbsp;KB.\n* '''Operating system:''' IBM [[PC DOS]] 2.10 (Boots to Cassette BASIC without cartridge or DOS){{r|levy198501}}\n* '''Input/Output:''' cassette port, light-pen port, two joystick ports, [[RGB color model|RGB]] monitor port, composite video port, television adapter output port, audio port, wired keyboard port, infrared keyboard sensor, serial port, two cartridge slots\n* '''Expandability:''' three internal slots, dedicated to PCjr-specific memory, [[modem]] (300 [[bits per second]] non-[[Hayes command set|Hayes]]-compatible modem available from IBM, although 2400&nbsp;bit/s Hayes-compatible modems were available from third parties), and floppy controller cards. External sidecar connector capable of daisy-chaining multiple sidecars.\n* '''Video:''' [[Motorola]] [[Motorola 6845|6845]], \"[[Color Graphics Adapter|CGA]] Plus\" This chip was officially called the VGA (Video Gate Array<ref name=\"vga\" />).\n** Text modes: 40&times;25, 80&times;25, 16 colors\n** Graphics modes: 320&times;200&times;4, 640&times;200&times;2, 160&times;100&times;16, 160&times;200&times;16, 320&times;200&times;16, 640&times;200&times;4{{r|halfhill198401}} \n** Video memory is shared with the first 128&nbsp;KB of system memory, and can be as small as 2&nbsp;KB and as large as 96&nbsp;KB.\n* '''Sound:''' [[Texas Instruments SN76489|Texas Instruments SN76496]]; three voices, 16 independent volume levels per channel, white noise\n* '''Storage:''' Optional 5.25-inch diskette drive or cassette.  Other storage options were provided by third parties.\n* '''Keyboard:''' 62-key detached.  Corded or infra-red operation.  IBM supplied two different keyboards, the first being the maligned 'Chiclet' keyboard, so named for its square rubber keys that resembled [[Chiclets]].  Many third-party keyboards were also available.\n\n==See also==\n* [[IBM JX]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://weblog.ceicher.com/archives/2002/12/christmas_1984_the_great_apple.html Christmas 1984: The Great Apple //c vs. PCjr Battle]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UrR7asU4aLE IBM PCjr running internal test and printing]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[IBM Personal Computer]] }}\n{{s-ttl|title  = IBM Personal Computers }}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[IBM PS/1]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:8086-based home computers]]\n[[Category:Home computers]]\n[[Category:IBM personal computers|PCjr]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 1984]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Home computer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox information appliance\n| name = IBM PCjr\n| logo = \n| image = Ibm pcjr with display.jpg\n| caption = IBM PCjr with original \"chiclet\" keyboard, PCjr color display, and 64&nbsp;KB memory expansion card\n| developer = \n| manufacturer = [[Teledyne Technologies|Teledyne]], [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]]\n| carrier = \n| family = \n| type = [[Personal computer]]\n| generation = \n| releasedate = {{Start date and100 age|1984|03}}\n| lifespan = \n| price = US$1,269 with 128&nbsp;KB memory and without monitor<!-- this is price at initial release, not the current price.--> (today US$3128.45)<br/> {{nowrap|[[British pound|GBP]]\u00a3800}} {{nowrap|(today \u00a3{{Inflation|GBP|800|1984|r=2}})}} w/o disk drive.<br/>{{nowrap|[[Canadian dollar|CAD]]$1900.00}}\n| discontinued = March 1985\n| unitssold = \n| unitsshipped = 500,000\n| media = \n| os = IBM [[PC DOS]] 2.10<!-- operating system -->\n| power = \n| cpu = [[Intel 8088]] @ 4.77 MHz\n| storage = \n| memory = 64 [[Kilobyte|KB]]\n| display = \n| graphics = [[Video Gate Array]]\n| sound = [[Texas Instruments]] [[SN76489]]\n| input = \n| location = <!-- GPS or Wi-Fi based -->\n| controllers = \n| output = \n| camera = \n| touchpad = \n| connectivity = \n| service = <!-- online service/s offered -->\n| dimensions = \n| weight = \n| topgame = \n| compatibility = \n| predecessor = [[IBM Personal Computer]]\n| successor = [[IBM PS/1]]\n| related = \n| website = \n}}\nThe '''IBM PCjr''' (read \"PC junior\") is a [[home computer]] that was produced and marketed by IBM from March 1984 to May 1985. The PCjr was positioned as a complement to the very successful [[IBM Personal Computer]] (PC), competing with other [[home computer]]s such as the [[Apple II series]] and the [[Commodore 64]]. It retains the IBM PC's [[Intel 8088|8088]] [[CPU]] and [[BIOS]] interface, but provides enhanced graphics and sound capabilities over the original IBM PC, [[ROM cartridge]] slots, joystick ports, and an infrared wireless keyboard. The PCjr supports expansion via \"sidecar\" modules, which are attached to the side of the unit. New software such as ''[[King's Quest I]]'' showcased its [[PC gaming]] capabilities.\n\nDespite widespread anticipation, the PCjr's launch was unsuccessful. IBM's inexperience with the consumer market led to unclear positioning, with analysts believing that IBM was unsuccessful at justifying the PCjr's higher cost in comparison to competitors such as the Commodore 64 and Apple II. It is only partially [[IBM PC compatible|IBM compatible]], so compatibility with existing PC software such as the [[killer app]] [[Lotus 1-2-3]] was not guaranteed. The PCjr's [[chiclet keyboard]] was widely criticized for its poor quality, with critics stating that it was unsuitable for extended use such as word processing. The PCjr's expandability is limited, and it was initially offered with up to 128&nbsp;KB of RAM only, insufficient for many IBM PC programs.\n\nIn 1984, IBM offered free replacement keyboards with a more traditional design, and a new 512&nbsp;KB RAM upgrade. A large advertising campaign promoted the PCjr's compatibility with \"over 1000\" of the most popular IBM PC applications (including a new [[porting|port]] of Lotus 1-2-3), and new discounted pricing and other bundle offers. PCjr sales greatly increased, amazing observers that saw it as a failure.\n\nBy January 1985, when the discounts ended, IBM had sold 250,000 PCjr computers, with 200,000 in the fourth quarter of 1984 alone. Unable to sell the computer without discounts, IBM abruptly discontinued the PCjr in March 1985 and would not produce a home-oriented computer until the [[IBM PS/1|PS/1]] in 1990. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' described the PCjr as \"one of the biggest flops in the history of computing\", with critics comparing it to the [[Edsel|Ford Edsel]] and [[New Coke]]. Inexpensive and almost entirely compatible [[PC clone]]s became popular in 1985 including the [[Tandy 1000]]. The Tandy was much more successful than the PCjr it imitated, and PCjr's enhanced graphics and sound standards became known as \"[[Tandy Graphics Adapter|Tandy-compatible]]\".\n\n==Description==\n\n===Overview===\nAnnounced November 1, 1983, and first shipped in late January 1984,<ref name=\"sanger19840517\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/05/17/business/ibm-s-problems-with-junior.html?pagewanted=all | title=I.B.M.'s Problems with Junior | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Sanger, David E. | date=May 17, 1984 | newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> the PCjr&mdash;nicknamed \"Peanut\" before its debut<ref name=\"time19840402\" />&mdash;came in two models: the '''4860-004''', with 64&nbsp;[[kilobyte|KB]] of memory, priced at US$669 ({{Inflation|US|669|1983|fmt=eq}}); and the '''4860-067''', with 128&nbsp;KB of memory and a 360&nbsp;KB 5.25-inch floppy disk drive, priced at US$1,269 ({{Inflation|US|1269|1983|fmt=eq}}). It was manufactured for IBM in [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]] by [[Teledyne Technologies|Teledyne]]. The PCjr promised a high degree of compatibility with the [[IBM PC]], which was already a popular business computer, in addition to offering built-in color graphics and 3 voice sound that was better than the standard [[PC speaker|PC-speaker]] sound and [[Color Graphics Adapter|color graphics]] of the standard IBM PC and compatibles of the day.  The PCjr was also the first PC compatible machine that was expressly designed to support [[page flipping]] for graphics operations. Since the PCjr uses system [[Random-access memory|RAM]] to store video content, and the location of this storage area can be changed, it can perform flicker-free animation and other effects that are difficult or impossible to produce on contemporary PC clones.\n\n====Video====\nUnlike the standard IBM PC, the PCjr has onboard video hardware. It is an improved subset of the [[Color/Graphics Adapter|CGA]] standard. The four CGA video modes (40x25 text, 80x25 text, 320x200x4, and 640x200x2 graphics) are supported in addition to three new graphics modes (160x200x16, 320x200x16, and 640x200x4). The 80x25 text mode, 320x200x16, and 640x200x4 modes are referred to in IBM's documentation as \"the high bandwidth modes\"; they are not supported on base models with only 64k of memory. The PCjr also has a composite video out and can support artifact colors on a TV or composite monitor much like the CGA cards, although the colors are slightly different. The PCjr also has palette registers which allow the colors to be redefined for any of the available 16\u2014this feature was retained in EGA and VGA cards. When the BIOS is used to set a video mode, it always sets up the PCjr palette table (i.e. the 16 palette registers) to emulate the CGA color palette for that mode.  Programs specifically written to use PCjr graphics can subsequently reprogram the palette table to use any colors desired.  Palette changes must be made during horizontal or vertical blanking periods of a video frame in order to avoid corrupting the display.  However, the provision of a vertical retrace interrupt (on IRQ5) simplifies this and also makes seamless page-flipping much easier. Although standard PC video cards had a flag to indicate that the vertical retrace was in progress, the PCjr added for the first time the ability to generate raster or VBLANK interrupts on IRQ 5. This allows the use of mixed video modes. The PCjr video subsystem also has a little-known graphics blink feature, which toggles the palette between the first and second groups of eight palette registers at the same rate used for the text blink feature, and a palette bit-masking feature that can be used to switch between palette subsets without reprogramming palette registers, by forcing one or more bits of each pixel value to zero before the value is used to look up the color in the palette table.\n\nVideo modes on the PCjr use varying amounts of system memory; 40x25 text mode uses 1k and 320x200x16 and 640x200x4 use 32k. Multiple text or graphics pages can be used as long as there is enough memory for them, thus the two largest modes allow only two graphics pages. The ability to page flip graphics modes answered one of the common criticisms of the CGA card, which had 16k of video memory and only supports multiple pages in text mode. Of the three new modes, 160x200x16 mode has the same layout as CGA graphics modes; the odd and even scanlines are stored in the first and second half of the video buffer, each half being 8k in size, and every four bits represents one pixel. The 320x200x16 and 640x200x4 modes have four blocks of scanlines; every four or two bits respectively represents a pixel.\n\nSince the PCjr uses the main system RAM for the video buffer, less memory is available for software than on a standard PC, which has its video memory in the A000h-BFFFh segments, above conventional memory.\n\n====Software====\nThe register mapping of the PCjr's video hardware is different from the standard CGA card, so software that tries to modify or read registers directly will not work\u2014the PCjr has a \"gate\" register in which the user writes the number of the video register to be accessed, followed by the value to be written into it.  Alteration of other CRTC registers cannot be assumed to produce the same results from the PCjr video system as from the CGA (and might damage the monitor).  (Programs for the CGA that manipulate the CRTC start address and that rely on address wrap-around above address 0xBC000 may not work correctly on the PCjr, because it always has a 32&nbsp;KB contiguous block of RAM in the video area from address 0xB8000 through 0xBFFFF.) The PCjr's video memory cannot be moved above 128k if expansion memory is added; some PC software that ran off of self-booting disks (mainly games) would not work on a PCjr if the software required more than 128k.\n\nPC DOS 2.10 was the minimum version of DOS required for the PCjr; IBM's OEM versions of MS-DOS supported the machine up to DOS 3.30, but memory expansion was required for DOS 3.20 and 3.30.\n\n====Hardware====\nThe PCjr display hardware consists primarily of two chips on the system board: a standard Motorola 6845 CRTC like the one used in the MDA and CGA adapters, and a custom IBM chip called the [[Video Gate Array]] (VGA)<ref name=\"vga\">VGA should not be confused with the later [[Video Graphics Array]] standard that IBM released with the [[PS/2]] line in 1987.</ref>{{r|nortonpcjrvideo19840124}}  The 6845 is responsible for the basic raster timing and video data address sequencing, and the Video Gate Array contains all the additional timing logic, the video data demultiplexing and color processing logic, and the programmable palette table logic, as well as the logic for multiplexing RAM access between the 8088 CPU and the video generation circuitry.  The 6845 CRTC and the VGA together are completely responsible for refreshing the internal DRAM of the PCjr (64 or 128&nbsp;KB), and this complicates the process of switching video modes on the PCjr.  (Resetting the VGA, which must be done during certain video mode switches, must be done by code not running from the internal RAM, and if the CRTC or the VGA is disabled for too long, the contents of the internal RAM can be lost.)  Additional external DRAM, in sidecar expansion modules, is refreshed separately, not by the CRTC and VGA.\n\n[[File:IBM PCB Jr Motherboard.jpg|thumb|IBM PC Jr Motherboard]]\n\n[[File:IBM PCB Jr Internal.jpg|thumb|IBM PC Jr Internal]]\n\n====Sound====\nThe PCjr's sound is provided by a [[Texas Instruments]] [[SN76496]] which can produce three square waves of varying amplitude and frequency along with a noise channel powered by a [[shift register]].<ref name=\"nortonpcjraudio19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Sound Abilities: The PCjr | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=137}}</ref> This device is sometimes also called a PSG (Programmable Sound Generator), and essentially equivalent devices were also used in the contemporary [[Sega Master System]] and the later [[Sega Genesis|Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]]. The PCjr design also allows for an analog sound source in an expansion-bus \"sidecar\" module, and software-controlled internal analog switch can select the source for the sound output from among the PC speaker, the SN76489, the cassette port, or the expansion-bus sound source.  Only one sound source can be selected at a time; the sources cannot be mixed.\n\n====Processor speed====\nThe PCjr's 4.77&nbsp;MHz [[Intel 8088]] [[CPU]] is faster than that of other computers that were aimed at the home market at the time,{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} though the stock PCjr usually does not run at the full rated 4.77&nbsp;MHz because access to the internal RAM is slowed by [[wait state]]s added by the Video Gate Array to synchronize shared access to RAM between the CPU and the video hardware. IBM claimed that an average of two wait states are added, but the designers of the Tandy 1000 claimed that six was a more accurate figure.<ref name=\"vose198412\">{{Cite magazine |last=Vose |first=G. Michael |date=December 1984 |title=The Tandy 1000 |url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1984-12/1984_12_BYTE_09-13_Communications#page/n99/mode/2up |magazine=BYTE |pages=98\u2013104}}</ref> However, this does not apply to programs or data located in ROM, including software on ROM cartridges plugged into the front of the PCjr, or located in additional RAM in a sidecar attachment; it only applies to the first 64 KB or 128 KB of RAM inside the system unit.  Therefore, under some circumstances the 8088 in the PCjr actually can run at the rated 4.77&nbsp;MHz.  The most common instances in which this maximum speed would be achieved are when running games or productivity applications from ROM cartridges; this would be a reason for PCjr users to prefer software in cartridges to software on disk media.  In fact, because the PCjr video subsystem continuously refreshes the system internal DRAM transparently, without disturbing the CPU, programs running from ROM on the PCjr will actually run slightly faster on the PCjr than on an IBM PC or XT.  This is because the PC and XT keep their DRAM refreshed by using a DMA channel to periodically request the bus from the CPU in order to perform a refresh cycle, whereas a program running from ROM on a PCjr will never be suspended for internal DRAM refresh cycles. To increase the system-speed of the IBM PCjr you can install a [[NEC V20]] instead of the 8088.\n\n====Wireless keyboard====\nThe detached wireless infrared keyboard promised a degree of convenience none of its competitors had, eliciting visions of word processing wirelessly from one's [[couch]] with the computer connected to a TV set as a display.{{r|hoffmann198403}}  For infrared wireless operation, it was powered by four common AA cells.  A keyboard cord option, that plugged into the keyboard with a modular 4-position telephone plug and into the back of the computer with a 6-pin (2x3) header connected, was also available for increased security and reliability. The cord also eliminated dependence on batteries; the keyboard IR receiver was automatically disabled when the keyboard cord was attached to the computer.\n\n===Differences from the IBM PC===\nWith a built-in [[RF modulator]], the PCjr can send video and audio to a television receiver; it also has an audio output jack to connect to an amplifier. The PCjr Color Display sold by IBM included an internal amplified speaker, being the only IBM monitor in the PC line to do so. [[IBM BASIC#IBM PCjr Cartridge BASIC|Cartridge BASIC]] enhances the standard IBM BASIC with commands to support the new video and audio functionality.<ref name=\"nortonpcjrvideo19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA128#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Screening the PCjr's Color, Video, And Memory Options | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | access-date=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=128}}</ref>{{r|nortonpcjraudio19840124}} Two joystick ports are also evidence of IBM's goal for marketing the PCjr as a home-friendly machine to compete with popular home machines like the Commodore 64, the Atari home computers, and the Apple II line. Other than the [[Tandy 1000]], which was designed as an enhanced PCjr clone to directly compete with the PCjr, and [[PC1512|Amstrad IBM PC compatible]] lines a few years later, the dual built-in joystick ports introduced by the PCjr never became standard on IBM PC compatibles, and have not been seen since. However, the single 15-pin D-subminiature joystick port common on later PCs supports two two-axis, two-button joysticks like those supported by the PCjr, and the 15-pin port can be split out to two separate joystick ports with a passive Y-adapter cable.\n\nFurther reinforcing the \"home-friendly\" goal, the PCjr also introduced two [[ROM cartridge]] slots on the front of the unit, meant to load software quickly and easily. The cartridges are plugged in from the front, prompting the computer to automatically reboot and run the software. This is more [[Usability|user-friendly]] than other home computer systems, which must be powered off when a cartridge was removed or inserted and come with warnings about damage to the computer if this requirement is ignored. Loading and saving data from cartridge software is possible via the floppy drive. The cartridge BASIC for the PCjr, in particular, gives programmers the advantage of a real programming language always ready without taking up system memory, as it was firmware, with its own address space. Being stored in ROM the BASIC loads very quickly, not needing access to the floppy disk or other storage.\n\nCartridges can also replace the system BIOS and other firmware.<ref name=\"norton19840320\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1tFFnOMCvv4C&lpg=PA477&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Unearthing The PCjr's Secrets | work=PC Magazine | date=March 20, 1984 | access-date=October 24, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=111}}</ref> A number of patches from various vendors are included on a single \"combo-cartridge\", licensed and sold by PC Enterprises, to support add-on hardware, bypass certain limitations of design, and keep up with changing OS requirements.\n\nExpansions (such as additional parallel ports, serial ports, memory, etc.) to the PCjr are provided via add-on [[daisy chain (electrical engineering)|\"sidecars\" that attach to the side of the PCjr]]. Multiple expansions are stacked together, increasing the width of the machine.\n\nThe floppy controller on the PCjr had its I/O registers mapped into different ports than on the PC, since the PCjr also did not have DMA, the BIOS routines for handling floppy access were different and more complex than those on the PC. Software that tried to perform direct, low-level disk access (mainly utilities, but also the occasional game such as ''Dunzhin: Warrior of Ras'') would not work unless it was rewritten for the PCjr.\n\nThe internal floppy drive on the PCjr was a half-height [[Qume]] 5.25\" unit; IBM also used these drives in the PC Portable, but the PCjr units were specially equipped with a small fan to prevent overheating since the computer did not have a case fan.\n\nThe PCjr's video uses 32&nbsp;kB of RAM as [[shared graphics memory]], which prevents using additional memory with the built-in 128&nbsp;KB under DOS.{{r|norton19840320}}  The specific issue is that while additional external RAM can be added directly above the internal RAM, making a [[flat memory model|flat model]], if the display is used, its buffer must reside somewhere within the first 128&nbsp;KB of RAM (from where it is mirrored at address 0xB8000).  Stock MS-DOS is not prepared to work around the video buffer in low RAM, using RAM both below and above it.  Two obvious solutions exist: Use the additional memory as a [[RAM drive]], or not use the built-in 128&nbsp;KB.<ref name=\"norton19840626\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IGkuDrOYjOcC&lpg=PA407&pg=PA98#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Adding to Junior's Memory | work=PC Magazine | date=June 26, 1984 | access-date=October 24, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=98}}</ref>  Another option would be to load a special DOS device driver or TSR, which would claim the RAM selected for use as the video buffer, causing DOS to load other drivers and programs above it.  A fourth option would be not to use MS-DOS, or to use a specially modified version of it.  For programs running from ROM cartridges, not using DOS was a very viable option, even in the mid-1980s when the PCjr was being marketed.\n[[File:IBM PC Jr BASIC Cartridge.jpg|thumb|IBM PC Jr BASIC Cartridge]]\n\n===Differences from other personal computers===\nThe PCjr initially shipped with a wireless [[chiclet keyboard]] called the \"Freeboard\",<ref name=\"halfhill198410\"/> powered by four AA batteries to provide infrared line-of-sight wireless communication. The keycaps are blank; labels appear between keys to permit [[Keyboard layout|overlays]].{{r|halfhill198401}} The chiclet keyboard was unpopular, and IBM replaced it with a model with typewriter keycaps.{{r|halfhill198410}} With 62 keys compared to the PC's 83, [[function keys]] and others need multiple keystrokes.{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|halfhill198401}} Certain room lights cause interference with the infrared keyboard sensor,<ref name=\"nichols20140322\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2014/03/22/ibm_pcjr_stripped_bare_still_mediocre_after_all_these_years/ | title=IBM PCjr STRIPPED BARE: We tear down the machine Big Blue would rather you forgot | website=The Register | date=March 22, 2014 | accessdate=April 1, 2014 | author=Nichols, Shaun}}</ref> as do multiple nearby keyboards.<ref name=\"lgr20110117\">{{cite AV media | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MbSto9irCoE | title=LGR - Experiencing The IBM PCjr Chiclet Keyboard | publisher=YouTube | date=January 17, 2011 | people=Lazy Game Reviews}}</ref> As mentioned previously, the keyboard can also operate with an optional [[modular connector|modular]] telephone-style cable, eliminating battery usage and IR interference.\n\nThe PCjr also has a [[light pen]] port. Besides being used for a light pen (a rarely purchased option), this port was used in combination with the serial port to supply voltage to a [[Mouse Systems]] optical mouse of the same design as those for [[Sun Microsystems|Sun workstations]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:PCjr.twinSCSI.jpg|thumb|A PCjr featuring most upgrades available from PC Enterprises, including combo cartridge, dual floppies, twin ST-225 HDDs (bootable via Future Domain firmware hidden under cover on right). Replacement keyboard sits on top of the Taxan RGB monitor. System is showing \"Battlechess\".]]\n\n===\"Peanut Panic\"===\n{{rquote|right|For my grandmother, and for millions of people like her, ''IBM '' and ''computer'' are synonymous.|''InfoWorld'', 1982<ref name=\"zussman19820823\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VDAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA19&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Let's keep those systems open | work=InfoWorld | date=1982-08-23 | accessdate=29 January 2015 | author=Zussman, John Unger | pages=29}}</ref>}}\n\nIBM in the early 1980s was the world's largest computer company, with 70% of the [[mainframe computer|mainframe]] market. When it introduced the IBM PC in August 1981, IBM did so as an experiment to defend against [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and others' newly popular microcomputers. While observers expected the PC to succeed, not even IBM executives expected it to become so popular so quickly. Within two years the PC created a large new ecosystem of business computers and software. It became a market leader<ref name=\"pollack19830327\">{{Cite news |last=Pollack |first=Andrew |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/03/27/business/big-ibm-has-done-it-again.html |title=Big I.B.M. Has Done It Again |date=1983-03-27 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-16 |page=Section 3, Page 1 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{r|ap19831102}}{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|time19831107}} with 26% of all microcomputers sold in 1983, in second place to the much less expensive [[Commodore 64]] (C64) and three times the [[Apple II]]'s share.<ref name=\"reimer20091102\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jeremyreimer.com/postman/node/329 | title=Total Share: Personal Computer Market Share 1975\u20132005 | accessdate=March 15, 2011 | author=Reimer, Jeremy | date=November 2, 2009 | publisher=Jeremy Reimer's Blog}}</ref>\n\nFor a year before the PCjr's announcement, the computer industry discussed rumors of a new IBM product, code named \"Peanut\", that would repeat the PC's success. The rumors described Peanut as a home computer with 64&nbsp;KB of memory that would be [[IBM PC compatible]], benefit from IBM's service network and, at US$600 to $1,000, less expensive than the [[Apple IIe]]. Customers visited stores attempting to buy the product, and rivals' revenue, product plans, and share prices reacted to the officially nonexistent computer in what the press called \"Peanut Panic\" or \"The Great Peanut Roast\".{{r|pollack19830327}}{{r|pollack19830619}}<ref name=\"greenwald19830711\">{{Cite magazine |last=Greenwald |first=John |date=1983-07-11 |title=The Colossus That Works |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,949693-2,00.html |url-status=live |url-access=subscription | magazine=TIME |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514004334/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,949693-2,00.html |archive-date=2008-05-14 |access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>{{r|coleco19830928}}{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"lock198312\">{{Cite magazine |last=Lock |first=Robert |date=December 1983 |title=Editor's Notes |url=https://archive.org/stream/1983-12-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_043_1983_Dec#page/n7/mode/2up |magazine=Compute! |page=6}}</ref><ref name=\"ruby198402\" /><ref name=\"infoworld19831121\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA19&dq=ibm%20peanut&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q=ibm%20peanut&f=false | title=Industry reacts to PCjr | accessdate=February 25, 2011 |author1=Mace, Scott |author2=Paul Freiberger | date=November 21, 1983 | pages=21\u201322 | work=InfoWorld}}</ref><ref name=\"springer198401\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/ahoy-magazine-01/Ahoy_01_January_1984#page/n37/mode/2up | title=Can the 64 Crack the Peanut? | work=Ahoy! | date=January 1984 | accessdate=October 16, 2013 | author=Springer, Steve | pages=39}}</ref>{{r|pollack19830619}}{{r|halfhill198401}}{{r|burton198303}}<ref name=\"gantz19831114\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA110#v=onepage&f=false | title=Heard On Tech Street | work=InfoWorld | date=November 14, 1983 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Gantz, John | pages=110}}</ref>{{r|levy198501}}\n\nMany expected, or feared, that an IBM home computer would destroy Apple, Commodore, and others, leaving no competitors. By November 1983, Peanut allegedly would cost $600-700 with the [[Motorola 68000]] or other powerful CPU, two {{frac|3|1|2}} inch disk drives, and sophisticated graphics.{{r|levy198501}} While the company repeatedly denied rumors<ref name=\"byte198311\">{{cite news|author=Curran, Lawrence J.|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1983-11/1983_11_BYTE_08-11_Inside_the_IBM_PC#page/n89/mode/2up|title=IBM's Estridge|date=November 1983|work=BYTE|accessdate=March 19, 2016|url-status=live|last2=Shuford, Richard S.|pages=88\u201397}}</ref>{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"maceiie19840409\"/>{{r|time19850401}} it estimated that 50 to 70% of PCs sold in retail stores went to the home, a market which CEO [[John Opel]] described as \"inevitable as the sunrise tomorrow\" for IBM.<ref name=\"burton198303\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7wCiNAUEuAMC&lpg=RA1-PA168&pg=RA1-PA467#v=onepage&f=false | title=Anatomy of a Colossus, Part III | work=PC | date=Mar 1983 | accessdate=March 30, 2014 | author=Burton, Kathleen | pages=467}}</ref> ''[[PC Magazine]]'' reported that observers believed the company did not \"face substantial competition on the home front\" from computers that many considered \"mere gadgets or expensive toys\".{{r|burton198303}} Andrew Pollack of ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated that \"One thing that seems certain is that movement will be away from game playing toward more powerful computers with greater capabilities\".<ref name=\"pollack19830619\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/19/business/the-coming-crisis-in-home-computers.html?pagewanted=all | title=The Coming Crisis in Home Computers | work=The New York Times | date=June 19, 1983 | accessdate=January 19, 2015 | author=Pollack, Andrew}}</ref> The success \"of the Peanut is as good as established\", ''Ahoy!'' predicted.{{r|springer198401}}\n\nBy September 1983, books and magazine articles on Peanut were ready for publishing, with only a few changes needed once the still officially nonexistent computer appeared. Software companies prepared to market products as \"Peanut compatible\" with the computer that, rumors said, IBM would produce 500,000 units of in the first year. ''[[Adweek]]'' estimated that IBM would spend $75 million on marketing, including an alleged license of [[Charles Schulz]]'s [[Peanuts]] characters. ''Smalltalk'' magazine in August published a detailed article on the computer, stating that it would cost $600 plus $400 for a disk drive, use a color TV as a display, and have a standard typewriter keyboard.<ref name=\"esd19830927\">{{Cite news |last=Sandberg-Diment |first=Erik |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/27/science/personal-computers-is-the-ibm-peanut-really-in-the-wings.html |title=Personal Computers; Is the I.B.M. Peanut Really in the Wings? |date=September 27, 1983 |work=The New York Times |access-date=December 14, 2017 |page=C5 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Release===\n[[File:PCjr chiclet.gif|thumb|right|300px|One observer compared using the original chiclet keyboard to \"massaging fruit cake\".{{r|sandler19840221}}]]\n\nOn what ''Time'' called \"[[Normandy landings|D-Day]] for the Home Computer\",<ref name=\"time19831107\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,949869,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122161630/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C949869%2C00.html |archive-date=November 22, 2008 |title=D-Day for the Home Computer |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=Moritz, Michael |author2=John Greenwald |author3=Frederick Ungeheuer |date=November 7, 1983 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and others described as \"the biggest fanfare in the history of computers\",{{r|ap19850321}} IBM announced the PCjr on November 1, 1983, at its [[IBM Building, New York City|New York City headquarters]] with an enormous amount of advance publicity, including live news coverage of the event.<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /> ''[[Compute!]]'' wrote \"Never before in the history of personal computing (admittedly a brief history) has a product been so eagerly awaited by so many\".<ref name=\"halfhill198401\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1984-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_044_1984_Jan#page/n45/mode/2up | title=IBM's New PCjr | work=Compute! | date=January 1984 | accessdate=October 30, 2013 | author=Halfhill, Tom R. | pages=44}}</ref>\n\n''[[Business Week]]''{{'}}s cover said \"AND THE WINNER IS...IBM!\"{{r|levy198501}} Experts predicted, according to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', that the PCjr \"will quickly become the standard by which all other home computers are measured\".{{r|wp19831106}} No longer facing a [[History of IBM#1969: Antitrust, the Unbundling of software and services|long-running antitrust suit by the United States government]], IBM and dealers boasted that \"we are going to sell as many of these things as we can possibly make\".{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|time19840402}} Observers agreed,<ref name=\"sanger19850707\">{{Cite news |last=Sanger |first=David E. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/07/07/magazine/the-changing-image-of-ibm.html |title=The Changing Image of I.B.M. |date=1985-07-07 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-11 |page=Section 6, Page 13 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> predicting sales of one million or more in 1984,<ref name=\"pollack19831102\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/02/business/the-debut-of-ibm-s-junior.html?pagewanted=all | title=The Debut of I.B.M.'S Junior | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Pollack, Andrew | date=November 2, 1983 | work=The New York Times}}</ref> and expected the PCjr to change the home-computer market in a similar way to how the IBM PC had changed the business-microcomputer market.<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /><ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" />{{r|halfhill198401}} They predicted that the PCjr would extend IBM's dominance, with customers able to use the company's computers in the home and in the office.{{r|burton198303}}{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|wp19831106}}\n\n''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' observed that \"The PCjr ... has at least three invaluable assets: the letters I, B, and M\".{{r|marcom19840222}} \"The three initials on its nameplate\", ''[[Popular Science]]'' wrote, were \"letters that, in the minds of many, represent quality, reliability, and an assurance that the company will be around for as long as the computer is\".{{r|ruby198402}} Even rivals like Coleco,<ref name=\"coleco19830928\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gg_I9TGYM-w |title=Coleco Presents The Adam Computer System |date=May 3, 2016 |publisher=YouTube |orig-year=1983-09-28 |time=1:05:15 |quote=We at Coleco think that IBM's possible or probably entry to the home-computer field with 'Peanut', whether it's this year or next year, is extremely encouraging and positive, both for the home-computer industry and in particular for Coleco. Now, I assure you I haven't taken leave of my senses, and obviously it's no lack of respect for the well-earned reputation of IBM that prompts me to say that. But there's at least four considerations that I'd like to throw out to you and help you as far as my thinking.}}</ref><ref name=\"ap19831102\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3360529// | title=Analysts say: IBM's PCjr won't disrupt Christmas for competitors | work=Santa Cruz Sentinel | date=November 2, 1983 | agency=Associated Press | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | pages=B-5}}</ref><ref name=\"rosenberg19831208\">{{Cite news |title=Home Computer? Maybe Next Year |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=December 8, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> Commodore,{{r|cook19840306}} and Tandy<ref name=\"mace19831226\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2i8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA86&pg=PA91#v=onepage&f=false | title=Q&A: Mark Yamagata | work=InfoWorld | date=December 26, 1983 \u2013 January 2, 1984 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | author=Mace, Scott | pages=91}}</ref> hoped that IBM would stabilize and bring credibility to the chaotic $2 billion home-computer market, which had seen \"cutthroat\" [[price war]]s between Commodore, [[Atari Inc.|Atari]], and others for 18 months.{{r|burton198303}}<ref name=\"ap19831101\">{{Cite news |title=IBM's Peanut Begins New Computer Phase |date=November 1, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>{{r|wp19831106}}<ref name=\"cook19840306\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhoP0KRkQe4C&lpg=PA8&pg=PA35#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Jr. Sneaks PC into Home | work=PC Magazine | date=March 6, 1984 | accessdate=October 24, 2013 | author=Cook, Karen | pages=35}}</ref><ref name=\"rosenberg19831106\">{{Cite news |title=Computers; The Abounding Uncertainties; Consumers and Companies Spar in New Arena without Guidelines |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=November 6, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>{{r|infoworld19831121}}{{r|ruby198402}} \"IBM is a company that knows how to make money\", Coleco CEO [[Arnold Greenberg (Coleco)|Arnold Greenberg]] said. \"What IBM can bring to the home-computer field is something that the field collectively needs, particularly now: A respect for profitability. A capability to earn money\".<ref name=\"coleco19830928b\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gg_I9TGYM-w |title=Coleco Presents The Adam Computer System |date=May 3, 2016 |publisher=YouTube |orig-year=1983-09-28 |time=1:06:55 |quote=IBM is just not another strong company making a positive statement about the home-computer field's future. IBM is a company that knows how to make money. IBM is a company that knows how to make money in hardware, and makes more money in software. What IBM can bring to the home-computer field is something that the field collectively needs, particularly now: A respect for profitability. A capability to earn money. That is precisely what the field needs ... I look back a year or two in the videogame field, or the home-computer field, how much better everyone was, when most people were making money, rather than very few were making money.}}</ref> TI left the market four days before IBM's announcement, after losing US$223 million in nine months against Commodore{{r|ap19831102}}{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"maceti19831121\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA19&dq=ibm%20peanut&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q=ibm%20peanut&f=false | title=TI retires from home-computer market | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Mace, Scott | date=November 21, 1983 | work=InfoWorld | pages=22, 27}}</ref> by selling its [[TI 99/4A|99/4A]] for as low as $99; such low prices likely damaged the reputation of the industry by making home computers appear to be inferior game machines.{{r|pollack19830619}}{{r|cook19840306}} (The 99/4A was so unsuccessful that TI stock immediately rose by 25% after the discontinuation.{{r|ap19831101}})\n\nIBM did not plan to sell the PCjr through discount stores,{{r|cook19840306}} and experts expected that the company would likely not compete on price;{{r|nyt19831102}} [[Paine Webber|PaineWebber]] predicted that the PCjr would open a \"price umbrella\" over home-computer companies.<ref name=\"wp19831106\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3360554// | title=IBM PCjr leads the way for industry | work=The Pantagraph | date=November 6, 1983 | agency=The Washington Post | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | pages=E6}}</ref> Observers did not see low-end computers as the PCjr's main competition, however, expecting it to most affect sales of the IIe, another home-business crossover product.{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|ap19831102}} PC expert [[Peter Norton]] wrote that the new computer \"has all, or nearly all, the capacity and flexibility that most of us who are already using PC's need ... All in all, the PCjr looks like a remarkable machine for its capabilities and an astounding one for its price\", and predicted that \"the PCjr will make an even bigger splash\" than the PC.{{r|norton19840124}} Financial writer John Gantz wrote \"Conventional wisdom says that with the PCjr, IBM has the personal-computer market sewed up [and that] IBM will kick hind end in any market remotely related to the PC, maybe in any market whatsoever\".{{r|gantz19831128}}\n\nDevelopers began developing PCjr software in 1982,{{r|maher20130718}} for which a rumor stated that IBM paid US$10 million.{{r|clapp19840109_16}} [[Sierra On-Line]], [[Software Publishing Corporation|SPC]], and [[The Learning Company]] were among those that produced two dozen games, productivity, and educational software as [[Launch game|launch titles]],{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|wiswell19840124}} using detailed IBM production outlines.{{r|rosenberg19840424}} IBM security made unannounced visits to search wastebaskets and verify that computer prototypes remained hidden in locked rooms,<ref name=\"sanger19840422\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/22/business/the-heady-world-of-ibm-suppliers.html |title=The Heady World of I.B.M. Suppliers |last=Sanger |first=David E. |date=April 22, 1984 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 | page=Section 3, Page 1 | |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |author-link=David E. Sanger}}</ref> with everyone entering signing logbooks that IBM could review at any time.<ref name=\"rosenberg19840424\">{{Cite news |title=The Secret World of IBM |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=April 24, 1984 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The PCjr's graphics and sound features were superior to the PC's,{{r|nortonpcjraudio19840124}}{{r|shea19840312}}{{r|pollack19831102}} and ''PC Magazine'' speculated that \"the PCjr might be the best game machine ever designed\".<ref name=\"wiswell19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA142#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Coming Soon: Games For The PCjr | work=PC | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=January 26, 2015 | author=Wiswell, Phil | pages=142\u2013145}}</ref> Prominent among launch titles was Sierra's [[graphical adventure]] ''[[King's Quest I]]''; IBM paid much of the game's $850,000 budget.<ref name=\"maher20130718\">{{cite web | url=http://www.filfre.net/2013/07/the-unmaking-and-remaking-of-sierra-on-line/ | title=The Unmaking and Remaking of Sierra On-Line | publisher=The Digital Antiquarian | date=July 18, 2013 | accessdate=February 5, 2015 | author=Maher, Jimmy}}</ref>\n\nObservers believed that software companies would also publish many non-game applications for the new computer{{r|cook19840306}} without fearing that it would quickly become [[orphaned technology]].{{r|pollack19831102}}<ref name=\"wierzbicki19831219\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5C8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA51&pg=PA51#v=onepage&f=false | title=Developers embrace PCjr despite drawbacks | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Wierzbicki, Barbara | date=December 19, 1983 | work=InfoWorld}}</ref> Major peripheral manufacturer [[Tecmar]] stated in full-page magazine advertisements \"We're glad you're here, PCjr. Tecmar will have a boat-load of products for you\".<ref name=\"ad198403\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/creativecomputing-1984-03/Creative_Computing_v10_n03_1984_Mar#page/n1/mode/2up | title=Welcome A-Board / Tecmar Greets the New PCjr | work=Creative Computing | date=March 1984 | accessdate=February 6, 2015 | pages=Inside front cover | type=advertisement}}</ref> Advanced Input, the small Idaho company IBM chose to manufacture the PCjr keyboard, predicted that it would be the world's largest keyboard manufacturer by 1990.{{r|nyt19831126}}\n\nAlthough IBM missed the [[Economics of Christmas|important Christmas sales season]] because of production delays, by announcing early the company succeeded in its likely goal of hurting competitors with [[fear, uncertainty and doubt]].<ref name=\"nyt19831102\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/02/business/ibm-s-speedy-redirection.html | title=I.B.M.'S Speedy Redirection | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | date=November 2, 1983 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{r|marcom19840222}}{{r|time19840402}}{{r|time19850401}} [[ComputerLand]] sold gift certificates with a large model of the computer \"'beautifully wrapped to go under your Christmas tree'\".<ref name=\"freiberger19840109_16\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ey4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA14&ots=qxysACmBMb&pg=PA20#v=onepage&f=false | title=IBM indicates March as likely PCjr delivery date | work=InfoWorld | date=January 9\u201316, 1984 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Freiberger, Paul | pages=20}}</ref> IBM planned to spend US$40 million on advertising<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,951424,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514070332/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C951424%2C00.html |archive-date=May 14, 2009 |title=A Flop Becomes a Hit |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=McCarroll, Thomas |author2=Philip Elmer-DeWitt |date=December 24, 1984 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> with [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s iconic character \"[[The Little Tramp]]\", already used in a successful campaign for the PC.<ref>{{cite web|title=IBM PCjr Classic Ad|url=http://www.adclassix.com/ads/84ibmpcjr.htm|year=1984}}</ref><ref name=\"papson1990\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC35folder/IBMtramp.html | title=The IBM tramp | author=Papson, Stephen | journal=Jump Cut: A Review of Contemporary Media |date=April 1990  | issue=35 | pages=66\u201372}}</ref> [[Ziff Davis]], publisher of the successful ''PC Magazine'', printed the first issue of ''PCjr Magazine'' before the first units shipped; competing [[computer magazine]]s included ''Peanut'', ''PCjr World'',<ref name=\"nyt19831109\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/09/business/boom-in-computer-magazines.html | title=Boom in Computer Magazines | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | date=November 9, 1983 | work=The New York Times }}</ref> ''jr'', and ''Compute! for the PC and PCjr''.<ref name=\"bartimo19841210\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=si4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA35&pg=PA35#v=onepage&f=false | title=Magazines Woo Users | accessdate=March 14, 2011 | author=Bartimo, Jim | date=December 10, 1984 | pages=35\u201336 | work=InfoWorld}}</ref> The publisher of an [[instant book]] that appeared the month of the computer's introduction said that consumers wanted to learn about it as much as [[Operation Entebbe]] and the [[Jonestown Massacre]].<ref name=\"rosenberg19831125\">{{Cite news |title=160-page 'Instant Book' on IBM's PCjr Home Computer Due Out Today |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=November 25, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe }}</ref>\n\n===Commercial failure===\n{{rquote|right|The machine has the smell of death about it.|[[Steven Levy]], 1984{{r|mccarroll19841224}}}}\n\nErik Sandberg-Diment of the ''Times'' wondered when discussing Peanut rumors in September 1983 why IBM would release a lower-cost, mass-market product compatible with PC software when demand for the PC exceeded supply: \"Why should I.B.M. undercut its own, already practically guaranteed sales, just to engage in a very messy fight in the notoriously fickle and often profitless consumer market? That just doesn't make sense\".{{r|esd19830927}}\n\n[[George Morrow (computers)|George Morrow]] was one of the few to be pessimistic about the PCjr after the November announcement, predicting that Commodore's [[Jack Tramiel]] would \"make mincemeat\" of the \"toylike\" computer.{{r|infoworld19831121}} \"Somehow the mighty colossus looked a lot smaller that day\", ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' wrote, calling PCjr \"a terrible disappointment\".<ref name=\"shapiro198402\">{{Cite magazine |last=Shapiro |first=Neil |date=February 1984 |title=Big Bytes for Little Bucks |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GuMDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA99&ots=046J8EGyex&pg=PA98#v=onepage&f=true |magazine=Popular Mechanics |pages=98\u201399,139\u2013142}}</ref> ''InCider'' agreed that the computer was disappointing, but observed that \"no product could have lived up to the jr's pre-release publicity\".<ref name=\"ryan198407\">{{Cite magazine |last=Ryan |first=Bob |date=July 1984 |title=The newest member of the family goes head to head with the PCjr. |url=https://archive.org/stream/inCider_84-07#page/n59/mode/2up |magazine=InCider |pages=60\u201363}}</ref> The ''Times'' noted that \"After all that waiting, it seems odd that no one appears particularly enthusiastic about the machine\".<ref name=\"esd19831227\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/27/science/personal-computers-the-little-ibm-finally-arrives-for-a-test.html |title=Personal Computers: The Little I.B.M. Finally Arrives for a Test |last=Sandberg-Diment |first=Erik |date=December 27, 1983 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Steven Levy]] recalled that at the press conference \"I felt like I was at the eighties version of [[Woodstock Festival|Woodstock]]. But what awaited us was, to my eyes, more like [[Altamont Free Concert|Altamont]]\". Despite his disappointment, Levy said that so many others were positive about the computer that he doubted his own judgment until receiving a review unit.{{r|levy198501}}\n\nSeveral ''[[InfoWorld]]'' writers criticized the computer. Offering a \"contrarian view: the PCjr could actually turn out to be a dog\", Gantz wrote that \"it's consumer and buyer demand that will spell success, not how awesome IBM is. It's still a free country, we don't ''have'' to buy the PCjr\".{{r|gantz19831128}} [[John Dvorak]] joked that \"champagne corks were popping all over the place. The bottles were being opened by Apple shareholders\".<ref name=\"dvorak19831128\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA188&ots=R2H3IQegBq&pg=PA188#v=onepage&f=false | title=Inside Track | work=InfoWorld | date=November 28, 1983 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | author=Dvorak, John C. | pages=188}}</ref> Doug Clapp called PCjr \"a pathetic, crippled computer\", but glumly expected that \"the magic letters IBM\" and the company's enormous financial and marketing resources would let it \"get away with this stuff\".<ref name=\"clapp19840109_16\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ey4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA14&ots=qxysACmBMb&pg=PA14#v=onepage&f=false | title=Clapp-Trapp | work=InfoWorld | date=January 9\u201316, 1984 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Clapp, Doug | pages=14}}</ref>\n\nDvorak added that after the PCjr announcement \"I go to my local ComputerLand dealer and everyone there is depressed. 'I'm not sure I even want to carry it,' said the manager\", in contrast to the reaction to the PC.{{r|dvorak19831128}} When the PCjr became widely available in early 1984{{r|freiberger19840109_16}} sales were below expectations. One store owner reported that \"Interest was at a fever pitch\" after the announcement, but \"Once we had a demonstration model (in January), the only thing I can say is that the response was underwhelming\".{{r|marcom19840222}} Dealers reported that consumers disliked the price, keyboard, and lack of memory;{{r|nyt19840420}}  those that sold to business customers did not know how to market it.<ref name=\"mcmullen19840221\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UCIvSU6Y2GAC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA120#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Apple Charts The Course For IBM | work=PC Magazine | date=1984-02-21 | accessdate=24 October 2013 | author=McMullen, Barbara E. and John F. | page=122}}</ref>\n\nBy March the press reported that PCjr could be an embarrassment for IBM, with executives reportedly worrying about demand. Stores began discounts while vendors slowed plans to release products.{{r|richter19840328}}<ref name=\"zientara19840409\"/>{{r|sanger19840517}} The company admitted that \"In April, demand for the PCjr has been variable, and is not growing quite as rapidly as we expected\". It said that demand in the first quarter of 1984 \"met our expectations\", but each dealer was required to purchase a certain quantity at the computer's introduction.<ref name=\"nyt19840420\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/20/business/pcjr-sales-less-than-expected.html |title=PCjr Sales Less Than Expected |date=1984-04-20 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-03-11 |page=D3 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> IBM began unusually early discounts of up to US$370<ref name=\"winter19850324\">{{cite news | url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1985/03/24/page/79/article/behind-the-short-unhappy-life-of-ibms-junior | title=Behind the short, unhappy life of IBM's Junior | work=Chicago Tribune | date=March 24, 1985 | accessdate=April 29, 2015 | author=Winter, Christine | pages=Section 7, Page 3}}</ref> on 7 June, lowering the two models' prices to $599 and $999,{{r|bulman19841105}} but many of its 1,400 dealers could not sell initial allotments of 25 computers.{{r|marcom19840222}}{{r|bulman19841105}} IBM allowed dealers to postpone paying for inventory for 180 days.<ref name=\"pollack19850120\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/01/20/business/the-daunting-power-of-ibm.html |title=The Daunting Power of I.B.M. |last=Pollack |first=Andrew |date=January 20, 1985 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 3, 2017 |page=A1 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \"Inventory is beginning to pile up\", ''Time'' wrote in April;<ref name=\"time19840402\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,954205-2,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609012541/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C954205%2C00.html |archive-date=June 9, 2008 |title=The Peanut Meets the Mac |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=McCarroll, Thomas |author2=Michael Moritz |author3=Philip Elmer-DeWitt |date=April 2, 1984 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> by August ''InfoWorld'' described it as \"the colossal flop that the experts said couldn't happen\";<ref name=\"mace19840813\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA38pg=PA38#v=onepage&f=true | title=PCjr: Back to Basics | work=InfoWorld | date=August 13, 1984 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Mace, Scott | pages=38}}</ref> and in December ''Time'' stated that the PCjr \"looked like one of the biggest flops in the history of computing...[it] sold as sluggishly as [[Edsel]]s in the late 1950s\".<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" />\n\n====Keyboard====\n{{rquote|right|How could IBM have made that mistake with the PCjr?|Tandy executive, 1984{{r|iw19840820}}}}\n\nJournalists at the PCjr announcement who hoped for, ''Compute!'' reported, \"a revolutionary machine that would reinvent the home computer\"{{r|halfhill198401}} \"gasp[ed in] dismay\"{{r|pollack19831102}} when they saw its chiclet keyboard. \"No single component in an IBM computer has ever attracted such controversy\", the ''Times'' said,{{r|sanger19840422}} describing it as \"not suitable for serious long-term typing\"{{r|pollack19831102}} and \"nearly useless\",<ref name=\"nyt19840821\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/21/science/personal-computer-keyboard-is-a-stroke-of-genius.html | title=Keyboard is a Stroke of Genius | work=The New York Times | date=August 21, 1984 | accessdate=July 31, 2014 | author=Sandberg-Diment, Erik}}</ref> with fingers having \"all the grace of a rubber-kneed centipede\" on it.{{r|esd19831227}} ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' described the \"noticeably different\" PCjr keyboard as \"weak for word processing\",<ref name=\"rosenberg19831102\">{{Cite news |title=Enter IBM with PCjr |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=November 2, 1983 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> and ''Popular Mechanics'' warned that no \"businessman or professional would feel comfortable with\" the \"distinctly toylike\" keyboard.{{r|shapiro198402}} ''PC Magazine'' quoted someone comparing the keyboard's touch to \"massaging fruit cake\",<ref name=\"sandler19840221\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UCIvSU6Y2GAC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA323#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=A Secret Inside The ROM | work=PC Magazine | date=February 21, 1984 | accessdate=October 24, 2013 | author=Sandler, Corey | pages=323}}</ref> and stated that using IBM's function keys-dependent [[IBM DisplayWrite|DisplayWrite]] word processor on the PCjr \"requires a level of digital dexterity more normally associated with concert piano playing\".{{r|dickinsondw19840918}}\n\nA [[Yankee Group]] analyst said that the keyboard\u2014which IBM reportedly sought to manufacture for the unusually low $15\u201320\u2014needed \"orangutan fingers to type on\",<ref name=\"nyt19831126\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/26/business/advanced-input-s-ibm-coup.html |title=Advanced Input's I.B.M. Coup |date=November 26, 1983 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Clapp wrote that \"to say that jr even ''has'' a keyboard is far too charitable\".{{r|clapp19840109_16}} ''Compute!'' agreed, stating that the computer \"leaves something to be desired. A keyboard for one\". The magazine observed that \"Atari and Coleco must have breathed collective sighs of relief, because both promptly raised January 1 pricing of their personal computer systems\".<ref name=\"lock198401\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1984-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_044_1984_Jan#page/n7/mode/2up | title=Editor's Notes | work=Compute! | date=January 1984 | accessdate=October 30, 2013 | author=Lock, Robert | pages=6}}</ref> ''[[BYTE]]'' called the keyboard \"a new standard for intentional product handicapping\",<ref name=\"malloy198406\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1984-06/1984_06_BYTE_09-06_Computers_and_Education#page/n297/mode/2up | title=Reviewer's Notebook | work=BYTE | date=June 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Malloy, Rich | pages=297}}</ref> and despite IBM denials{{r|levy198501}} other publications and experts agreed that the keyboard was evidence of [[product differentiation]] by the company, giving the PCjr less capability to avoid [[cannibalization (marketing)|cannibalizing]] IBM PC sales.{{r|nyt19831126}}<ref name=\"ruby198402\" />{{r|time19831107}}<ref name=\"ahoy198402\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/ahoy-magazine-02/Ahoy_02_February_1984#page/n13/mode/2up | title=Rumor, Innuendo & \"Ted\" | work=Ahoy! | date=February 1984 | accessdate=October 16, 2013 | pages=14}}</ref>{{r|mccarroll19841224}}\n\nThe keyboard design stunned many in the industry, including [[Ken Williams (game developer)|Ken Williams]] and others at Sierra\u2014whose prototypes did not have the chiclet keyboard\u2014and [[Doug Carlston]] of [[Br\u00f8derbund|Br\u00f8derbund Software]].{{r|infoworld19831121}}{{r|sanger19840422}}{{r|maher20130718}} \"How could IBM have made that mistake with the PCjr?\", an astounded Tandy executive asked.<ref name=\"iw19840820\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA50&pg=PA50#v=onepage&f=false | title=From Home to Business: The Eclectic Radio Shack Computer Line | accessdate=May 26, 2011 | date=August 20, 1984 | work=InfoWorld | pages=47\u201352}}</ref> Dvorak stated that \"the week before the announcement, [another journalist] told me it had a 'chiclet' keyboard. 'No way \u2014 that's the dumbest thing IBM could do,' I replied ... [it's] associated with $99 el cheapo computers\".{{r|dvorak19831128}} Factory workers manufacturing the keyboard mocked its poor quality,<ref name=\"digibarn\">{{cite web | url=http://www.digibarn.com/collections/devices/pcjr-chicklet-keyboard/index.html | title=Chicklet Keyboard frm IBM PC Jr | publisher=DigiBarn Computer Museum | accessdate=January 26, 2015 | author=Damer, Bruce}}</ref> even IBM salesmen advised customers to buy a replacement,{{r|sanger19840517}} and Dvorak predicted that other companies would \"make a fortune selling real keyboards for the thing\".{{r|dvorak19831128}}\n\n====Cost====\n{{rquote|right|Junior is probably the most expensive product sold with the famous legend, \"Batteries not included.\"|''PC Magazine'' on the PCjr's wireless keyboard, 1985<ref name=\"manes19850528\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DDlmJxSURq8C&lpg=PP1&pg=RA1-PA67#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Junior and Edsel: Two of A Kind Together At Last! | work=PC Magazine | date=1985-05-28 | accessdate=28 October 2013 | author=Manes, Stephen | pages=67}}</ref>}}\n\nThe PCjr's cost was its biggest disadvantage, even more so than the keyboard.<ref name=\"time19840402\" /> ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that customers \"find that the PCjr is expensive for a home computer but isn't very powerful for an expensive computer\".{{r|marcom19840222}} ''Ahoy!'' wrote that \"a machine with relatively limited technology at a relatively high price, not only presented much less of a threat than the industry had feared\", but benefited the C64 by encouraging Atari and Coleco to raise prices.<ref name=\"leemon198405\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/Ahoy_Issue_05_1984-05_Ion_International_US#page/n43/mode/2up | title=The Future of Commodore? | work=Ahoy! | date=May 1984 | accessdate=June 27, 2014 | author=Leemon, Sheldon | pages=44}}</ref> IBM did not say whether the target market was the home, schools, or executives working at home, confusing software developers, consumers,{{r|wierzbicki19831219}}{{r|ap19850321}} and dealers,{{r|mcmullen19840221}} but likely erred by setting the PCjr's price in the US$800\u2013$1,600 range, where demand was weaker than for computers that cost less\u2014especially the C64\u2014or more. Norton warned that the PCjr \"may well be targeted at a gray area in the market that just does not exist\",{{r|sanger19840517}} and an observer estimated that \"perhaps only 10 to 15% of the home market will be interested\".{{r|uston198403}} IBM were surprised to learn that many of the initial customers for the PCjr were not home users as they assumed, but instead businesses who wanted a cheaper PC that took less space on a desk.\n\nIBM was unfamiliar with the consumer market but hoped that customers would be willing to pay more for a product with, as an industry expert said, \"those three letters\".{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|wp19831106}} Many consumers wanted a computer more sophisticated than those costing less than $500, but did not want to spend more than $1,000.{{r|ap19850321}} Without a [[VisiCalc]]-like [[killer app]] for the home \"There is no compelling reason, based on what's available in software, to convince families to\" spend $2,000 on a computer, one computer-store chain manager said.<ref name=\"rosenberg19840228\">{{Cite news |title=Doubts Raised About PCjr |last=Rosenberg |first=Ronald |date=February 28, 1984 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> ''Popular Mechanics'' warned that at $669 and $1,269, PCjr \"has been priced out of those markets\" and [[Coleco Adam]] or \"almost any other computer in those price ranges is a better buy\".{{r|shapiro198402}} Gantz agreed, stating that \"inasmuch as it goes after the home market, [the PCjr] goes to a very price-sensitive crowd\". Unlike IBM's traditional corporate customers \"the home computer crowd has no notion of concepts like upward compatibility, software availability, or the importance of vendor stability\", he wrote;<ref name=\"gantz19831128\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sy8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA186&pg=PA186#v=onepage&f=false | title=Heard on Tech Street | work=InfoWorld | date=November 28, 1983 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Gantz, John | pages=186}}</ref> such customers usually bought the C64, which became more popular.{{r|sanger19840517}}\n\nThe PCjr cost more than twice as much as the C64 and the [[Atari 8-bit family]], while inferior to both and the IIe for games.{{r|pollack19831102}}{{r|lima19841203}} [[Imagic]] stated that the C64 was \"a lot faster and it sells for one third the price\",{{r|cook19840306}} Sierra's Williams predicted that \"There's no way our game [[Frogger]] will ever look as good on the PCjr as it does on the Commodore 64 or the Atari\",{{r|pollack19831102}} and Spinnaker said that \"for its level of performance it is simply the most expensive machine on the market\".{{r|time19840402}} After the PCjr's discontinuation, Spinnaker chairman William Bowman said that it developed software assuming that the more expensive model would cost $800 to $900, and \"we dropped production immediately\" when the company learned that it would cost $1,269.<ref name=\"ap19850321\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31243737/poughkeepsie_journal/ |title=The runner stumbles: IBM pulls back from troubled PCjr |date=1985-03-21 |work=Poughkeepsie Journal |access-date=2019-05-05 |agency=Associated Press |page=7 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThose willing to pay more than $1,000 could buy better computers than the PCjr for the same price.{{r|ap19850321}} Consumers were reportedly much more excited about the also-new [[Macintosh 128K]], more sophisticated but only US$300 more expensive with accessories and software.{{r|time19840402}}<ref name=\"marcom19840222\">{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3360489// | title=IBM's PCjr receives a cool reception | work=Santa Cruz Sentinel | date=February 22, 1984 | agency=Wall Street Journal | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | author=Marcom, John Jr. | pages=B-5}}</ref> So compelling that one dealer called it \"the first $2,500 [[impulse item]] I've ever seen\", Macintosh reportedly outsold the IBM product during their first two months on the market.<ref name=richter19840328>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31276226/the_cincinnati_enquirer/ |title=Macintosh Takes Lead In Sales Race |last=Richter |first=Paul |date=1984-03-28 |work=The Cincinnati Enquirer |access-date=2019-05-05 |agency=Los Angeles Times |pages=B-1, B-2 |language=en}}</ref> PCjr's price was close to that of the Coleco Adam, but the Adam also included a [[tape drive]], a printer, and software.{{r|time19831107}} A realistic cost including peripherals was $2,000{{r|esd19831227}}{{r|levy198501}} and other packages cost $3,000 or more,<ref name=\"ruby198402\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQAAAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA68&dq=peanut%20ibm%20pcjr&pg=PA68#v=onepage&q=peanut%20ibm%20pcjr&f=false | title=IBM's PCjr&mdash;was it worth the wait? | accessdate=February 24, 2011 | author=Ruby, Daniel | date=February 1984 | work=Popular Science | pages=68\u201371}}</ref> even while IBM did not include batteries for the wireless keyboard.{{r|manes19850528}}{{r|levy198501}}\n\nThe IIe was the PCjr's most direct competition.{{r|richter19840328}}{{r|zientara19840409}}{{r|ryan198407}} Although the PC outsold it{{r|maceiie19840409}} Apple sold almost 110,000 units in December 1983, in part to customers who had waited until details of the PCjr became available.<ref name=\"pollack19840116\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/01/16/business/apple-expands-product-line.html |title=Apple Expands Product Line |last=Pollack |first=Andrew |date=January 16, 1984 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 2, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Apple estimated that 80% of its dealers sold IBM and Apple computers, and many visitors disappointed by the PCjr, or curious about the Macintosh, reportedly left with a IIe instead; the latter was so popular that a shortage occurred in early 1984.<ref name=\"maceiie19840409\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jC4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA15&pg=PA54#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Apple IIe Sales Surge as IIc is Readied | work=InfoWorld | date=April 9, 1984 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Mace, Scott | pages=54\u201355}}</ref> The US$669 PCjr model compared favorably to a $1,400 IIe also with 64&nbsp;KB and no floppy drive,<ref name=\"pollack19831102\" />{{r|wierzbicki19831219}} but Apple lowered the computer's price<ref name=\"time19840402\" /> as part of a \"Starter System\" with monitor and floppy drive with a price as low as $1,300,{{r|maceiie19840409}} offered a 30% discount to the important education market,{{r|infoworld19831121}} and in April 1984 introduced the [[Apple IIc]], a portable version with a more compact form factor, 128&nbsp;KB of RAM, and a floppy drive. Although the PCjr's CPU is superior, the IIc\u2014which Apple did not describe as a home computer, to avoid the \"game machine\" connotation\u2014has an excellent keyboard and is compatible with the Apple II's thousands of programs.<ref name=\"winter19840424\">{{cite news | url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1984/04/24/page/37/article/apple-aiming-to-take-bite-out-of-ibm | title=Apple aiming to take bite out of IBM | work=Chicago Tribune | date=April 24, 1984 | accessdate=April 29, 2015 | author=Winter, Christine | pages=Section 3, Page 1}}</ref>{{r|sanger19840517}}<ref name=\"miller198407\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n7/116_Apple_announces_the_IIc.php | title=Apple announces the IIc | accessdate=March 17, 2011 | author=Miller, George A. | date=July 1984 | work=Creative Computing | pages=116}}</ref><ref name=\"ah08\">{{cite web | url=http://apple2history.org/history/ah08/ | title=The Apple IIc | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | work=Apple II History| date=June 23, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"hayes19840424\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/24/business/apple-is-banking-on-new-portable-the-iic-computer.html | title=Apple is Banking on New Portable: The IIc Computer | work=The New York Times | date=April 24, 1984 | accessdate=January 5, 2015 | author=Hayes, Thomas C.}}</ref> A dealer stated that Apple \"very neatly bracketed the PCjr\", and the IIc and IIe's good sales compared to the PCjr implied that cost was not the latter's only problem.{{r|sanger19840517}}\n\n====Not fully PC compatible====\n{{rquote|right|The PCjr cannot be used for serious business computing.|''The New York Times'', 1983{{r|pollack19831102}}}}\n\n{{rquote|right|The PCjr is a failure as a game machine.|''InfoWorld'', 1984{{r|lima19841203}}}}\n\nBy early 1984, PC compatibility was vital for any new non-Apple computer's success. ''InfoWorld''{{'}}s Clapp suggested that were [[Cray]] to introduce an incredibly sophisticated, shirt pocket-sized computer, \"what's the first question that the computer community asks? [[Influence of the IBM PC on the personal computer market#\"Is it PC compatible?\"|'Is it PC compatible?']]\"<ref name=\"clapp19840227\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gy4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA15&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=PC compatibility | work=InfoWorld | date=February 27, 1984 | accessdate=January 18, 2015 | author=Clapp, Doug | pages=22}}</ref>\n\n\"IBM had given us a machine for little kids that also runs some grown-up programs\", Levy wrote.{{r|levy198501}} Unfamiliar with the  consumer market IBM expected that most customers would be new to computers, but 75% were familiar with computers and wanted to run business software on the PCjr.{{r|sanger19850707}} An important market was executives who took data home to work on applications such as the spreadsheet [[Lotus 1-2-3]], and many customers visited stores believing that the PCjr could run most PC software;{{r|marcom19840222}}{{r|time19840402}}{{r|sanger19840517}}{{r|nyt19831102}}{{r|gantz19831128}} they compared it\u2014which the ''Times'' warned \"cannot be used for serious business computing\"{{r|pollack19831102}}\u2014unfavorably to the PC instead of other home computers.<ref name=\"sanger19850118\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/01/18/business/computer-giant-finds-problems-in-success.html?pagewanted=all | title=Computer Giant Finds Problems in Success | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Sanger, David E. | date=January 18, 1985 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nPeanut had been rumored to be fully PC compatible.{{r|greenwald19830711}} Norton estimated that the PCjr had about 85% of the PC's capability for a smaller fraction of its price.<ref name=\"norton19840124\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA109#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=The Two Faces of PCjr | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=109}}</ref> IBM technical documentation stated that the \"PCjr is a different computer than the PC\", but \"has a high level of programming compatibility\". The documentation also promised software developers that \"if your application maintains an interface ... at the BIOS and DOS interrupt interfaces, then all hardware differences are handled transparently to your application\".<ref name=\"ibm198311\">{{cite book | title=IBM Personal Computer PCjr Hardware Reference Library / Technical Reference | publisher=IBM | url=https://archive.org/stream/IbmPcjrTechnicalReference#page/n317/mode/2up | year=1983 | pages=4\u20131 to 4\u201311}}</ref> Norton expected that \"any program that followed a design guideline of 64&nbsp;KB and one disk drive is likely to run beautifully on the PCjr. That means that the PCjr will run most of the PC's programs nicely\".{{r|norton19840124}} He warned that developers \"must understand the PCjr's basic limitations and promise not to cheat\", however, and predicted that applications that required more than 128&nbsp;KB of memory, did not support using only one disk drive, or used IBM PC-specific [[copy protection]], would have problems.<ref name=\"pcnortonpcjrport\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSzKzjWHeVEC&lpg=PA61&pg=PA144#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Developing PCjr Software | work=PC Magazine | date=January 24, 1984 | accessdate=October 23, 2013 | author=Norton, Peter | pages=144}}</ref>\n\nThousands of PC applications did require more than 128K of memory{{r|diamond19840801}} and one disk drive.{{r|esd19831227}}{{r|levy198501}} The PCjr was incompatible with about 60% of software, including the popular word-processing program [[WordStar]] and Lotus 1-2-3,<ref name=\"time19840402\" /><ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" /> often used to test PC compatibility;<ref name=\"alsop19940131\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AzsEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PT1&dq=%22flight%20simulator%22&pg=PT1#v=onepage&q=%22flight%20simulator%22&f=false | title=A public Windows pane to make compatibility clearer | accessdate=February 28, 2011 | author=Alsop, Stewart | date=January 31, 1994 | work=InfoWorld | pages=102}}</ref><ref name=shea19840312>{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=li4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA38&pg=PA37#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=PCjr users wait for packages | accessdate=February 24, 2011 | author=Shea, Tom | date=March 12, 1984 | work=InfoWorld | pages=37\u201339}}</ref><ref name=\"trivette198504\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue59/review_lotus_123.php | title=Lotus 1-2-3 For IBM PCjr | work=Compute! | date=April 1985 | accessdate=October 6, 2013 | author=Trivette, Donald B. | pages=63}}</ref> even IBM DisplayWrite requires a separate PCjr version.<ref name=\"dickinsondw19840918\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pq3POofPsBEC&lpg=PA62&pg=PA248#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=IBM's Displaywriter Begets a Family of PC Software | work=PC | date=September 18, 1984 | accessdate=January 29, 2015 | author=Dickinson, John | pages=238}}</ref> The limitations made the computer unsuitable for taking work home;{{r|levy198501}} although 1-2-3 was so important that ''InfoWorld'' joked that \"PC compatible\" really meant \"1-2-3 compatible\",{{r|clapp19840227}} a PCjr version did not become available until a year after the computer's announcement.{{r|trivette198504}} IBM's own stores had a list of software they distributed that was compatible with the PCjr, but customers had to, the ''Chicago Tribune'' reported, learn from \"trial and error\".{{r|winter19840424}}\n\nLevy observed that unlike most good computers, PCjr did not have a killer app.{{r|levy198501}} An analyst stated that its incompatibility with PC software made the PCjr akin to a game machine, benefiting Apple,{{r|hayes19840424}} but ''InfoWorld'' stated that compared to Apples it \"is a failure as a game machine\" because of poor performance with arcade games.{{r|lima19841203}} Apple satirized IBM's Tramp mascot in a commercial that emphasized the IIc's larger software library.{{r|papson1990}}<ref name=\"IIcAd\">{{cite AV media | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DywV6FogNsA | title=Apple IIc versus IBM PCjr commercial | publisher=YouTube | date=June 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====Limited hardware expansion====\nComputer dealers quickly identified the PCjr's limited hardware expansion capability as another major disadvantage.<ref name=\"zientara19840409\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jC4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA15&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=PCjr sales below expectations, dealers say | accessdate=April 3, 2011 | work=InfoWorld | author=Zientara, Marguerite | date=April 9, 1984 | publisher=IDG}}</ref>{{r|time19840402}} Spinnaker expected to sell most PCjr programs on disk because of cartridges' small storage capacity;{{r|cook19840306}} the PCjr version of Lotus 1-2-3 requires two cartridges and a floppy disk, and a 128&nbsp;KB model running it does not have enough memory for many business spreadsheets.{{r|trivette198504}} The computer only has an internal slot for a modem and an external slot on the right side for \"sidecar\" peripherals. IBM published technical details for the PCjr as it had done for the IBM PC to encourage third parties to develop accessories, but did not offer a second floppy drive, hard drive,{{r|wp19831106}}<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /> or memory beyond 128&nbsp;KB{{r|hoffmann198403}} although many customers preferred to use IBM peripherals.{{r|halfhill198410}} Multiple sidecars are very clumsy, and the computer requires additional power supplies with a second floppy drive or more than one sidecar. IBM advised against adding more than four sidecars.<ref name=\"ruby198402\" /><ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" />{{r|levy198501}} The PCjr also lacks a DMA controller, so the 8088 CPU has to service standard system interrupts such as the serial port or the keyboard directly. The PCjr thus cannot use modems faster than 2400 baud, and it refuses to process keyboard input if its buffer is full or while the disk drive is in use.<ref name=\"hoffmann198403\">{{cite web | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n3/74_IBM_PCjr.php | title=IBM PCjr | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Hoffmann, Thomas V. | date=March 1984 | work=Creative Computing | pages=74}}</ref>{{r|levy198501}}{{r|manes19850528}}\n\n===The \"Save-the-Junior campaign\"===\n{{rquote|right|I want an Apple.|Child demonstrating PCjr at IBM event, when asked what computer she wanted for Christmas.<ref name=\"diamond19840801\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/01/business/ibm-raises-dividend-offers-a-free-keyboard.html | title=I.B.M. Raises Dividend, Offers a Free Keyboard | work=The New York Times | date=1984-08-01 | accessdate=4 February 2015 | author=Diamond, Stuart}}</ref>}}\n\nBy mid-1984, the PCjr had experienced months of bad publicity, and dealers were panicking.{{r|mccarroll19841224}} Sales were poor and falling each month before rising slightly with the June discounts; each dealer sold an average of 15 units total in the first half of the year.{{r|bulman19841105}} Levy described it as \"the biggest flop in the history of computing\". Sierra's Williams told him that his company \"was taking a bath on\" PCjr software; \"'The machine is a turkey', he said\".<ref name=levy198501>{{Cite magazine |last=Levy |first=Steven |date=January 1985 |title=The Life and Times of PC junior |url=https://archive.org/details/popular-computing-1985-01/page/n94/mode/2up/search/smell |magazine=Popular Computing |page=92 |access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Apple sold almost as many IIc computers on its first day as PCjr since introduction.{{r|levy198501}} Observers believed that it was doomed; no company had ever succeeded in improving early poor sales of a personal computer.<ref name=\"bulman19841105\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31277231/fort_lauderdale_news/ |title=Big time: IBM skillfully revives lackluster sales of PCjr |last=Bulman |first=Philip |date=1984-11-05 |work=Fort Lauderdale News |access-date=2019-05-05 |page=47 |language=en}}</ref> \"The machine has the smell of death about it\", Levy said.{{r|levy198501}}\n\n[[Don Estridge]] in April said \"The only people who don't like [the keyboard] are writers, and they are the only ones who write about it\",{{r|sanger19840422}}{{r|levy198501}} but on 31 July his company announced that it would replace customers' chiclet keyboards for free with a new model with conventional typewriter keys. Although IBM attempted to hide the decision at the end of a press conference about an educational program for schools,{{r|levy198501}} the press focused on the new keyboard. The act surprised observers by being unusually generous even for IBM\u2014with a reputation for excellent customer service\u2014and the industry;{{r|halfhill198410}}<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" /><ref name=\"lima19841203\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qS4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA60&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=New PC Jr | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Lima, Tony | date=December 3, 1984 | work=InfoWorld | pages=60\u201361}}</ref> ''[[Creative Computing]]'' compared it to an auto maker sending four new free tires to customers,{{r|sandler198411}} and the ''Times'' favorably compared the free keyboard to Apple charging $995 for upgrading the Macintosh to [[Macintosh 512K|512K]].<ref name=\"esd19850319\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/19/science/personal-computers-apple-might-learn-a-thing-or-two-from-ibm.html |title=Apple Might Learn a Thing or Two from I.B.M. |last=Sandberg-Diment |first=Erik |date=1985-03-19 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-07-03 |page=C4 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By replacing the keyboards IBM also acknowledged its initial mistake;{{r|halfhill198410}} other than the keycaps the two designs are identical, so the company could have released the conventional one with the PCjr.{{r|nichols20140322}} The new keyboards cost US$50 each but IBM had to replace only about 60,000 to 75,000, compared to the 250,000 to 480,000 computers that experts had estimated the company would sell during the first six months.{{r|diamond19840801}}{{r|halfhill198410}}<ref name=\"fastie198502\">{{Cite magazine |last=Fastie |first=Will |date=February 1985 |title=An old friend takes a hard look at the IBM product line. |url=https://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v11n2/150_IBM_images_an_old_friend.php |department=IBM Images |magazine=Creative Computing |page=150 |access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 1984 IBM began a massive advertising campaign through the end of the year.{{r|bulman19841105}} It reduced the PCjr's list price, offering a US$999 package that was arguably superior to the comparably priced IIe and IIc, and introduced new IBM-made memory expansion options to 512&nbsp;KB.<ref name=\"halfhill198410\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue53/020_1_IBMs_New_Improved_PCjr.php | title=IBM's New & Improved PCjr | accessdate=February 24, 2011 | author=Halfhill, Tom R. | date=October 1984 | work=Compute! | pages=50}}</ref> As part of $32.5 million in advertising for the computer during 1984,<ref name=\"shiver19850926\">{{Cite news |title=Advertising Age Report Spending by Top 100 U.S. Advertisers Up 16% in '84 |last=Shiver |first=Jube Jr. |date=September 26, 1985 |work=Los Angeles Times |page=2}}</ref> it began what the company described as the most extensive marketing campaign in IBM history, in which 98% of Americans would see at least 30 PCjr advertisements in the last four months of the year. Three simultaneous [[bundled software]] promotions, a sweepstakes with [[Procter & Gamble]], and direct mail to more than 10 million people marketed the redesigned computer,<ref name=\"sandler198411\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n11/298_IBM_colossus_of_Armonk.php | title=IBM: Colossus of Armonk | work=Creative Computing | date=November 1984 | accessdate=February 26, 2013 | author=Sandler, Corey | pages=298}}</ref>{{r|rosch19841113}} while deemphasizing the PCjr's role as a home computer and emphasizing PC compatibility.{{r|halfhill198410}}{{r|levy198501}} Advertisements listed the new price, \"new typewriter-style keyboard\", standard 128&nbsp;KB of memory and expansion options, the PCjr version of 1-2-3, and the ability to \"run over a thousand of the most popular programs written for the IBM PC\".<ref name=\"ibm198412\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mF8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA47&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Now picture this. | work=Black Enterprise | date=December 1984 | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | pages=47 | type=advertisement}}</ref> A $500 rebate to dealers let them include a free color monitor with the discounted PCjr.{{r|fastie198502}}{{r|winter19850324}}\n\nDespite widespread skepticism,<ref name=\"dudek19841002\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d-tPdHcBE9wC&lpg=PA346&pg=PA35#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Is jr 'Likely to Succeed'? Friends Gloat, Foes Groan | work=PC Magazine | author=Dudek, Virginia | date=October 2, 1984 | accessdate=October 25, 2013 | pages=35}}</ref> what observers called the \"Save-the-Junior campaign\"{{r|rosch19841113}} succeeded, amazing the industry. Sales rose every month from June (1.9 units sold per store) to September (4.2);{{r|bulman19841105}} many dealers reported selling more in the weeks following the changes than in the previous seven months.<ref name=\"mccarroll19841224\" /><ref name=\"sanger19841115\">{{cite news\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/11/15/business/at-computer-show-many-retrenching.html\n | title=At Computer Show, Many Retrenching\n | work=The New York Times\n | date=November 15, 1984\n | accessdate=October 24, 2013\n | author=Sanger, David E.\n}}</ref>{{r|rosch19841113}} One large dealer stated in November 1984 that \"it could be a PCjr Christmas\".{{r|mccarroll19841224}} The more expensive model now cost the $800 to $900 that Spinnaker had expected.{{r|ap19850321}} With the new hardware options and lower prices consumers could buy a PCjr for $1,000 less than a comparable PC.{{r|diamond19840801}}{{r|halfhill198410}} The PCjr reportedly became the best-selling computer,<ref name=\"kennedy19850514\">{{Cite news |last=Kennedy, Don |title=Junior Axed By IBM |date=May 14, 1985 |work=PC |pages=33}}</ref> outselling the IIe and IIc by four to one in some stores{{r|fastie198502}}<ref name=\"machrone19850402\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w1aA2lOwdNIC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=PCjr Renaissance | work=PC Magazine | date=April 2, 1985 | accessdate=October 28, 2013 | author=Machrone, Bill | pages=81}}</ref> and even the C64.{{r|mccarroll19841224}} As sales reached an estimated 50 per store in December{{r|pollack19850320}} dealers increased inventories,{{r|ap19850321}} and Tecmar resumed production of PCjr peripherals after retailers suddenly ordered its millions of dollars of unwanted products.<ref name=\"rosch19841113\">{{Cite news |last=Rosch, Winn L. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ukz6hjZEA4C&lpg=PA33&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=true |title=Jr's Growth Spurts Sales |date=November 13, 1984 |work=PC |access-date=2020-03-15 |pages=33, 35}}</ref>\n\n===Discontinuation===\n{{rquote|right|We're just sitting here trying to put our PCjrs in a pile and burn them. And the damned things don't burn. That's the only thing IBM did right with the machine\u2014they made it flame-proof.|William H. Bowman, Chairman of PCjr software company [[Spinnaker Software|Spinnaker]], March 1985<ref name=\"bowman19850611\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZFw924nLBSoC&lpg=PA86&pg=PA59#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Burn Baby Burn, Says PCjr Software Maker | work=PC Magazine | date=1985-06-11 | accessdate=28 October 2013 | pages=59}}</ref>}}\n\nBy January 1985 experts estimated that IBM had sold 240-275,000 PCjrs, including 200,000 in the fourth quarter of 1984. When the discounts ended, however, sales decreased to 2.4 units in February{{r|kennedy19850514}}<ref name=\"pollack19850320\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/20/business/ibm-drops-pcjr-production.html | title=I.B.M. Drops PCjr Production | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | author=Pollack, Andrew | date=March 20, 1985 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{r|time19850401}}\u2014compared to 4.0 units in February 1984{{r|bulman19841105}}\u2014with large unsold inventories.{{r|ap19850321}} By this time three PCjr-specific magazines had ended publication;{{r|bartimo19841210}} [[ABC Publishing]] reportedly lost $100,000 or more on its magazine.<ref name=\"tuller19861116\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/16/business/abc-s-axe-wielding-publisher-robert-g-burton-championing-print-in-a-tv-world.html?pagewanted=all |title=ABC'S AXE-WIELDING PUBLISHER: ROBERT G. BURTON; Championing Print in a TV World |last=Tuller |first=David |date=November 16, 1986 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> IBM was unable to meet the demand for its new [[PC AT]] business microcomputer, but the home-computer market was in decline{{r|sanger19850118}}{{r|time19850401}} and the company was likely unable to make a sufficient profit when selling the PCjr at a discount.{{r|pollack19850120}}{{r|pollack19850320}}{{r|ap19850321}}{{r|time19850401}}\n\nIBM discontinued the PCjr on March 19, 1985, stating that \"The home market didn't expand to the degree I.B.M. and many observers thought it would\". The surprise decision{{r|pollack19850320}}<ref name=\"time19850401\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,964850,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625185216/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C964850%2C00.html |archive-date=June 25, 2009 |title=Kicking Junior Out of the Family |access-date=February 23, 2011 |author1=Castro, Janice |author2=Bob Buderi |author3=Thomas McCarroll |date=April 1, 1985 |work=Time |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> by CEO [[John Akers]] himself{{r|sanger19850707}} astounded Sierra and others, some of which only made PCjr products.{{r|kennedy19850514}} Rumored to have 100,000 to 400,000 unsold PCjrs{{r|kennedy19850514}}<ref name=\"steele19850709\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SprPDrQRvM8C&lpg=PA51&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=COMDEX: Nothing New Under the Georgia Sun | work=PC Magazine | date=July 9, 1985 | accessdate=October 28, 2013 | author=Steele, William | pages=34}}</ref>{{r|mintzer19860114}} despite not having ordered new microprocessors from Intel since summer 1984,<ref name=\"iw19850415\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zC4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA13&ots=a_Fs_n1Np8&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Death of the PCjr: Insiders Foresaw It | work=InfoWorld | date=April 15, 1985 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | pages=13 | editor=McCarthy, Michael}}</ref> the company offered large discounts to its employees<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/09/19/business/ibm-offers-a-pcjr-deal.html | title=I.B.M. Offers a PCjr Deal | accessdate=February 25, 2011 | date=September 19, 1985 | work=The New York Times}}</ref> and consumers. Inventory remained through Christmas 1985, and IBM used discounts and radio and full-page print ads for the computer;<ref name=\"mintzer19860114\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hoPbDSDNLTQC&lpg=PA75&pg=PA75#v=onepage&f=false | title=News in Brief | work=PC | date=January 14, 1986 | accessdate=January 21, 2015 | pages=38 | editor=Mintzer, Jane}}</ref> one industry executive stated that \"only the unaware purchaser would be liable to pick that thing up\".<ref name=\"mace19851202\">{{cite news|last=Mace|first=Scott|title=Christmas Contenders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=My8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA28&dq=mecc&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q=mecc&f=false|accessdate=January 22, 2011|newspaper=InfoWorld|date=December 2, 1985}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{rquote|right|It will never happen again.|IBM engineer, 1985{{r|strehlo19850617}}}}\n\nThe press widely covered the first public failure of the world's most profitable company.{{r|sanger19850707}} Although PCjr had little effect on its $46 billion in 1984 revenue, discontinuing such a prominent product embarrassed IBM.{{r|ap19850321}} The failure was so great that the ''Chicago Tribune'' later compared PCjr to that of the Edsel and [[New Coke]],<ref name=\"lynch19901026\">{{cite news | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-26/entertainment/9003300627_1_ibm-ps-prodigy-software-microsoft-works | title=The Pros, Cons Of Buying An IBM PS/1 | work=Chicago Tribune | date=October 26, 1990 | accessdate=February 4, 2015 | author=Lynch, Dennis}}</ref> and IBM reportedly created a '''Chiclet rule''', requiring [[human factors]] testing for future products.<ref name=\"strehlo19850617\">{{cite news\n | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FS8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA8&pg=PA8#v=onepage&f=false\n | title=The Chiclet Rule and the Green Dragon\n | work=InfoWorld\n | date=June 17, 1985\n | accessdate=May 31, 2016\n | author=Strehlo, Kevin\n | quote=\"\n | page=8}}</ref>\n\nSome observers believed that IBM's bureaucratic culture, so different from that of the less-rigid Boca Raton division that created the PC, had caused PCjr to fail; others thought that the absence of IBM's cautious and thorough bureaucrats had caused the failure. Estridge said \"It turned out that we had it all wrong\" by expecting that first-time computer users would buy PCjr.{{r|sanger19850707}} Spinnaker's Bowman said \"IBM didn't talk to anybody when they designed this product. They tried to enter a market segment without knowing anything about the customers\".{{r|ap19850321}} Even PCjr's end surprised the company. When it announced the discontinuation IBM promised to continue to support the computer, as it did with mainframes. The press criticized the company, however, for orphaning the product. Executives admitted that the reaction was another example of IBM not understanding the consumer market.{{r|sanger19850707}}\n\n[[Sell-side analyst]] Barbara Isgur correctly predicted in 1984 that the PCjr \"will probably establish the standard operating system for the home market as it has in business. So even if the PCjrs have gone into the closet, I think that as the software continues to evolve and increase, they will be brought out\".<ref name=\"uston198403\">{{cite news | url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v10n3/18_Barbara_Isgur_talks_to_Ke.php | title=Barbara Isgur talks to Ken Uston; an industry analyst speaks out. | work=Creative Computing | date=Mar 1984 | accessdate=January 5, 2015 | author=Uston, Ken | pages=18}}</ref>{{r|loguidice2014}} [[Tandy Corporation]] released a clone, the [[Tandy 1000]], in November 1984,<ref name=\"infoworld19850121\">{{cite magazine | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9y4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=%22tandy+1000%22&hl=en&ei=bTdrTeuLIITmsQPlx8SmBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=48&ved=0COwBEOgBMC84ZA#v=onepage&q=%22tandy%201000%22&f=false | title=BRIEFS | accessdate=February 27, 2011 | date=February 12, 1985 | magazine=InfoWorld | pages=23}}</ref> describing it as \"what the PCjr should have been\".<ref name=\"bartimo19850311\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5C4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA28&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Tandy Revamps Product Line | work=InfoWorld | date=March 11, 1985 | accessdate=January 21, 2015 | author=Bartimo, Jim | pages=28\u201329}}</ref> After its discontinuation Tandy quickly removed any mention of the PCjr in advertising while emphasizing the {{Not a typo|1000's}} PC compatibility. The machine and its many successors sold well, unlike the PCjr, partly because the Tandy 1000 was sold in ubiquitous [[Radio Shack]] stores and partly because it was less costly, easier to expand, and almost entirely compatible with the IBM PC. The PCjr's enhanced graphics and sound standards became known as \"[[Tandy Graphics Adapter|Tandy-compatible]]\", and many PC games advertised their Tandy support. A company developed a PCjr modification that made it compatible with Tandy software.<ref name=\"loguidice2014\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=wZnpAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA97&pg=PA96#v=onepage&f=false | title=Vintage Game Consoles: An Inside Look at Apple, Atari, Commodore, Nintendo, and the Greatest Gaming Platforms of All Time | publisher=CRC Press |author1=Loguidice, Bill |author2=Barton, Matt | year=2014 | pages=95\u201397 | isbn=978-1135006518}}</ref>\n\n\"[The PCjr] was a nice enough machine, a little underpowered for its price, but not fatally flawed. Its cardinal sin\", ''PC Magazine'' concluded in late 1985, \"was that it wasn't PC compatible\".<ref name=\"machrone19851126\">{{cite magazine | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VUKL2rKYb8UC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA59#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Compatibility Wars\u2014Here and Abroad |magazine=PC Magazine | date=November 26, 1985 | accessdate=October 29, 2013 | author=Machrone, Bill |page=59}}</ref> From mid-1985, what ''Compute!'' described as a \"wave\" of inexpensive clones from American and Asian companies caused prices to decline; by the end of 1986, the equivalent to a US$1,600 real IBM PC with 256&nbsp;KB RAM and two disk drives cost as little as $600, lower than the price of the Apple IIc. Consumers began purchasing DOS computers for the home in large numbers; Radio Shack estimated that half of Tandy 1000 sales went to homes, not offices. The inexpensive clones succeeded with consumers where the PCjr had failed; unlike the IBM product, they were as fast as or faster than the IBM PC and highly compatible.<ref name=\"halfhill198612\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1986-12-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_079_1986_Dec#page/n33/mode/2up | title=The MS-DOS Invasion / IBM Compatibles Are Coming Home | work=Compute! | date=December 1986 | accessdate=November 9, 2013 | author=Halfhill, Tom R. | pages=32}}</ref>\n\nSeveral upgrades for the PCjr were designed by IBM/Teledyne but never reached the store shelves before the IBM PCjr was canceled. These included a wireless joystick and various memory/drive upgrades. PC Enterprises became the last of the major third party vendors to supply full service, parts, and add-ons, extending the functional life of the PCjr to about 10 years, often buying out inventory and rights for PCjr support.\n\nOther manufacturers provided support items for PCjr fans, such as hard drive attachments and specialized sidecars that the user could use to enhance the system. The PCjr was able to run other software designed for the PC, such as word processor, database and spreadsheet programs ran well on the PCjr with 128K of memory. When fully expanded to over 600K memory, the PCjr would run all IBM PC software.<ref>http://oldcomputers.net/ibm-pcjr.html see the comments.</ref>\n\n\nIBM returned to the home market in 1990 with the [[IBM PS/1|PS/1]]. Unlike the PCjr, the PS/1 offered full PC compatibility, a low price, and a conventional keyboard.{{r|lynch19901026}}\n\n==Technical specifications==\n* '''CPU:''' [[Intel 8088]], 4.77&nbsp;MHz\n* '''Memory:''' 64&nbsp;KB on the motherboard, expandable to 128&nbsp;KB via a card in a dedicated slot. Further expansion via IBM sidecar adapters. Later third-party add-ons and modifications raised the limit to 736&nbsp;KB.\n* '''Operating system:''' IBM [[PC DOS]] 2.10 (Boots to Cassette BASIC without cartridge or DOS){{r|levy198501}}\n* '''Input/Output:''' cassette port, light-pen port, two joystick ports, [[RGB color model|RGB]] monitor port, composite video port, television adapter output port, audio port, wired keyboard port, infrared keyboard sensor, serial port, two cartridge slots\n* '''Expandability:''' three internal slots, dedicated to PCjr-specific memory, [[modem]] (300 [[bits per second]] non-[[Hayes command set|Hayes]]-compatible modem available from IBM, although 2400&nbsp;bit/s Hayes-compatible modems were available from third parties), and floppy controller cards. External sidecar connector capable of daisy-chaining multiple sidecars.\n* '''Video:''' [[Motorola]] [[Motorola 6845|6845]], \"[[Color Graphics Adapter|CGA]] Plus\" This chip was officially called the VGA (Video Gate Array<ref name=\"vga\" />).\n** Text modes: 40&times;25, 80&times;25, 16 colors\n** Graphics modes: 320&times;200&times;4, 640&times;200&times;2, 160&times;100&times;16, 160&times;200&times;16, 320&times;200&times;16, 640&times;200&times;4{{r|halfhill198401}} \n** Video memory is shared with the first 128&nbsp;KB of system memory, and can be as small as 2&nbsp;KB and as large as 96&nbsp;KB.\n* '''Sound:''' [[Texas Instruments SN76489|Texas Instruments SN76496]]; three voices, 16 independent volume levels per channel, white noise\n* '''Storage:''' Optional 5.25-inch diskette drive or cassette.  Other storage options were provided by third parties.\n* '''Keyboard:''' 62-key detached.  Corded or infra-red operation.  IBM supplied two different keyboards, the first being the maligned 'Chiclet' keyboard, so named for its square rubber keys that resembled [[Chiclets]].  Many third-party keyboards were also available.\n\n==See also==\n* [[IBM JX]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://weblog.ceicher.com/archives/2002/12/christmas_1984_the_great_apple.html Christmas 1984: The Great Apple //c vs. PCjr Battle]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UrR7asU4aLE IBM PCjr running internal test and printing]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[IBM Personal Computer]] }}\n{{s-ttl|title  = IBM Personal Computers }}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[IBM PS/1]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:8086-based home computers]]\n[[Category:Home computers]]\n[[Category:IBM personal computers|PCjr]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 1984]]\n", "name_user": "Ylee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKeyboard:cite reuse", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM_PCjr"}
{"title_page": "New Standard Encyclopedia (1910)", "text_new": "{{about|the encyclopedia founded in 1910 as ''Aiton's Encyclopedia'' |the one founded in 1906|New Standard Encyclopedia (1906)}}\nThe '''''New Standard Encyclopedia''''' was the most common name for an encyclopedia that ran from 1910 to the mid-1960s.\n\nThe set began on the initiative of [[George Aiton|George Briggs Aiton]], a [[Inspector of schools|Inspector of Schools]] in [[Minnesota]], who felt that he could use experience and contact with children to create a home and school encyclopedia. This edition, ''Aiton's Encyclopedia'', in 5 volumes, was published by the [[Minneapolis]] based [[Welles Brothers and Company]] would be the only one that Aiton was involve in or carry his name.<ref>S. Padraig Walsh ''Anglo-American General Encyclopedias 1704-1967'' New York: R. R. Baker and Company, 1968 p.2</ref>  \n\nThe set appeared under the name ''Standard Reference Work'' in 1912 in 6 volumes, published under the imprint of the [[Interstate Publishing Company]] of Chicago. It was reprinted again the next year by Welles Brothers and Company. It was issued again in 1915 and 1917, when it was enlarged to 7 volumes, the last being a reading and study guide). In 1922 it was published in 10 volumes, the last two being a study guide. This was published under the imprint of the [[Standard Education Society]]. It was this edition that brought the attention of the [[Federal Trade Commission]] who issued a Cease and Desist Order for misrepresentation in 1923 (Docket #994).<ref>Walsh p.159</ref> As a result, in 1923 the set was reprinted as the ''National Encyclopedia for the Home, School and Library'' in 10 volumes under the [[National Encyclopedia Company]] imprint. It is unclear whether this was meant to be permanent, but the set reverted to the old name one last time for an edition in 1927.<ref>Walsh p.159</ref>\n\nFrom 1930 to at least the 1960s it was published under the title ''New Standard Encyclopedia'' under the [[Standard Encyclopaedia Company]] imprint. Ovrtime its quality improved from poor to fair, as one bibliographer put it.<ref>Walsh pp.127, 159</ref>\n\nIn 1939 there was also an edition for Canadian and Commonwealth readers published as the ''Consolidated Encyclopedia''.<ref>Walsh p.35</ref>\n\nIn 1983 the encyclopedia was expanded from 14 to 17 volumes. Under the direction of [[Douglas Downey]], the ''New Standard'' was considered a \"solid respectable set\" for older students and family, though its lack of an index, inadequate coverage of controversial subjects, overly concise tone and poor, black and white illustrations.<ref>Kennth F. Kister ''Best Encyclopedias'' Phoenix, AZ; Orynx Press, 1986 pp.161, 163-4</ref> However, one of the sets strengths was its up-to-dateness, the 1985 edition including new or updated articles on such subjects as [[AIDS]], [[compact disc players]], [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]], [[Geraldine Ferraro]], [[Milton Friedman]], [[options trading]], and the [[space shuttle]]. When discussing controversial topics such as the [[death penalty]], the encyclopedia tried to given an impartial overview of differing views, however with other subjects like [[abortion]] or [[Scientology]] the encyclopedia did not mention any of the controversies surrounding them.<ref>Kister 1986 pp.161-2</ref> This edition had 10,000 pages, 17,500 articles and 6.5 million words. The articles were of the specific entry type, averaging 375 words or more than half a page. None of the articles were signed, but 90 editors were listed at the beginning of Volume 1, together with a larger staff of 700 contributors, consultants, advisors and authentication. There were 12,000 illustrations, 5,000 in color and 650 maps. In lieu of an index, there were 53,000 cross-references.<ref>Kister 1986 p.160</ref>\n\nIn 1989 the encyclopedia expanded to 20 volumes and added an index. This helped improve the sets standing, however it was still considered second rate compared to ''[[Compton's Encyclopedia]]'' or ''[[World Book Encyclopedia]]''<ref>Kennth F. Kister ''Best Encyclopedias'' 2nd ed. Phoenix, AZ; Orynx Press, 1994 pp.83, 86-7</ref> The 1993 set had 8 million words, 10,750 pages, 17,500 articles and 1,000 bibliographies. There were 13,000 maps an illustrations, 53,600 cross references and 100,000 index entries. Downey staff numbered 80, but there were 800 contributors in all. The sets reputation for factual accuracy was partly due to the authenticator system, in which each article was reviewed by five different.<ref>Kister 1994 pp.82-4</ref> The set was kept rigorously up-to-date with 2,000 articles out of 17,000 revised in some way each year. There was also an updating supplement ''World Progress: The Standard Quarterly Review'' published four times a year. Still the set was criticized for superficial treatment of controversial issues including abortion, adoption, [[race and intelligence]] and alcoholism. And even with its strong revision system did not mention things such as Galileos's pardon by the Catholic Church, controversies regarding the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]] or then recent (1993) [[US Supreme Court cases]] regarding abortion.<ref>Kister 1994 pp.84-5</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{italic title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:English-language encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:20th-century encyclopedias]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the encyclopedia founded in 1910 as ''Aiton's Encyclopedia'' |the one founded in 1906|New Standard Encyclopedia (1906)}}\nThe '''''New Standard Encyclopedia''''' was the most common name for an encyclopedia that ran from 1910 to the mid-1960s.\n\nThe set began on the initiative of [[George Aiton|George Briggs Aiton]], a [[Inspector of schools|Inspector of Schools]] in [[Minnesota]], who felt that he could use experience and contact with children to create a home and school encyclopedia. This edition, ''Aiton's Encyclopedia'', in 5 volumes, was published by the [