{"title_page": "F. W. Pomeroy", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:Justice (3643291515).jpg|thumb|Pomeroy's statue of ''[[Lady Justice|Justice]]'' (1905\u20131906) at the [[Old Bailey]]]]\n'''Frederick William Pomeroy''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Royal Academy|RA]]}} (London 1857/58{{cn|date=February 2019}} &ndash; 26 May 1924) was a prolific British sculptor of architectural and monumental works. He was one of the so-called [[New Sculpture|New Sculptors]] identified by [[Edmund Gosse]] in 1894 \u2013 a group distinguished by a stylistic turn towards [[Naturalism (arts)|naturalism]] and their work in [[architectural sculpture]].\n\n==Early life and training==\n[[File:Belfast city hall.jpg|thumb|[[Belfast City Hall]]]]\nPomeroy was born in London, the son of an artist-craftsman. He trained with [[William Silver Frith]] at the [[South London Technical School of Art]] (formerly [[Lambeth School of Art]] and now the [[City and Guilds of London Art School]]<ref>[http://www.cityandguildsartschool.ac.uk/ City and Guilds of London Art School]</ref>), where he was also taught by [[Jules Dalou]]. In 1880, he was able to enter the [[Royal Academy Schools]], where he won a travelling scholarship; which took him to Paris (where he studied under [[Antonin Merci\u00e9]]) and Italy. He was elected [[Associate of the Royal Academy|ARA]] in 1906, and [[Royal Academy|RA]] in 1917.\n\n==Action in London==\nOn returning to London Pomeroy carved [[Frederic Leighton]]'s marble group, ''[[Athlete wrestling with a python]]'' (private collection). In 1887 he joined the [[Art Workers Guild]], and from 1888 he exhibited with the [[Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society]] (in 1907 he became master of the Art Workers Guild). He became a leading sculptor in the New Sculpture movement, both in London and elsewhere in Britain. His work in London includes the figure of [[Lady Justice|Justice]] (1905\u20131906) on the dome of the [[Old Bailey]] (the Central Criminal Court)<ref>{{cite web |title=Justice - Frederick William Pomeroy |url=http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/pomeroy/25.html |website=Victorian Web |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> and the statue of [[W. E. Gladstone]] in the [[Houses of Parliament]].\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:A memorial to F. W. Pomeroy in St James's Church, Piccadilly.jpg|thumb|Memorial in [[St James's Church, Piccadilly]]]]\nIn 1913 Pomeroy married Patricia Morrison Coughlan, of [[Douglas, County Cork|Douglas]], County Cork. With her he had two sons.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename= A Noted English Sculptor. Mr. F. W. Pomeroy, R.A. |section= Obituaries |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=27 May 1924 |page_number=21 |column=E }}</ref>\n\nIn May 1924 Pomeroy offered a prize \"for the most perfect pair of feet\"; the actress [[Daisy Burrell]] and the dancer Margery Prince tied for the first prize of \u00a350.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Miami News]] |title=. |date=29 May 1924 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2206&dat=19240529&id=8G0uAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h9gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2578,5325222 |page=9}} column 2{{dl|date=February 2019}}</ref> Pomeroy died on 26 May 1924,<ref>{{cite book |chapter=POMEROY, F. W., RA 1917 (ARA 1906) |title=Who Was Who 1916\u20131928 |place=London |publisher=[[A & C Black]] |year=1992 |isbn=0-7136-3143-0|title-link=Who's Who (UK) }} \"died 26 May 1924\"</ref> aged 65, and was buried at [[Boscombe]] in Hampshire. A memorial to him lies in [[St James's Church, Piccadilly]].\n\n==Works==\nPomeroy's largest outdoor works are the four enormous bronze figures on the upstream side of [[Vauxhall Bridge]] in London. Dating from 1907, they represent: ''Pottery'', ''Engineering'', ''Architecture'' and ''Agriculture''. Pomeroy's other architectural sculpture includes:\n* [[Sheffield Town Hall]]\n* the figures of ''Truth'', ''Fortitude'' and the ''Recording Angel'' at the [[Old Bailey]], London\n* [[City Hall, Cardiff]]\n* [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] Town Hall\n* the pediment of [[Belfast City Hall]]\n* [[Holy Trinity Sloane Street|Holy Trinity Church]], Sloane Street, London\n* extensive work at [[Liverpool John Moores University]]\n\nSmaller works include:\n* ''The Spearman'' bronze statue<ref>[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], ed. 1911, vol. 24, pg. 505, Plate IV.</ref>\n* statue of [[Queen Victoria]] in [[Woolwich Town Hall]]\n* [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|bronze statue of Oliver Cromwell]] in [[St Ives, Cambridgeshire|St Ives, Huntingdonshire]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1968 |title=Bedfordshire and the County of Huntingdon and Peterborough |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |place=Harmondsworth |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |isbn=0-14-0710-34-5 |page=338}}</ref>\n* statue of the [[Frederick Stanley, 16th Earl of Derby|16th Earl of Derby]] in the Concert Hall of [[St George's Hall, Liverpool]]<ref>Sharples, Joseph; Pollard, Richard. Liverpool F.C.. In {{cite book |last1=Pollard |first1=Richard |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=2006 |title=Lancashire: Liverpool and the South-West |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |edition= |place=New Haven and London |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=0-300-10910-5 |page=296}}</ref>\n* statue of the Reverend Dr [[Thomas Guthrie]] DD in [[West Princes Street Gardens]], [[Edinburgh]]\n* marble [[reredos]] at St Saviour's Church, [[Colgate, West Sussex]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Elleray |first=D Robert |year=2004 |title=Sussex Places of Worship |place=Worthing |publisher=Optimus Books |isbn=0-9533132-7-1|page=17}}</ref>\n* statue of [[George Livesey]] of the Metropolitan Gas Works 1909, [[Peckham]], [[London Borough of Southwark]]\n* [[Robert Burns]] statue at [[Fountain Gardens, Paisley]] In 1921 a copy of this statue was unveiled in Auckland, New Zealand. The bronze casting was carried out by Ercole James Parlanti of London.<ref>New Zealand Herald 5th May 1921 \n</ref>\n* statue of [[Robert Blake (admiral)|Robert Blake]] in [[Bridgwater]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery style=\"text-align: center\">\nFile:Pomeroy Pottery.JPG|''Pottery'' on [[Vauxhall Bridge]]\nFile:Statue of Oliver Cromwell - geograph.org.uk - 310979.jpg|Pomeroy's [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|statue of Oliver Cromwell]] in [[St Ives, Cambridgeshire|St Ives, Huntingdonshire]]\nFile:Boer War memorial, Guildhall, London.jpg|[[Boer War]] memorial, [[Guildhall]], [[London]]\nFile:Hywel Dda at Cardiff City Hall.jpg|Sculpture of [[Hywel Dda]], [[City Hall, Cardiff|City Hall]], [[Cardiff]]\nFile:Sir Clements Robert Markham Bust.jpg|Bust of Sir [[Clements Robert Markham]]\nFile:Frederick William Pomeroy - The Lily of Killarney.jpg|''The Lily of Killarney''\nFile:EB1911 Plate IV. v24, pg.505, Fig 1.jpg|''The Spearman'' bronze statue\nFile:F. W. Pomeroy (1857-1924) - The Wood Nymph (1908) front part right, Lady Lever Art Gallery, Port Sunlight, Cheshire, June 2013 (9097771208).png|The Wood Nymph (1908), Lady Lever Art Gallery, Port Sunlight, Cheshire\nFile:Bishop Ridding - geograph.org.uk - 1428652.jpg|Bishop Ridding Memorial to [[George Ridding]] in the choir of [[Southwell Minster]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Frederick William Pomeroy}}\n* [http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/speel/sculpt/pomeroy.htm Online description of Pomeroy's work]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/65986072@N00/866428101/ Perseus with the Head of Medusa \u2013 bronze statuette in V&A] Photo by ketrin1407 on [[Flickr]]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/65986072@N00/5131983078/ The Nymph of Loch Awe] Photo by ketrin1407 on Flickr \u2013 one of a set taken at [[Tate Britain]]'s [[New Sculpture]] exhibition in August \u2013 September 2010\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pomeroy, Frederick}}\n\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:British male sculptors]]\n[[Category:20th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:British architectural sculptors]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from London]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the City and Guilds of London Art School]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:Justice (3643291515).jpg|thumb|Pomeroy's statue of ''[[Lady Justice|Justice]]'' (1905\u20131906) at the [[Old Bailey]]]]\n'''Frederick William Pomeroy''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Royal Academy|RA]]}} (London 1857/58{{cn|date=February 2019}} &ndash; 26 May 1924) was a prolific British sculptor of architectural and monumental works. He was one of the so-called [[New Sculpture|New Sculptors]] identified by [[Edmund Gosse]] in 1894 \u2013 a group distinguished by a stylistic turn towards [[Naturalism (arts)|naturalism]] and their work in [[architectural sculpture]].\n\n==Early life and training==\n[[File:Belfast city hall.jpg|thumb|[[Belfast City Hall]]]]\nPomeroy was born in London, the son of an artist-craftsman. He trained with [[William Silver Frith]] at the [[South London Technical School of Art]] (formerly [[Lambeth School of Art]] and now the [[City and Guilds of London Art School]]<ref>[http://www.cityandguildsartschool.ac.uk/ City and Guilds of London Art School]</ref>), where he was also taught by [[Jules Dalou]]. In 1880, he was able to enter the [[Royal Academy Schools]], where he won a travelling scholarship; which took him to Paris (where he studied under [[Antonin Merci\u00e9]]) and Italy. He was elected [[Associate of the Royal Academy|ARA]] in 1906, and [[Royal Academy|RA]] in 1917.\n\n==Action in London==\nOn returning to London Pomeroy carved [[Frederic Leighton]]'s marble group, ''[[Athlete wrestling with a python]]'' (private collection). In 1887 he joined the [[Art Workers Guild]], and from 1888 he exhibited with the [[Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society]] (in 1907 he became master of the Art Workers Guild). He became a leading sculptor in the New Sculpture movement, both in London and elsewhere in Britain. His work in London includes the figure of [[Lady Justice|Justice]] (1905\u20131906) on the dome of the [[Old Bailey]] (the Central Criminal Court)<ref>{{cite web |title=Justice - Frederick William Pomeroy |url=http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/pomeroy/25.html |website=Victorian Web |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> and the statue of [[W. E. Gladstone]] in the [[Houses of Parliament]].\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:A memorial to F. W. Pomeroy in St James's Church, Piccadilly.jpg|thumb|Memorial in [[St James's Church, Piccadilly]]]]\nIn 1913 Pomeroy married Patricia Morrison Coughlan, of [[Douglas, County Cork|Douglas]], County Cork. With her he had two sons.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename= A Noted English Sculptor. Mr. F. W. Pomeroy, R.A. |section= Obituaries |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=27 May 1924 |page_number=21 |column=E }}</ref>\n\nIn May 1924 Pomeroy offered a prize \"for the most perfect pair of feet\"; the actress [[Daisy Burrell]] and the dancer Margery Prince tied for the first prize of \u00a350.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Miami News]] |title=. |date=29 May 1924 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2206&dat=19240529&id=8G0uAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h9gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2578,5325222 |page=9}} column 2{{dl|date=February 2019}}</ref> Pomeroy died on 26 May 1924,<ref>{{cite book |chapter=POMEROY, F. W., RA 1917 (ARA 1906) |title=Who Was Who 1916\u20131928 |place=London |publisher=[[A & C Black]] |year=1992 |isbn=0-7136-3143-0|title-link=Who's Who (UK) }} \"died 26 May 1924\"</ref> aged 65, and was buried at [[Boscombe]] in Hampshire. A memorial to him lies in [[St James's Church, Piccadilly]].\n\n==Works==\nPomeroy's largest outdoor works are the four enormous bronze figures on the upstream side of [[Vauxhall Bridge]] in London. Dating from 1907, they represent: ''Pottery'', ''Engineering'', ''Architecture'' and ''Agriculture''. Pomeroy's other architectural sculpture includes:\n* [[Sheffield Town Hall]]\n* the figures of ''Truth'', ''Fortitude'' and the ''Recording Angel'' at the [[Old Bailey]], London\n* [[City Hall, Cardiff]]\n* [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] Town Hall\n* the pediment of [[Belfast City Hall]]\n* [[Holy Trinity Sloane Street|Holy Trinity Church]], Sloane Street, London\n* extensive work at [[Liverpool John Moores University]]\n\nSmaller works include:\n* ''The Spearman'' bronze statue<ref>[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], ed. 1911, vol. 24, pg. 505, Plate IV.</ref>\n* statue of [[Queen Victoria]] in [[Woolwich Town Hall]]\n* [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|bronze statue of Oliver Cromwell]] in [[St Ives, Cambridgeshire|St Ives, Huntingdonshire]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1968 |title=Bedfordshire and the County of Huntingdon and Peterborough |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |place=Harmondsworth |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |isbn=0-14-0710-34-5 |page=338}}</ref>\n* statue of the [[Frederick Stanley, 16th Earl of Derby|16th Earl of Derby]] in the Concert Hall of [[St George's Hall, Liverpool]]<ref>Sharples, Joseph; Pollard, Richard. Liverpool F.C.. In {{cite book |last1=Pollard |first1=Richard |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=2006 |title=Lancashire: Liverpool and the South-West |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |edition= |place=New Haven and London |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=0-300-10910-5 |page=296}}</ref>\n* statue of the Reverend Dr [[Thomas Guthrie]] DD in [[West Princes Street Gardens]], [[Edinburgh]]\n* marble [[reredos]] at St Saviour's Church, [[Colgate, West Sussex]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Elleray |first=D Robert |year=2004 |title=Sussex Places of Worship |place=Worthing |publisher=Optimus Books |isbn=0-9533132-7-1|page=17}}</ref>\n* statue of [[George Livesey]] of the Metropolitan Gas Works 1909, [[Peckham]], [[London Borough of Southwark]]\n* [[Robert Burns]] statue at [[Fountain Gardens, Paisley]]\n* statue of [[Robert Blake (admiral)|Robert Blake]] in [[Bridgwater]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery style=\"text-align: center\">\nFile:Pomeroy Pottery.JPG|''Pottery'' on [[Vauxhall Bridge]]\nFile:Statue of Oliver Cromwell - geograph.org.uk - 310979.jpg|Pomeroy's [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|statue of Oliver Cromwell]] in [[St Ives, Cambridgeshire|St Ives, Huntingdonshire]]\nFile:Boer War memorial, Guildhall, London.jpg|[[Boer War]] memorial, [[Guildhall]], [[London]]\nFile:Hywel Dda at Cardiff City Hall.jpg|Sculpture of [[Hywel Dda]], [[City Hall, Cardiff|City Hall]], [[Cardiff]]\nFile:Sir Clements Robert Markham Bust.jpg|Bust of Sir [[Clements Robert Markham]]\nFile:Frederick William Pomeroy - The Lily of Killarney.jpg|''The Lily of Killarney''\nFile:EB1911 Plate IV. v24, pg.505, Fig 1.jpg|''The Spearman'' bronze statue\nFile:F. W. Pomeroy (1857-1924) - The Wood Nymph (1908) front part right, Lady Lever Art Gallery, Port Sunlight, Cheshire, June 2013 (9097771208).png|The Wood Nymph (1908), Lady Lever Art Gallery, Port Sunlight, Cheshire\nFile:Bishop Ridding - geograph.org.uk - 1428652.jpg|Bishop Ridding Memorial to [[George Ridding]] in the choir of [[Southwell Minster]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Frederick William Pomeroy}}\n* [http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/speel/sculpt/pomeroy.htm Online description of Pomeroy's work]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/65986072@N00/866428101/ Perseus with the Head of Medusa \u2013 bronze statuette in V&A] Photo by ketrin1407 on [[Flickr]]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/65986072@N00/5131983078/ The Nymph of Loch Awe] Photo by ketrin1407 on Flickr \u2013 one of a set taken at [[Tate Britain]]'s [[New Sculpture]] exhibition in August \u2013 September 2010\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULT